AG.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
AG.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

AG.AGSEQ.label: Sequence Number
AG.AGSEQ.description: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

AG.AGGRPID.label: Group ID
AG.AGGRPID.description: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

AG.AGSPID.label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
AG.AGSPID.description: Sponsor-defined reference number. May be preprinted on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: Line number from the procedure or test page.

AG.AGLNKID.label: Link ID
AG.AGLNKID.description: Identifier used to link related records across domains.This may be a one-to-one or a one-to-many relationship.

AG.AGLNKGRP.label: Link Group ID
AG.AGLNKGRP.description: Identifier used to link related records across domains.This will usually be a many-to-one relationship.

AG.AGTRT.label: Reported Agent Name
AG.AGTRT.description: Verbatim medication name that is either preprinted or collected on a CRF.

AG.AGMODIFY.label: Modified Reported Name
AG.AGMODIFY.description: If AGTRT is modified to facilitate coding, then AGMODIFY will contain the modified text.

AG.AGDECOD.label: Standardized Agent Name
AG.AGDECOD.description: Standardized or dictionary-derived text description of AGTRT or AGMODIFY. Equivalent to the generic medication name in WHO Drug. The sponsor is expected to provide the dictionary name and version used to map the terms utilizing the external codelist element in the Define-XML document. If an intervention term does not have a decode value in the dictionary, then AGDECOD will be left blank.

AG.AGCAT.label: Category for Agent
AG.AGCAT.description: Used to define a category of agent. Examples: "CHALLENGE AGENT", "PET TRACER".

AG.AGPRESP.label: AG Pre-Specified
AG.AGPRESP.description: Used to indicate whether ("Y"/null) information about the use of a specific agent was solicited on the CRF.

AG.AGOCCUR.label: AG Occurrence
AG.AGOCCUR.description: When the use of specific agent is solicited, AGOCCUR is used to indicate whether ("Y"/"N") use of the agent occurred. Values are null for agents not specifically solicited.

AG.AGSTAT.label: Completion Status
AG.AGSTAT.description: Used to indicate that a question about a prespecified agent was not answered. Should be null or have a value of "NOT DONE".

AG.AGREASND.label: Reason Procedure Agent Not Collected
AG.AGREASND.description: Describes the reason a response to a question about the occurrence of a procedure agent was not collected. Used in conjunction with AGSTAT when value is "NOT DONE".

AG.AGCLAS.label: Agent Class
AG.AGCLAS.description: Drug class. May be obtained from coding. When coding to a single class, populate with class value. If using a dictionary and coding to multiple classes, follow guidance in Section 4.2.8.3, Multiple Values for a Non-result Qualifier Variable, or omit AGCLAS.

AG.AGCLASCD.label: Agent Class Code
AG.AGCLASCD.description: Class code corresponding to AGCLAS. Drug class. May be obtained from coding. When coding to a single class, populate with class code. If using a dictionary and coding to multiple classes, follow guidance in Section 4.2.8.3, Multiple Values for a Non-result Qualifier Variable, or omit AGCLASCD.

AG.AGDOSTXT.label: Dose Description
AG.AGDOSTXT.description: Dosing amounts or a range of dosing information collected in text form. Units may be stored in AGDOSU. Examples: "200-400", "15-20".

AG.AGDOSU.label: Dose Units
AG.AGDOSU.description: Units for AGDOSE and AGDOSTXT. Examples: "ng", "mg", "mg/kg".

AG.AGDOSFRQ.label: Dosing Frequency per Interval
AG.AGDOSFRQ.description: Usually expressed as the number of repeated administrations of AGDOSE within a specific time period. Example: "ONCE".

AG.AGROUTE.label: Route of Administration
AG.AGROUTE.description: Route of administration for AGTRT. Example: "ORAL".

AG.VISITNUM.label: Visit Number
AG.VISITNUM.description: 1. Clinical encounter number. \n 2. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

AG.VISIT.label: Visit Name
AG.VISIT.description: 1. Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter. \n 2. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY.

AG.VISITDY.label: Planned Study Day of Visit
AG.VISITDY.description: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

AG.TAETORD.label: Planned Order of Element within Arm
AG.TAETORD.description: Number that gives the planned order of the element within the arm for the element in which the agent administration started.

AG.EPOCH.label: Epoch
AG.EPOCH.description: Epoch associated with the start date/time of the agent administration started.

AG.AGSTDTC.label: Start Date/Time of Agent
AG.AGSTDTC.description: The date/time when administration of the treatment indicated by AGTRT and the dosing variables began.

AG.AGENDTC.label: End Date/Time of Agent
AG.AGENDTC.description: The date/time when administration of the treatment indicated by AGTRT and the dosing variables ended.

AG.AGSTDY.label: Study Day of Start of Agent
AG.AGSTDY.description: Study day of start of agent relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.

AG.AGENDY.label: Study Day of End of Agent
AG.AGENDY.description: Study day of end of agent relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.

AG.AGDUR.label: Duration of Agent
AG.AGDUR.description: Collected duration for an agent episode. Used only if collected on the CRF and not derived from start and end date/times.

AG.AGSTRF.label: Start Relative to Reference Period
AG.AGSTRF.description: Describes the start of the agent relative to sponsor-defined reference period. The sponsor-defined reference period is a continuous period of time defined by a discrete starting point and a discrete ending point (represented by RFSTDTC and RFENDTC in Demographics). If information such as "PRIOR", "ONGOING", or "CONTINUING" was collected, this information may be translated into AGSTRF. \n Not all values of the codelist are allowable for this variable. See Section 4.4.7, Use of Relative Timing Variables.

AG.AGENRF.label: End Relative to Reference Period
AG.AGENRF.description: Describes the end of the agent relative to the sponsor-defined reference period. The sponsor-defined reference period is a continuous period of time defined by a discrete starting point and a discrete ending point (represented by RFSTDTC and RFENDTC in Demographics). If information such as "PRIOR", "ONGOING", or "CONTINUING" was collected, this information may be translated into AGENRF. \n Not all values of the codelist are allowable for this variable. See Section 4.4.7, Use of Relative Timing Variables.

AG.AGSTRTPT.label: Start Relative to Reference Time Point
AG.AGSTRTPT.description: Identifies the start of the agent as being before or after the sponsor-defined reference time point defined by variable AGSTTPT. \n Not all values of the codelist are allowable for this variable. See Section 4.4.7, Use of Relative Timing Variables.

AG.AGSTTPT.label: Start Reference Time Point
AG.AGSTTPT.description: Description or date/time in ISO 8601 character format of the reference point referred to by AGSTRTPT. Examples: "2003-12-15", "VISIT 1".

AG.AGENRTPT.label: End Relative to Reference Time Point
AG.AGENRTPT.description: Identifies the end of the agent as being before or after the reference time point defined by variable AGENTPT. Identifies the end of the agent as being before or after the sponsor-defined reference time point defined by variable AGENTPT. \n Not all values of the codelist are allowable for this variable. See Section 4.4.7, Use of Relative Timing Variables.

AG.AGENTPT.label: End Reference Time Point
AG.AGENTPT.description: Description or date/time in ISO 8601 character format of the reference point referred to by AGENRTPT. Examples: "2003-12-25", "VISIT 2".

CM.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
CM.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

CM.CMSEQ.label: Sequence Number
CM.CMSEQ.description: Sequence number to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

CM.CMGRPID.label: Group ID
CM.CMGRPID.description: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

CM.CMSPID.label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
CM.CMSPID.description: Sponsor-defined reference number. Example: a number preprinted on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or record identifier defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: line number on a concomitant medication page.

CM.CMTRT.label: Reported Name of Drug, Med, or Therapy
CM.CMTRT.description: Verbatim medication name that is either preprinted or collected on a CRF.

CM.CMMODIFY.label: Modified Reported Name
CM.CMMODIFY.description: If CMTRT is modified to facilitate coding, then CMMODIFY will contain the modified text.

CM.CMDECOD.label: Standardized Medication Name
CM.CMDECOD.description: Standardized or dictionary-derived text description of CMTRT or CMMODIFY. Equivalent to the generic drug name in WHO Drug. The sponsor is expected to provide the dictionary name and version used to map the terms utilizing the external codelist element in the Define-XML document. If an intervention term does not have a decode value in the dictionary, then CMDECOD will be left blank.

CM.CMCAT.label: Category for Medication
CM.CMCAT.description: Used to define a category of medications/treatment. Examples: "PRIOR", "CONCOMITANT", "ANTI-CANCER MEDICATION", "GENERAL CONMED".

CM.CMSCAT.label: Subcategory for Medication
CM.CMSCAT.description: A further categorization of medications/treatment. Examples: "CHEMOTHERAPY", "HORMONAL THERAPY", "ALTERNATIVE THERAPY".

CM.CMPRESP.label: CM Pre-specified
CM.CMPRESP.description: Used to indicate whether ("Y"/null) information about the use of a specific medication was solicited on the CRF.

CM.CMOCCUR.label: CM Occurrence
CM.CMOCCUR.description: When the use of a specific medication is solicited. CMOCCUR is used to indicate whether ("Y"/"N") use of the medication occurred. Values are null for medications not specifically solicited.

CM.CMSTAT.label: Completion Status
CM.CMSTAT.description: Used to indicate that a question about the occurrence of a prespecified intervention was not answered. Should be null or have a value of "NOT DONE".

CM.CMREASND.label: Reason Medication Not Collected
CM.CMREASND.description: Reason not done. Used in conjunction with CMSTAT when value is "NOT DONE".

CM.CMINDC.label: Indication
CM.CMINDC.description: Denotes why a medication was taken or administered. Examples: "NAUSEA", "HYPERTENSION".

CM.CMCLAS.label: Medication Class
CM.CMCLAS.description: Drug class. May be obtained from coding. When coding to a single class, populate with class value. If using a dictionary and coding to multiple classes, then follow Section 4.2.8.3, Multiple Values for a Non-result Qualifier Variable, or omit CMCLAS.

CM.CMCLASCD.label: Medication Class Code
CM.CMCLASCD.description: Class code corresponding to CMCLAS. Drug class. May be obtained from coding. When coding to a single class, populate with class code. If using a dictionary and coding to multiple classes, then follow Section 4.2.8.3, Multiple Values for a Non-result Qualifier Variable, or omit CMCLASCD.

CM.CMDOSE.label: Dose per Administration
CM.CMDOSE.description: Amount of CMTRT given. Not populated when CMDOSTXT is populated.

CM.CMDOSTXT.label: Dose Description
CM.CMDOSTXT.description: Dosing amounts or a range of dosing information collected in text form. Units may be stored in CMDOSU. Examples: "200-400", "15-20". Not populated when CMDOSE is populated.

CM.CMDOSU.label: Dose Units
CM.CMDOSU.description: Units for CMDOSE, CMDOSTOT, or CMDOSTXT. Examples: "ng", "mg", "mg/kg".

CM.CMDOSFRQ.label: Dosing Frequency per Interval
CM.CMDOSFRQ.description: Usually expressed as the number of repeated administrations of CMDOSE within a specific time period. Examples: "BID" (twice daily), "Q12H" (every 12 hours).

CM.CMDOSTOT.label: Total Daily Dose
CM.CMDOSTOT.description: Total daily dose of CMTRT using the units in CMDOSU. Used when dosing is collected as total daily dose. Total dose over a period other than day could be recorded in a separate supplemental qualifier variable.

CM.CMDOSRGM.label: Intended Dose Regimen
CM.CMDOSRGM.description: Text description of the (intended) schedule or regimen for the Intervention. Example: "TWO WEEKS ON, TWO WEEKS OFF".

CM.CMROUTE.label: Route of Administration
CM.CMROUTE.description: Route of administration for the intervention. Examples: "ORAL", "INTRAVENOUS".

CM.CMADJ.label: Reason for Dose Adjustment
CM.CMADJ.description: Describes reason or explanation of why a dose is adjusted. Examples: "ADVERSE EVENT", "INSUFFICIENT RESPONSE", "NON-MEDICAL REASON".

CM.CMRSDISC.label: Reason the Intervention Was Discontinued
CM.CMRSDISC.description: When dosing of a treatment is recorded over multiple successive records, this variable is applicable only for the (chronologically) last record for the treatment.

CM.TAETORD.label: Planned Order of Element within Arm
CM.TAETORD.description: Number that gives the planned order of the element within the arm for the element in which the medication administration started. Null for medications that started before study participation.

CM.EPOCH.label: Epoch
CM.EPOCH.description: Epoch associated with the start date/time of the medication administration. Null for medications that started before study participation.

CM.CMSTDTC.label: Start Date/Time of Medication
CM.CMSTDTC.description: Start date/time of the medication administration represented in ISO 8601 character format.

CM.CMENDTC.label: End Date/Time of Medication
CM.CMENDTC.description: End date/time of the medication administration represented in ISO 8601 character format.

CM.CMSTDY.label: Study Day of Start of Medication
CM.CMSTDY.description: Study day of start of medication relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.

CM.CMENDY.label: Study Day of End of Medication
CM.CMENDY.description: Study day of end of medication relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.

CM.CMDUR.label: Duration
CM.CMDUR.description: Collected duration for a treatment episode. Used only if collected on the CRF and not derived from start and end date/times.

CM.CMSTRF.label: Start Relative to Reference Period
CM.CMSTRF.description: Describes the start of the medication relative to sponsor-defined reference period. The sponsor-defined reference period is a continuous period of time defined by a discrete starting point and a discrete ending point (represented by RFSTDTC and RFENDTC in Demographics). If information such as "PRIOR" was collected, this information may be translated into CMSTRF. \n Not all values of the codelist are allowable for this variable. See Section 4.4.7, Use of Relative Timing Variables.

CM.CMENRF.label: End Relative to Reference Period
CM.CMENRF.description: Describes the end of the medication relative to the sponsor-defined reference period. The sponsor-defined reference period is a continuous period of time defined by a discrete starting point and a discrete ending point (represented by RFSTDTC and RFENDTC in Demographics). If information such as "PRIOR", "ONGOING, or "CONTINUING" was collected, this information may be translated into CMENRF. \n Not all values of the codelist are allowable for this variable. See Section 4.4.7, Use of Relative Timing Variables.

CM.CMSTRTPT.label: Start Relative to Reference Time Point
CM.CMSTRTPT.description: Identifies the start of the medication as being before or after the sponsor-defined reference time point defined by variable CMSTTPT. \n Not all values of the codelist are allowable for this variable. See Section 4.4.7, Use of Relative Timing Variables.

CM.CMSTTPT.label: Start Reference Time Point
CM.CMSTTPT.description: Description or date/time in ISO 8601 character format of the sponsor-defined reference point referred to by CMSTRTPT. Examples: "2003-12-15", "VISIT 1".

CM.CMENRTPT.label: End Relative to Reference Time Point
CM.CMENRTPT.description: Identifies the end of the medication as being before or after the sponsor-defined reference time point defined by variable CMENTPT. \n Not all values of the codelist are allowable for this variable. See Section 4.4.7, Use of Relative Timing Variables.

CM.CMENTPT.label: End Reference Time Point
CM.CMENTPT.description: Description or date/time in ISO 8601 character format of the sponsor-defined reference point referred to by CMENRTPT. Examples: "2003-12-25", "VISIT 2".

EC.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
EC.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

EC.ECSEQ.label: Sequence Number
EC.ECSEQ.description: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

EC.ECGRPID.label: Group ID
EC.ECGRPID.description: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

EC.ECREFID.label: Reference ID
EC.ECREFID.description: Internal or external identifier (e.g., kit number, bottle label, vial identifier).

EC.ECSPID.label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
EC.ECSPID.description: Sponsor-defined reference number. May be preprinted on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: Line number on a CRF page.

EC.ECLNKID.label: Link ID
EC.ECLNKID.description: Identifier used to link related records across domains.

EC.ECLNKGRP.label: Link Group ID
EC.ECLNKGRP.description: Identifier used to link related, grouped records across domains.

EC.ECTRT.label: Name of Treatment
EC.ECTRT.description: Name of the intervention treatment known to the subject and/or administrator.

EC.ECMOOD.label: Mood
EC.ECMOOD.description: Mode or condition of the record specifying whether the intervention (activity) is intended to happen or has happened. Values align with BRIDG pillars (e.g., scheduled context, performed context) and HL7 activity moods (e.g., intent, event). Examples: "SCHEDULED", "PERFORMED".

EC.ECCAT.label: Category of Treatment
EC.ECCAT.description: Used to define a category of related ECTRT values.

EC.ECSCAT.label: Subcategory of Treatment
EC.ECSCAT.description: A further categorization of ECCAT values.

EC.ECPRESP.label: Pre-Specified
EC.ECPRESP.description: Used when a specific intervention is prespecified. Values should be "Y" or null.

EC.ECOCCUR.label: Occurrence
EC.ECOCCUR.description: Used to indicate whether a treatment occurred when information about the occurrence is solicited. ECOCCUR = "N" when a treatment was not taken, not given, or missed.

EC.ECREASOC.label: Reason for Occur Value
EC.ECREASOC.description: The reason for the value in --OCCUR. If --OCCUR = "N", this is the reason the exposure did not occur.

EC.ECDOSE.label: Dose
EC.ECDOSE.description: Amount of ECTRT when numeric. Not populated when ECDOSTXT is populated.

EC.ECDOSTXT.label: Dose Description
EC.ECDOSTXT.description: Amount of ECTRT when non-numeric. Dosing amounts or a range of dosing information collected in text form. Example: "200-400". Not populated when ECDOSE is populated.

EC.ECDOSU.label: Dose Units
EC.ECDOSU.description: Units for ECDOSE, ECDOSTOT, or ECDOSTXT.

EC.ECDOSFRQ.label: Dosing Frequency per Interval
EC.ECDOSFRQ.description: Usually expressed as the number of repeated administrations of ECDOSE within a specific time period. Examples: "Q2H", "QD", "BID".

EC.ECDOSTOT.label: Total Daily Dose
EC.ECDOSTOT.description: Total daily dose of ECTRT using the units in ECDOSU. Used when dosing is collected as total daily dose.

EC.ECDOSRGM.label: Intended Dose Regimen
EC.ECDOSRGM.description: Text description of the intended schedule or regimen for the Intervention. Example: "TWO WEEKS ON", "TWO WEEKS OFF".

EC.ECROUTE.label: Route of Administration
EC.ECROUTE.description: Route of administration for the intervention. Examples: "ORAL", "INTRAVENOUS".

EC.ECLOT.label: Lot Number
EC.ECLOT.description: Lot number of the ECTRT product.

EC.ECLAT.label: Laterality
EC.ECLAT.description: Qualifier for anatomical location further detailing laterality of the intervention administration. Examples: "LEFT", "RIGHT".

EC.ECDIR.label: Directionality
EC.ECDIR.description: Qualifier for anatomical location further detailing directionality. Examples: "ANTERIOR", "LOWER", "PROXIMAL", "UPPER".

EC.ECPORTOT.label: Portion or Totality
EC.ECPORTOT.description: Qualifier for anatomical location further detailing distribution (i.e., arrangement of, apportioning of). Examples: "ENTIRE", "SINGLE", "SEGMENT".

EC.ECFAST.label: Fasting Status
EC.ECFAST.description: Indicator used to identify fasting status. Examples: "Y", "N".

EC.ECPSTRG.label: Pharmaceutical Strength
EC.ECPSTRG.description: Amount of an active ingredient expressed quantitatively per dosage unit, per unit of volume, or per unit of weight, according to the pharmaceutical dose form.

EC.ECADJ.label: Reason for Dose Adjustment
EC.ECADJ.description: Describes reason or explanation of why a dose is adjusted.

EC.TAETORD.label: Planned Order of Element within Arm
EC.TAETORD.description: Number that gives the planned order of the element within the arm.

EC.EPOCH.label: Epoch
EC.EPOCH.description: Trial epoch of the exposure as collected record. Examples: "RUN-IN", "TREATMENT".

EC.ECSTDTC.label: Start Date/Time of Treatment
EC.ECSTDTC.description: The date/time when administration of the treatment indicated by ECTRT and ECDOSE began.

EC.ECENDTC.label: End Date/Time of Treatment
EC.ECENDTC.description: The date/time when administration of the treatment indicated by ECTRT and ECDOSE ended. For administrations considered given at a point in time (e.g., oral tablet, pre-filled syringe injection), where only an administration date/time is collected, ECSTDTC should be copied to ECENDTC as the standard representation.

EC.ECSTDY.label: Study Day of Start of Treatment
EC.ECSTDY.description: Study day of ECSTDTC relative to the sponsor-defined DM.RFSTDTC.

EC.ECENDY.label: Study Day of End of Treatment
EC.ECENDY.description: Study day of ECENDTC relative to the sponsor-defined DM.RFSTDTC.

EC.ECDUR.label: Duration of Treatment
EC.ECDUR.description: Collected duration of administration. Used only if collected on the CRF and not derived from start and end date/times.

EC.ECTPT.label: Planned Time Point Name
EC.ECTPT.description: Text description of time when administration should occur. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point, such as time of last dose. See ECTPTNUM and ECTPTREF.

EC.ECTPTNUM.label: Planned Time Point Number
EC.ECTPTNUM.description: Numerical version of ECTPT to aid in sorting.

EC.ECELTM.label: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
EC.ECELTM.description: Planned elapsed time relative to the planned fixed reference (ECTPTREF). This variable is useful where there are repetitive measures. Not a clock time.

EC.ECTPTREF.label: Time Point Reference
EC.ECTPTREF.description: Name of the fixed reference point referred to by ECELTM, ECTPTNUM, and ECTPT. Examples: "PREVIOUS DOSE", "PREVIOUS MEAL".

EC.ECRFTDTC.label: Date/Time of Reference Time Point
EC.ECRFTDTC.description: Date/time for a fixed reference time point defined by ECTPTREF.

EX.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
EX.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

EX.EXSEQ.label: Sequence Number
EX.EXSEQ.description: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

EX.EXGRPID.label: Group ID
EX.EXGRPID.description: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

EX.EXREFID.label: Reference ID
EX.EXREFID.description: Internal or external identifier (e.g., kit number, bottle label, vial identifier).

EX.EXSPID.label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
EX.EXSPID.description: Sponsor-defined reference number. May be preprinted on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: Line number on a CRF page.

EX.EXLNKID.label: Link ID
EX.EXLNKID.description: Identifier used to link related records across domains.

EX.EXLNKGRP.label: Link Group ID
EX.EXLNKGRP.description: Identifier used to link related, grouped records across domains.

EX.EXTRT.label: Name of Treatment
EX.EXTRT.description: Name of the protocol-specified study treatment given during the dosing period for the observation.

EX.EXCAT.label: Category of Treatment
EX.EXCAT.description: Used to define a category of EXTRT values.

EX.EXSCAT.label: Subcategory of Treatment
EX.EXSCAT.description: A further categorization of EXCAT values.

EX.EXDOSE.label: Dose
EX.EXDOSE.description: Amount of EXTRT when numeric. Not populated when EXDOSTXT is populated.

EX.EXDOSTXT.label: Dose Description
EX.EXDOSTXT.description: Amount of EXTRT when non-numeric. Dosing amounts or a range of dosing information collected in text form. Example: "200-400". Not populated when EXDOSE is populated.

EX.EXDOSU.label: Dose Units
EX.EXDOSU.description: Units for EXDOSE, EXDOSTOT, or EXDOSTXT representing protocol-specified values. Examples: "ng", "mg", "mg/kg", "mg/m2".

EX.EXDOSFRQ.label: Dosing Frequency per Interval
EX.EXDOSFRQ.description: Usually expressed as the number of repeated administrations of EXDOSE within a specific time period. Examples: "Q2H", "QD", "BID".

EX.EXDOSRGM.label: Intended Dose Regimen
EX.EXDOSRGM.description: Text description of the intended schedule or regimen for the Intervention. Example: "TWO WEEKS ON, TWO WEEKS OFF".

EX.EXROUTE.label: Route of Administration
EX.EXROUTE.description: Route of administration for the intervention. Examples: "ORAL", "INTRAVENOUS".

EX.EXLOT.label: Lot Number
EX.EXLOT.description: Lot number of the intervention product.

EX.EXLAT.label: Laterality
EX.EXLAT.description: Qualifier for anatomical location further detailing laterality of the intervention administration. Examples: "LEFT", "RIGHT".

EX.EXDIR.label: Directionality
EX.EXDIR.description: Qualifier for anatomical location further detailing directionality. Examples: "ANTERIOR", "LOWER", "PROXIMAL", "UPPER".

EX.EXFAST.label: Fasting Status
EX.EXFAST.description: Indicator used to identify fasting status. Examples: "Y", "N".

EX.EXADJ.label: Reason for Dose Adjustment
EX.EXADJ.description: Describes reason or explanation of why a dose is adjusted.

EX.TAETORD.label: Planned Order of Element within Arm
EX.TAETORD.description: Number that gives the planned order of the element within the arm.

EX.EPOCH.label: Epoch
EX.EPOCH.description: Trial epoch of the exposure record. Examples: "RUN-IN", "TREATMENT".

EX.EXSTDTC.label: Start Date/Time of Treatment
EX.EXSTDTC.description: The date/time when administration of the treatment indicated by EXTRT and EXDOSE began.

EX.EXENDTC.label: End Date/Time of Treatment
EX.EXENDTC.description: The date/time when administration of the treatment indicated by EXTRT and EXDOSE ended. For administrations considered given at a point in time (e.g., oral tablet, pre-filled syringe injection), where only an administration date/time is collected, EXSTDTC should be copied to EXENDTC as the standard representation.

EX.EXSTDY.label: Study Day of Start of Treatment
EX.EXSTDY.description: Study day of EXSTDTC relative to DM.RFSTDTC.

EX.EXENDY.label: Study Day of End of Treatment
EX.EXENDY.description: Study day of EXENDTC relative to DM.RFSTDTC.

EX.EXDUR.label: Duration of Treatment
EX.EXDUR.description: Collected duration of administration. Used only if collected on the CRF and not derived from start and end date/times.

EX.EXTPT.label: Planned Time Point Name
EX.EXTPT.description: Text description of time when administration should occur. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point, such as time of last dose. See EXTPTNUM and EXTPTREF.

EX.EXTPTNUM.label: Planned Time Point Number
EX.EXTPTNUM.description: Numerical version of EXTPT to aid in sorting.

EX.EXELTM.label: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
EX.EXELTM.description: Planned elapsed time relative to the planned fixed reference (EXTPTREF). This variable is useful where there are repetitive measures. Not a clock time.

EX.EXTPTREF.label: Time Point Reference
EX.EXTPTREF.description: Name of the fixed reference point referred to by EXELTM, EXTPTNUM, and EXTPT. Examples: PREVIOUS DOSE, PREVIOUS MEAL.

EX.EXRFTDTC.label: Date/Time of Reference Time Point
EX.EXRFTDTC.description: Date/time for a fixed reference time point defined by EXTPTREF.

ML.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
ML.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

ML.MLSEQ.label: Sequence Number
ML.MLSEQ.description: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

ML.MLGRPID.label: Group ID
ML.MLGRPID.description: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

ML.MLSPID.label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
ML.MLSPID.description: Sponsor-defined reference number. Examples: a number preprinted on the CRF as an explicit line identifier, record identifier defined in the sponsor's operational database.

ML.MLTRT.label: Name of Meal
ML.MLTRT.description: Verbatim food product name that is either preprinted or collected on a CRF.

ML.MLCAT.label: Category for Meal
ML.MLCAT.description: Used to define a category of MLTRT values.

ML.MLSCAT.label: Subcategory for Meal
ML.MLSCAT.description: Used to define a further categorization of MLCAT values.

ML.MLPRESP.label: ML Pre-specified
ML.MLPRESP.description: Used when a specific meal is prespecified on a CRF. Values should be "Y" or null.

ML.MLOCCUR.label: ML Occurrence
ML.MLOCCUR.description: Used to record whether a prespecified meal occurred when information about the occurrence of a specific meal is solicited.

ML.MLSTAT.label: Completion Status
ML.MLSTAT.description: Used to indicate when a question about the occurrence of a prespecified meal was not answered. Should be null or have a value of "NOT DONE".

ML.MLREASND.label: Reason Meal Not Collected
ML.MLREASND.description: Describes the reason a response to a question about the occurrence of a meal was not collected. Used in conjunction with MLSTAT when value is "NOT DONE".

ML.MLDOSE.label: Dose
ML.MLDOSE.description: Amount of MLTRT consumed. Not populated when MLDOSTXT is populated.

ML.MLDOSTXT.label: Dose Description
ML.MLDOSTXT.description: Amount description of MLTRT consumed, collected in text form. Not populated when MLDOSE is populated. Examples: "<1 per day", "200-400".

ML.MLDOSU.label: Dose Units
ML.MLDOSU.description: Units for MLDOSE, MLDOSTOT, or MLDOSTXT.

ML.MLDOSFRM.label: Dose Form
ML.MLDOSFRM.description: Dosage form for MLTRT. Example: "BAR, CHEWABLE".

ML.VISITNUM.label: Visit Number
ML.VISITNUM.description: Clinical encounter number. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

ML.VISIT.label: Visit Name
ML.VISIT.description: Protocol-defined description of a clinical encounter.

ML.VISITDY.label: Planned Study Day of Visit
ML.VISITDY.description: Planned study day of VISIT. Should be an integer.

ML.TAETORD.label: Planned Order of Element within Arm
ML.TAETORD.description: Number that gives the planned order of the element within the arm for the element in which the meal started.

ML.EPOCH.label: Epoch
ML.EPOCH.description: Epoch associated with the start date/time of the meal.

ML.MLDTC.label: Date/Time of Collection
ML.MLDTC.description: Collection date and time of the meal represented in ISO 8601 character format.

ML.MLSTDTC.label: Start Date/Time of Meal
ML.MLSTDTC.description: Start date/time of the meal represented in ISO 8601 character format.

ML.MLENDTC.label: End Date/Time of Meal
ML.MLENDTC.description: End date/time of the meal represented in ISO 8601 character format.

ML.MLDY.label: Study Day of Visit/Collection/Exam
ML.MLDY.description: Actual study day of the visit/collection expressed in integer days relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics.

ML.MLSTDY.label: Study Day of Start of Meal
ML.MLSTDY.description: Actual study day of start of the meal expressed in integer days relative to sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics.

ML.MLENDY.label: Study Day of End of Meal
ML.MLENDY.description: Actual study day of end of the meal expressed in integer days relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics.

ML.MLDUR.label: Duration of Meal
ML.MLDUR.description: Collected duration of the meal represented in ISO 8601 character format. Used only if collected on the CRF and not derived.

ML.MLTPT.label: Planned Time Point Name
ML.MLTPT.description: Text description of time when a measurement or observation should be taken as defined in the protocol. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point. See MLTPTNUM and MLTPTREF.

ML.MLTPTNUM.label: Planned Time Point Number
ML.MLTPTNUM.description: Numeric version of planned time point used in sorting.

ML.MLELTM.label: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
ML.MLELTM.description: Planned elapsed time (in ISO 8601) relative to the planned fixed reference (MLTPTREF). This variable is useful when there are repetitive measures. Not a clock time or a date/time variable. Represented as an ISO 8601 duration.

ML.MLTPTREF.label: Time Point Reference
ML.MLTPTREF.description: Description of the fixed reference point referred to by MLELTM, MLTPTNUM, and MLTPT.

ML.MLRFTDTC.label: Date/Time of Reference Time Point
ML.MLRFTDTC.description: Date/time for a fixed reference time point defined by MLTPTREF in ISO 8601 character format.

ML.MIDS.label: Disease Milestone Instance Name
ML.MIDS.description: The name of a specific instance of a disease milestone type (MIDSTYPE) described in the Trial Disease Milestones dataset. This should be unique within a subject. Used only in conjunction with RELMIDS and MIDSDTC.

ML.RELMIDS.label: Temporal Relation to Milestone Instance
ML.RELMIDS.description: The temporal relationship of the observation to the disease milestone instance name in MIDS. Examples: "IMMEDIATELY BEFORE", "AT TIME OF", "AFTER".

ML.MIDSDTC.label: Disease Milestone Instance Date/Time
ML.MIDSDTC.description: The start date/time of the disease milestone instance name in MIDS, in ISO 8601 format.

PR.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
PR.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

PR.PRSEQ.label: Sequence Number
PR.PRSEQ.description: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

PR.PRGRPID.label: Group ID
PR.PRGRPID.description: Used to link together a block of related records within a subject in a domain.

PR.PRSPID.label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
PR.PRSPID.description: Sponsor-defined identifier. Example: preprinted line identifier on a CRF, record identifier defined in the sponsor's operational database.

PR.PRLNKID.label: Link ID
PR.PRLNKID.description: Used to facilitate identification of relationships between records.

PR.PRLNKGRP.label: Link Group ID
PR.PRLNKGRP.description: Used to facilitate identification of relationships between records.

PR.PRTRT.label: Reported Name of Procedure
PR.PRTRT.description: Name of procedure performed, either preprinted or collected on a CRF.

PR.PRDECOD.label: Standardized Procedure Name
PR.PRDECOD.description: Standardized or dictionary-derived name of PRTRT. If the codelist "PROCEDUR" is not used, the sponsor is expected to provide the dictionary name and version used to map the terms in the external codelist element in the Define-XML document. If an intervention term does not have a decode value, then PRDECOD will be null.

PR.PRCAT.label: Category
PR.PRCAT.description: Used to define a category of procedure values.

PR.PRSCAT.label: Subcategory
PR.PRSCAT.description: Used to define a further categorization of PRCAT values.

PR.PRPRESP.label: Pre-specified
PR.PRPRESP.description: Used when a specific procedure is pre-specified on a CRF. Values should be "Y" or null.

PR.PROCCUR.label: Occurrence
PR.PROCCUR.description: Used to record whether a prespecified procedure occurred when information about the occurrence of a specific procedure is solicited.

PR.PRINDC.label: Indication
PR.PRINDC.description: Denotes the indication for the procedure (e.g., why the procedure was performed).

PR.PRDOSE.label: Dose
PR.PRDOSE.description: Amount of PRTRT administered. Not populated when PRDOSTXT is populated.

PR.PRDOSTXT.label: Dose Description
PR.PRDOSTXT.description: Dosing information collected in text form. Examples: "<1", "200-400". Not populated when PRDOSE is populated.

PR.PRDOSU.label: Dose Units
PR.PRDOSU.description: Units for PRDOSE, PRDOSTOT, or PRDOSTXT.

PR.PRDOSFRQ.label: Dosing Frequency per Interval
PR.PRDOSFRQ.description: Usually expressed as the number of doses given per a specific interval.

PR.PRDOSRGM.label: Intended Dose Regimen
PR.PRDOSRGM.description: Text description of the intended schedule or regimen for the procedure.

PR.PRLAT.label: Laterality
PR.PRLAT.description: Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing laterality.

PR.PRDIR.label: Directionality
PR.PRDIR.description: Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing directionality.

PR.PRPORTOT.label: Portion or Totality
PR.PRPORTOT.description: Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing the distribution, which means arrangement of, apportioning of.

PR.VISITNUM.label: Visit Number
PR.VISITNUM.description: Clinical encounter number. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

PR.VISIT.label: Visit Name
PR.VISIT.description: Protocol-defined description of a clinical encounter.

PR.VISITDY.label: Planned Study Day of Visit
PR.VISITDY.description: Planned study day of VISIT. Should be an integer.

PR.TAETORD.label: Planned Order of Element within Arm
PR.TAETORD.description: Number that gives the planned order of the element within the arm.

PR.EPOCH.label: Epoch
PR.EPOCH.description: Epoch associated with the start date/time of the procedure.

PR.PRSTDTC.label: Start Date/Time of Procedure
PR.PRSTDTC.description: Start date/time of the procedure represented in ISO 8601 character format.

PR.PRENDTC.label: End Date/Time of Procedure
PR.PRENDTC.description: End date/time of the procedure represented in ISO 8601 character format.

PR.PRSTDY.label: Study Day of Start of Procedure
PR.PRSTDY.description: Study day of start of procedure expressed in integer days relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics.

PR.PRENDY.label: Study Day of End of Procedure
PR.PRENDY.description: Study day of end of procedure expressed in integer days relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics.

PR.PRDUR.label: Duration of Procedure
PR.PRDUR.description: Collected duration of a procedure represented in ISO 8601 character format. Used only if collected on the CRF and not derived from start and end date/times.

PR.PRTPT.label: Planned Time Point Name
PR.PRTPT.description: Text description of time when a procedure should be performed. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point, such as time of last dose. See PRTPTNUM and PRTPTREF.

PR.PRTPTNUM.label: Planned Time Point Number
PR.PRTPTNUM.description: Numerical version of planned time point used in sorting.

PR.PRELTM.label: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
PR.PRELTM.description: Planned elapsed time in ISO 8601 format relative to a planned fixed reference (PRTPTREF). This variable is useful where there are repetitive measures. Not a clock time or a date/time variable, but an interval, represented as ISO duration.

PR.PRTPTREF.label: Time Point Reference
PR.PRTPTREF.description: Description of the fixed reference point referred to by PRELTM, PRTPTNUM, and PRTPT.

PR.PRRFTDTC.label: Date/Time of Reference Time Point
PR.PRRFTDTC.description: Date/time for a fixed reference time point defined by PRTRTREF in ISO 8601 character format.

PR.PRSTRTPT.label: Start Relative to Reference Time Point
PR.PRSTRTPT.description: Identifies the start of the observation as being before or after the sponsor-defined reference time point defined by variable PRSTTPT. \n Not all values of the codelist are allowable for this variable. See Section 4.4.7, Use of Relative Timing Variables.

PR.PRSTTPT.label: Start Reference Time Point
PR.PRSTTPT.description: Description or date/time in ISO 8601 character format of the sponsor-defined reference point referred to by PRSTRTPT. Examples: "2003-12-15", "VISIT 1".

PR.PRENRTPT.label: End Relative to Reference Time Point
PR.PRENRTPT.description: Identifies the end of the observation as being before or after the sponsor-defined reference time point defined by variable PRENTPT. \n Not all values of the codelist are allowable for this variable. See Section 4.4.7, Use of Relative Timing Variables.

PR.PRENTPT.label: End Reference Time Point
PR.PRENTPT.description: Description or date/time in ISO 8601 character format of the sponsor-defined reference point referred to by PRENRTPT. Examples: "2003-12-25", "VISIT 2".

SU.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
SU.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

SU.SUSEQ.label: Sequence Number
SU.SUSEQ.description: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

SU.SUGRPID.label: Group ID
SU.SUGRPID.description: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

SU.SUSPID.label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
SU.SUSPID.description: Sponsor-defined reference number. May be preprinted on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: Line number on a Tobacco & Alcohol Use CRF page.

SU.SUMODIFY.label: Modified Substance Name
SU.SUMODIFY.description: If SUTRT is modified, then the modified text is placed here.

SU.SUDECOD.label: Standardized Substance Name
SU.SUDECOD.description: Standardized or dictionary-derived text description of SUTRT or SUMODIFY if the sponsor chooses to code the substance use. The sponsor is expected to provide the dictionary name and version used to map the terms utilizing the external codelist element in the Define-XML document.

SU.SUCAT.label: Category for Substance Use
SU.SUCAT.description: Used to define a category of related records. Examples: "TOBACCO", "ALCOHOL", or "CAFFEINE".

SU.SUSCAT.label: Subcategory for Substance Use
SU.SUSCAT.description: A further categorization of substance use. Examples: "CIGARS", "CIGARETTES", "BEER", "WINE".

SU.SUPRESP.label: SU Pre-Specified
SU.SUPRESP.description: Used to indicate whether ("Y"/null) information about the use of a specific substance was solicited on the CRF.

SU.SUOCCUR.label: SU Occurrence
SU.SUOCCUR.description: When the use of specific substances is solicited, SUOCCUR is used to indicate whether ("Y"/"N") a particular prespecified substance was used. Values are null for substances not specifically solicited.

SU.SUSTAT.label: Completion Status
SU.SUSTAT.description: When the use of prespecified substances is solicited, the completion status indicates that there was no response to the question about the prespecified substance. When there is no prespecified list on the CRF, then the completion status indicates that substance use was not assessed for the subject.

SU.SUREASND.label: Reason Substance Use Not Collected
SU.SUREASND.description: Describes the reason substance use was not collected. Used in conjunction with SUSTAT when value of SUSTAT is "NOT DONE".

SU.SUCLAS.label: Substance Use Class
SU.SUCLAS.description: Substance use class. May be obtained from coding. When coding to a single class, populate with class value. If using a dictionary and coding to multiple classes, then follow Section 4.2.8.3, Multiple Values for a Non-result Qualifier Variable, or omit SUCLAS.

SU.SUCLASCD.label: Substance Use Class Code
SU.SUCLASCD.description: Code corresponding to SUCLAS. May be obtained from coding.

SU.SUDOSE.label: Substance Use Consumption
SU.SUDOSE.description: Amount of SUTRT consumed. Not populated if SUDOSTXT is populated.

SU.SUDOSTXT.label: Substance Use Consumption Text
SU.SUDOSTXT.description: Substance use consumption amounts or a range of consumption information collected in text form. Not populated if SUDOSE is populated.

SU.SUDOSU.label: Consumption Units
SU.SUDOSU.description: Units for SUDOSE, SUDOSTOT, or SUDOSTXT. Examples: "oz", "CIGARETTE", "PACK", "g".

SU.SUDOSFRQ.label: Use Frequency Per Interval
SU.SUDOSFRQ.description: Usually expressed as the number of repeated administrations of SUDOSE within a specific time period. Example: "Q24H" (every day).

SU.SUDOSTOT.label: Total Daily Consumption
SU.SUDOSTOT.description: Total daily use of SUTRT using the units in SUDOSU. Used when dosing is collected as total daily dose. If a sponsor needs to aggregate the data over a period other than daily, then the aggregated total could be recorded in a supplemental qualifier variable.

SU.SUROUTE.label: Route of Administration
SU.SUROUTE.description: Route of administration for SUTRT. Examples: "ORAL", "INTRAVENOUS".

SU.TAETORD.label: Planned Order of Element within Arm
SU.TAETORD.description: Number that gives the planned order of the element within the arm for the element in which the substance use started. Null for substances that started before study participation.

SU.EPOCH.label: Epoch
SU.EPOCH.description: Epoch associated with the start date/time of the substance use. Null for substances that started before study participation.

SU.SUSTDTC.label: Start Date/Time of Substance Use
SU.SUSTDTC.description: Start date/time of the substance use represented in ISO 8601 character format.

SU.SUENDTC.label: End Date/Time of Substance Use
SU.SUENDTC.description: End date/time of the substance use represented in ISO 8601 character format.

SU.SUSTDY.label: Study Day of Start of Substance Use
SU.SUSTDY.description: Study day of start of substance use relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.

SU.SUENDY.label: Study Day of End of Substance Use
SU.SUENDY.description: Study day of end of substance use relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.

SU.SUDUR.label: Duration of Substance Use
SU.SUDUR.description: Collected duration of substance use in ISO 8601 format. Used only if collected on the CRF and not derived from start and end date/times.

SU.SUSTRF.label: Start Relative to Reference Period
SU.SUSTRF.description: Describes the start of the substance use relative to the sponsor-defined reference period. The sponsor-defined reference period is a continuous period of time defined by a discrete starting point and a discrete ending point (represented by RFSTDTC and RFENDTC in Demographics). If information such as "PRIOR" was collected, this information may be translated into SUSTRF. \n Not all values of the codelist are allowable for this variable. See Section 4.4.7, Use of Relative Timing Variables.

SU.SUENRF.label: End Relative to Reference Period
SU.SUENRF.description: Describes the end of the substance use with relative to the sponsor-defined reference period. The sponsor-defined reference period is a continuous period of time defined by a discrete starting point and a discrete ending point (represented by RFSTDTC and RFENDTC in Demographics). If information such as "PRIOR", "ONGOING", or "CONTINUING" was collected, this information may be translated into SUENRF. \n Not all values of the codelist are allowable for this variable. See Section 4.4.7, Use of Relative Timing Variables.

SU.SUSTRTPT.label: Start Relative to Reference Time Point
SU.SUSTRTPT.description: Identifies the start of the substance as being before or after the reference time point defined by variable SUSTTPT. \n Not all values of the codelist are allowable for this variable. See Section 4.4.7 , Use of Relative Timing Variables.

SU.SUSTTPT.label: Start Reference Time Point
SU.SUSTTPT.description: Description or date/time in ISO 8601 character format of the reference point referred to by SUSTRTPT. Examples: "2003-12-15", "VISIT 1".

SU.SUENRTPT.label: End Relative to Reference Time Point
SU.SUENRTPT.description: Identifies the end of the substance as being before or after the reference time point defined by variable SUENTPT. \n Not all values of the codelist are allowable for this variable. See Section 4.4.7 , Use of Relative Timing Variables.

SU.SUENTPT.label: End Reference Time Point
SU.SUENTPT.description: Description or date/time in ISO 8601 character format of the reference point referred to by SUENRTPT. Examples: "2003-12-25", "VISIT 2".

AE.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
AE.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

AE.SPDEVID.label: Sponsor Device Identifier
AE.SPDEVID.description: A sequence of characters used by the sponsor to uniquely identify a specific device. Used to represent a device associated in some way with the adverse event. SPDEVID values are defined in the Device Identifiers (DI) domain.

AE.AESEQ.label: Sequence Number
AE.AESEQ.description: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

AE.AEGRPID.label: Group ID
AE.AEGRPID.description: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

AE.AEREFID.label: Reference ID
AE.AEREFID.description: Internal or external identifier such as a serial number on an SAE reporting form.

AE.AESPID.label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
AE.AESPID.description: Sponsor-defined identifier. It may be preprinted on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: Line number on an Adverse Events CRF page.

AE.AETERM.label: Reported Term for the Adverse Event

AE.AEMODIFY.label: Modified Reported Term
AE.AEMODIFY.description: If AETERM is modified to facilitate coding, then AEMODIFY will contain the modified text.

AE.AELLT.label: Lowest Level Term
AE.AELLT.description: Dictionary-derived text description of the lowest level term.

AE.AELLTCD.label: Lowest Level Term Code
AE.AELLTCD.description: Dictionary-derived code for the lowest level term.

AE.AEDECOD.label: Dictionary-Derived Term
AE.AEDECOD.description: Dictionary-derived text description of AETERM or AEMODIFY. Equivalent to the Preferred Term (PT in MedDRA). The sponsor is expected to provide the dictionary name and version used to map the terms utilizing the external codelist element in the Define-XML document.

AE.AEPTCD.label: Preferred Term Code
AE.AEPTCD.description: Dictionary-derived code for the preferred term.

AE.AEHLT.label: High Level Term
AE.AEHLT.description: Dictionary-derived text description of the high level term for the primary system organ class (SOC).

AE.AEHLTCD.label: High Level Term Code
AE.AEHLTCD.description: Dictionary-derived code for the high level term for the primary SOC.

AE.AEHLGT.label: High Level Group Term
AE.AEHLGT.description: Dictionary-derived text description of the high level group term for the primary SOC.

AE.AEHLGTCD.label: High Level Group Term Code
AE.AEHLGTCD.description: Dictionary-derived code for the high level group term for the primary SOC.

AE.AECAT.label: Category for Adverse Event
AE.AECAT.description: Used to define a category of related records. Examples: "BLEEDING", "NEUROPSYCHIATRIC".

AE.AESCAT.label: Subcategory for Adverse Event
AE.AESCAT.description: A further categorization of adverse event. Example: "NEUROLOGIC".

AE.AEPRESP.label: Pre-Specified Adverse Event
AE.AEPRESP.description: A value of "Y" indicates that this adverse event was prespecified on the CRF. Values are null for spontaneously reported events (i.e., those collected as free-text verbatim terms).

AE.AEBODSYS.label: Body System or Organ Class
AE.AEBODSYS.description: Dictionary derived. Body system or organ class used by the sponsor from the coding dictionary (e.g., MedDRA). When using a multi-axial dictionary such as MedDRA, this should contain the SOC used for the sponsor's analyses and summary tables, which may not necessarily be the primary SOC.

AE.AEBDSYCD.label: Body System or Organ Class Code
AE.AEBDSYCD.description: Dictionary derived. Code for the body system or organ class used by the sponsor. When using a multi-axial dictionary such as MedDRA, this should contain the SOC used for the sponsor's analyses and summary tables, which may not necessarily be the primary SOC.

AE.AESOC.label: Primary System Organ Class
AE.AESOC.description: Dictionary-derived text description of the primary SOC. Will be the same as AEBODSYS if the primary SOC was used for analysis.

AE.AESOCCD.label: Primary System Organ Class Code
AE.AESOCCD.description: Dictionary-derived code for the primary SOC. Will be the same as AEBDSYCD if the primary SOC was used for analysis.

AE.AELOC.label: Location of Event
AE.AELOC.description: Describes anatomical location relevant for the event (e.g., "ARM" for skin rash).

AE.AESEV.label: Severity/Intensity
AE.AESEV.description: The severity or intensity of the event. Examples: "MILD", "MODERATE", "SEVERE".

AE.AESER.label: Serious Event
AE.AESER.description: Is this a serious event? Valid values are "Y" and "N".

AE.AEACN.label: Action Taken with Study Treatment
AE.AEACN.description: Describes changes to the study treatment as a result of the event. AEACN is specifically for the relationship to study treatment. AEACNOTH is for actions unrelated to dose adjustments of study treatment. Examples of AEACN values include ICH E2B values: "DRUG WITHDRAWN", "DOSE REDUCED", "DOSE INCREASED", "DOSE NOT CHANGED", "UNKNOWN" and "NOT APPLICABLE".

AE.AEACNOTH.label: Other Action Taken
AE.AEACNOTH.description: Describes other actions taken as a result of the event that are unrelated to dose adjustments of study treatment. Usually reported as free text. Example: "TREATMENT UNBLINDED. PRIMARY CARE PHYSICIAN NOTIFIED".

AE.AEACNDEV.label: Action Taken with Device
AE.AEACNDEV.description: An action taken with a device as the result of the event. The device may or may not be a device under study.

AE.AEREL.label: Causality
AE.AEREL.description: Records the investigator's opinion as to the causality of the event to the treatment. ICH does not establish any required or recommended terms for non-device relatedness. ICH E2A and E2B examples include (up-cased here for alignment to SDTM conventions) terms such as "NOT RELATED", "UNLIKELY RELATED", "POSSIBLY RELATED", "RELATED", but these example terms do not establish any conventions or expectations. Controlled terminology may be defined in the future. Check with regulatory authority for population of this variable.

AE.AERLDEV.label: Relationship of Event to Device
AE.AERLDEV.description:
A judgment as to the likelihood that the device caused the adverse event. The relationship is to a device identified in the data (i.e., has an SPDEVID). The device may be ancillary or under study. 
 Terminology: 
 * In the EU, follow the European Commission Guidelines on Medical Devices, Clinical Investigations: SAE Reporting (MEDDEV 2.7/3) (e.g., Not Related, Unlikely, Possible, Probable, Causal Relationship), with device-specific definitions. 
 * No required Controlled Terminology in US.

AE.AERELNST.label: Relationship to Non-Study Treatment
AE.AERELNST.description: Records the investigator's opinion as to whether the event may have been due to a treatment other than study drug. May be reported as free text. Example: "MORE LIKELY RELATED TO ASPIRIN USE".

AE.AEPATT.label: Pattern of Adverse Event
AE.AEPATT.description: Used to indicate the pattern of the event over time. Examples: "INTERMITTENT", "CONTINUOUS", "SINGLE EVENT".

AE.AEOUT.label: Outcome of Adverse Event
AE.AEOUT.description: Description of the outcome of an event.

AE.AESCAN.label: Involves Cancer
AE.AESCAN.description: Was the serious event associated with the development of cancer? Valid values are "Y" and "N". This is a legacy seriousness criterion. It is not included in ICH E2A or E2B.

AE.AESCONG.label: Congenital Anomaly or Birth Defect
AE.AESCONG.description: Was the serious event associated with congenital anomaly or birth defect? Valid values are "Y" and "N".

AE.AESDISAB.label: Persist or Signif Disability/Incapacity
AE.AESDISAB.description: Did the serious event result in persistent or significant disability/incapacity? Valid values are "Y" and "N".

AE.AESDTH.label: Results in Death
AE.AESDTH.description: Did the serious event result in death? Valid values are "Y" and "N".

AE.AESHOSP.label: Requires or Prolongs Hospitalization
AE.AESHOSP.description: Did the serious event require or prolong hospitalization? Valid values are "Y" and "N".

AE.AESLIFE.label: Is Life Threatening
AE.AESLIFE.description: Was the serious event life-threatening? Valid values are "Y" and "N".

AE.AESOD.label: Occurred with Overdose
AE.AESOD.description: Did the serious event occur with an overdose? Valid values are "Y" and "N". This is a legacy seriousness criterion. It is not included in ICH E2A or E2B.

AE.AESMIE.label: Other Medically Important Serious Event
AE.AESMIE.description: Do additional categories for seriousness apply? Valid values are "Y" and "N".

AE.AESINTV.label: Needs Intervention to Prevent Impairment
AE.AESINTV.description: Records whether medical or surgical intervention was necessary to preclude permanent impairment of a body function, or to prevent permanent damage to a body structure, with either situation suspected to be due to the use of a medical product. This variable is used in conjunction with the other "seriousness" variables (e.g., fatal, life-threatening). It is part of the US federal government definition of a serious adverse event; see 21 CFR Part 803.3(w)(3).

AE.AEUNANT.label: Unanticipated Adverse Device Effect
AE.AEUNANT.description:
Any serious adverse effect on health or safety or any life-threatening problem or death caused by or associated with a device, if that effect, problem, or death was not previously identified in nature, severity, or degree of incidence in the investigational plan or application (including a supplementary plan or application), 
 or 
 any other unanticipated serious problem associated with a device that relates to the rights, safety, or welfare of subjects. (21 CFR Part 812.3(s)). 
 This variable applies only to serious AEs and should hold collected data; if the value is derived, it should be held in ADaM.

AE.AERLPRT.label: Rel of AE to Non-Dev-Rel Study Activity
AE.AERLPRT.description:
The investigator's opinion as to the causality of the event as related to other protocol-required activities, actions, or assessments (e.g., medication changes, tests/assessments, other procedures). The relationship is to a protocol-specified, non-device-related activity where the device is identified in the data (i.e., has an SPDEVID). The device may be ancillary or under study. 
 Terminology: 
 * In the EU, follow the European Commission Guidelines on Medical Devices, Clinical Investigations: SAE Reporting (MEDDEV 2.7/3) (e.g., Not Related, Unlikely, Possible, Probable, Causal Relationship), with device-specific definitions. 
 * No required Controlled Terminology in US.

AE.AERLPRC.label: Rel of AE to Device-Related Procedure
AE.AERLPRC.description:
The investigator's opinion as to the likelihood that the device-related study procedure (e.g., implant/insertion, revision/adjustment, explant/removal) caused the AE. The relationship is to a device-related procedure where the device is identified in the data (i.e., has an SPDEVID). The device may be ancillary or under study. 
 Terminology: 
 * In the EU, follow the European Commission Guidelines on Medical Devices, Clinical Investigations: SAE Reporting (MEDDEV 2.7/3) (e.g., Not Related, Unlikely, Possible, Probable, Causal Relationship), with device-specific definitions. 
 * No required Controlled Terminology in US.

AE.AECONTRT.label: Concomitant or Additional Trtmnt Given
AE.AECONTRT.description: Was another treatment given because of the occurrence of the event? Valid values are "Y" and "N".

AE.AETOXGR.label: Standard Toxicity Grade
AE.AETOXGR.description: Toxicity grade according to a standard toxicity scale (e.g., Common Terminology Criteria for Adverse Events, CTCAE). Sponsors should specify the name of the scale and version used in the metadata (see assumption 7d). If value is from a numeric scale, represent only the number (e.g., "2", not "Grade 2").

AE.TAETORD.label: Planned Order of Element within Arm
AE.TAETORD.description: Number that gives the planned order of the element within the arm.

AE.EPOCH.label: Epoch
AE.EPOCH.description: Epoch associated with the start date/time of the adverse event. Examples: "SCREENING", "TREATMENT", "FOLLOW-UP".

AE.AESTDTC.label: Start Date/Time of Adverse Event
AE.AESTDTC.description: Start date/time of the adverse event represented in ISO 8601 character format.

AE.AEENDTC.label: End Date/Time of Adverse Event
AE.AEENDTC.description: End date/time of the adverse event represented in ISO 8601 character format.

AE.AESTDY.label: Study Day of Start of Adverse Event
AE.AESTDY.description: Study day of start of adverse event relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.

AE.AEENDY.label: Study Day of End of Adverse Event
AE.AEENDY.description: Study day of end of event relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.

AE.AEDUR.label: Duration of Adverse Event
AE.AEDUR.description: Collected duration and unit of an adverse event. Used only if collected on the CRF and not derived from start and end date/times. Example: "P1DT2H" (for 1 day, 2 hours).

AE.AEENRF.label: End Relative to Reference Period
AE.AEENRF.description: Describes the end of the event relative to the sponsor-defined reference period. The sponsor-defined reference period is a continuous period of time defined by a discrete starting point (RFSTDTC) and a discrete ending point (RFENDTC) of the trial. \n Not all values of the codelist are allowable for this variable. See Section 4.4.7, Use of Relative Timing Variables.

AE.AEENRTPT.label: End Relative to Reference Time Point
AE.AEENRTPT.description: Identifies the end of the event as being before or after the reference time point defined by variable AEENTPT. \n Not all values of the codelist are allowable for this variable. See Section 4.4.7, Use of Relative Timing Variables.

AE.AEENTPT.label: End Reference Time Point
AE.AEENTPT.description: Description of date/time in ISO 8601 character format of the reference point referred to by AEENRTPT. Examples: "2003-12-25", "VISIT 2".

BE.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
BE.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

BE.BESEQ.label: Sequence Number
BE.BESEQ.description: Sequence number to ensure uniqueness of records within a dataset for a subject. May be any valid number (including decimals) and does not have to start at 1.

BE.BEGRPID.label: Group ID
BE.BEGRPID.description: Optional group identifier, used to link together a block of related records within a subject in a domain.

BE.BEREFID.label: Reference ID
BE.BEREFID.description: Internal or external identifier for the specimen affected or created by the event.

BE.BESPID.label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
BE.BESPID.description: Optional sponsor-defined reference number. Example: Line number on a CRF page.

BE.BETERM.label: Reported Term for the Biospecimen Event
BE.BETERM.description: Topic variable for an event observation, which is the verbatim or pre-specified name of the event.

BE.BEMODIFY.label: Modified Reported Term
BE.BEMODIFY.description: If the value for BETERM is modified for coding purposes, then the modified text is placed here.

BE.BEDECOD.label: Dictionary-Derived Term
BE.BEDECOD.description: Dictionary-derived text description of BETERM or BEMODIFY, if applicable.

BE.BECAT.label: Category for Biospecimen Event
BE.BECAT.description: Used to define a category of topic-variable values. Example: COLLECTION, PREPARATION, TRANSPORT.

BE.BESCAT.label: Subcategory for Biospecimen Event
BE.BESCAT.description: A further categorization of BECAT values.

BE.BELOC.label: Anatomical Location of Event
BE.BELOC.description: Describes the anatomical location relevant for the event (e.g. BRAIN, LUNG).

BE.BEPARTY.label: Accountable Party
BE.BEPARTY.description: Party accountable for the transferable object (e.g. specimen) as a result of the activity performed in the associated BETERM variable. The party could be an individual (e.g., subject), an organization (e.g., sponsor), or a location that is a proxy for an individual or organization (e.g., site). It is usually a somewhat general term that is further identified in the BEPRTYID variable.

BE.BEPRTYID.label: Identification of Accountable Party
BE.BEPRTYID.description: Identification of the specific party accountable for the transferable object (e.g. Specimen) after the action in BETERM is taken. Used in conjunction with BEPARTY.

BE.VISITNUM.label: Visit Number
BE.VISITNUM.description: Clinical encounter number. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

BE.VISITDY.label: Planned Study Day of Visit
BE.VISITDY.description: Planned study day of VISIT. Should be an integer.

BE.BEDTC.label: Date/Time of Specimen Collection
BE.BEDTC.description: Date and time of specimen collection.

BE.BESTDY.label: Study Day of Start of Biospecimen Event
BE.BESTDY.description: Actual study day of start of observation expressed in integer days relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics.

BE.BEENDY.label: Study Day of End of Biospecimen Event
BE.BEENDY.description: Actual study day of end of observation expressed in integer days relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics.

BE.BEDUR.label: Duration of Biospecimen Event
BE.BEDUR.description: Collected duration and unit of a biospecimen event. Used only if collected on the CRF and not derived from start and end date/times. Example: P1DT2H (for 1 day, 2 hours).

CE.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
CE.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

CE.CESEQ.label: Sequence Number
CE.CESEQ.description: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

CE.CEGRPID.label: Group ID
CE.CEGRPID.description: Used to link together a block of related records for a subject within a domain.

CE.CEREFID.label: Reference ID
CE.CEREFID.description: Internal or external identifier (e.g., lab specimen ID, UUID for an ECG waveform or medical image).

CE.CETERM.label: Reported Term for the Clinical Event
CE.CETERM.description: Term for the medical condition or event. Most likely preprinted on CRF.

CE.CEDECOD.label: Dictionary-Derived Term
CE.CEDECOD.description: Controlled terminology for the name of the clinical event. The sponsor is expected to provide the dictionary name and version used to map the terms utilizing the external codelist element in the Define-XML document.

CE.CECAT.label: Category for the Clinical Event
CE.CECAT.description: Used to define a category of related records.

CE.CESCAT.label: Subcategory for the Clinical Event
CE.CESCAT.description: A further categorization of the condition or event.

CE.CEPRESP.label: Clinical Event Pre-specified
CE.CEPRESP.description: Used to indicate whether the event in CETERM was prespecified. Value is "Y" for prespecified events and null for spontaneously reported events.

CE.CEOCCUR.label: Clinical Event Occurrence
CE.CEOCCUR.description: Used when the occurrence of specific events is solicited, to indicate whether or not a clinical event occurred. Values are null for spontaneously reported events.

CE.CESTAT.label: Completion Status
CE.CESTAT.description: The status indicates that a question from a prespecified list was not answered.

CE.CEREASND.label: Reason Clinical Event Not Collected
CE.CEREASND.description: Describes the reason clinical event data was not collected. Used in conjunction with CESTAT when value is "NOT DONE".

CE.CEBODSYS.label: Body System or Organ Class
CE.CEBODSYS.description: Dictionary-derived. Body system or organ class that is involved in an event or measurement from a standard hierarchy (e.g., MedDRA). When using a multi-axial dictionary such as MedDRA, this should contain the SOC used for the sponsor's analyses and summary tables, which may not necessarily be the primary SOC.

CE.CESEV.label: Severity/Intensity
CE.CESEV.description: The severity or intensity of the event. Examples: "MILD", "MODERATE", "SEVERE".

CE.CETOXGR.label: Standard Toxicity Grade
CE.CETOXGR.description: Toxicity grade according to a standard toxicity scale (e.g., Common Terminology Criteria for Adverse Events (CTCAE) v3.0). Sponsor should specify name of the scale and version used in the metadata. If value is from a numeric scale, represent only the number (e.g., "2", not "Grade 2").

CE.TAETORD.label: Planned Order of Element within Arm
CE.TAETORD.description: Number that gives the planned order of the element within the arm for the element in which the clinical event started.

CE.EPOCH.label: Epoch
CE.EPOCH.description: Epoch associated with the start date/time of the clinical event.

CE.CEDTC.label: Date/Time of Event Collection
CE.CEDTC.description: Collection date and time for the clinical event observation represented in ISO 8601 character format.

CE.CESTDTC.label: Start Date/Time of Clinical Event
CE.CESTDTC.description: Start date/time of the clinical event represented in ISO 8601 character format.

CE.CEENDTC.label: End Date/Time of Clinical Event
CE.CEENDTC.description: End date/time of the clinical event, represented in ISO 8601 character format.

CE.CEDY.label: Study Day of Event Collection
CE.CEDY.description: Study day of clinical event collection, measured as integer days. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics. This formula should be consistent across the submission.

CE.CESTDY.label: Study Day of Start of Event
CE.CESTDY.description: Actual study day of start of the clinical event expressed in integer days relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics.

CE.CEENDY.label: Study Day of End of Event
CE.CEENDY.description: Actual study day of end of the clinical event expressed in integer days relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics.

CE.CESTRF.label: Start Relative to Reference Period
CE.CESTRF.description: Describes the start of the clinical event relative to the sponsor-defined reference period. The sponsor-defined reference period is a continuous period of time defined by a discrete starting point and a discrete ending point (represented by RFSTDTC and RFENDTC in Demographics). \n Not all values of the codelist are allowable for this variable. See Section 4.4.7, Use of Relative Timing Variables.

CE.CEENRF.label: End Relative to Reference Period
CE.CEENRF.description: Describes the end of the event relative to the sponsor-defined reference period. The sponsor-defined reference period is a continuous period of time defined by a discrete starting point and a discrete ending point (represented by RFSTDTC and RFENDTC in Demographics). \n Not all values of the codelist are allowable for this variable. See Section 4.4.7, Use of Relative Timing Variables.

CE.CESTRTPT.label: Start Relative to Reference Time Point
CE.CESTRTPT.description: Identifies the start of the observation as being before or after the reference time point defined by variable CESTTPT. \n Not all values of the codelist are allowable for this variable. See Section 4.4.7, Use of Relative Timing Variables.

CE.CESTTPT.label: Start Reference Time Point
CE.CESTTPT.description: Description or date/time in ISO 8601 character format of the sponsor-defined reference point referred to by --STRTPT. Examples: "2003-12-15", "VISIT 1".

CE.CEENRTPT.label: End Relative to Reference Time Point
CE.CEENRTPT.description: Identifies the end of the observation as being before or after the sponsor-defined reference time point defined by variable CEENTPT. \n Not all values of the codelist are allowable for this variable. See Section 4.4.7, Use of Relative Timing Variables.

CE.CEENTPT.label: End Reference Time Point
CE.CEENTPT.description: Description or date/time in ISO 8601 character format of the reference point referred to by CEENRTPT. Examples: "2003-12-25", "VISIT 2".

DS.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
DS.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

DS.DSSEQ.label: Sequence Number
DS.DSSEQ.description: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

DS.DSGRPID.label: Group ID
DS.DSGRPID.description: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

DS.DSSPID.label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
DS.DSSPID.description: Sponsor-defined reference number. May be preprinted on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: Line number on a Disposition page.

DS.DSTERM.label: Reported Term for the Disposition Event
DS.DSTERM.description: Verbatim name of the event or protocol milestone. Some terms in DSTERM will match DSDECOD, but others, such as "Subject moved", will map to controlled terminology in DSDECOD, such as "LOST TO FOLLOW-UP".

DS.DSDECOD.label: Standardized Disposition Term
DS.DSDECOD.description: Controlled terminology for the name of disposition event or protocol milestone. Examples of protocol milestones: "INFORMED CONSENT OBTAINED", "RANDOMIZED". There are separate codelists used for DSDECOD where the choice depends on the value of DSCAT. Codelist "NCOMPLT" is used for disposition events, codelist "PROTMLST" is used for protocol milestones, and codelist "OTHEVENT" is used for other events.

DS.DSCAT.label: Category for Disposition Event
DS.DSCAT.description: Used to define a category of related records.

DS.DSSCAT.label: Subcategory for Disposition Event
DS.DSSCAT.description: A further categorization of DSCAT (e.g., "STUDY PARTICIPATION", "STUDY TREATMENT" when DSCAT = "DISPOSITION EVENT"). The variable may be subject to controlled terminology for other categories of disposition event records.

DS.EPOCH.label: Epoch
DS.EPOCH.description: Epoch associated with the start date/time of the event.

DS.DSDTC.label: Date/Time of Collection
DS.DSDTC.description: Collection date and time of the disposition observation represented in ISO 8601 character format.

DS.DSSTDTC.label: Start Date/Time of Disposition Event
DS.DSSTDTC.description: Start date/time of the disposition event in ISO 8601 character format.

DS.DSDY.label: Study Day of Collection
DS.DSDY.description: Study day of collection of event relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.

DS.DSSTDY.label: Study Day of Start of Disposition Event
DS.DSSTDY.description: Study day of start of event relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.

DV.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
DV.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

DV.DVSEQ.label: Sequence Number
DV.DVSEQ.description: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

DV.DVSPID.label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
DV.DVSPID.description: Sponsor-defined reference number. May be preprinted on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: Line number on a CRF page.

DV.DVTERM.label: Protocol Deviation Term
DV.DVTERM.description: Verbatim name of the protocol deviation criterion. Example: "IVRS PROCESS DEVIATION - NO DOSE CALL PERFORMED". DVTERM values will map to the controlled terminology in DVDECOD (e.g., "TREATMENT DEVIATION").

DV.DVDECOD.label: Protocol Deviation Coded Term
DV.DVDECOD.description: Controlled terminology for the name of the protocol deviation. Examples: "SUBJECT NOT WITHDRAWN AS PER PROTOCOL", "SELECTION CRITERIA NOT MET", "EXCLUDED CONCOMITANT MEDICATION", "TREATMENT DEVIATION".

DV.DVCAT.label: Category for Protocol Deviation
DV.DVCAT.description: Category of the protocol deviation criterion.

DV.DVSCAT.label: Subcategory for Protocol Deviation
DV.DVSCAT.description: A further categorization of the protocol deviation.

DV.TAETORD.label: Planned Order of Element within Arm
DV.TAETORD.description: Number that gives the planned order of the element within the arm.

DV.EPOCH.label: Epoch
DV.EPOCH.description: Epoch associated with the start date/time of the deviation. Examples: "TREATMENT", "SCREENING", "FOLLOW-UP".

DV.DVSTDTC.label: Start Date/Time of Deviation
DV.DVSTDTC.description: Start date/time of deviation represented in ISO 8601 character format.

DV.DVENDTC.label: End Date/Time of Deviation
DV.DVENDTC.description: End date/time of deviation represented in ISO 8601 character format.

DV.DVSTDY.label: Study Day of Start of Deviation Event
DV.DVSTDY.description: Study day of start of event relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.

DV.DVENDY.label: Study Day of End of Deviation Event
DV.DVENDY.description: Study day of end of event relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC.

HO.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
HO.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

HO.HOSEQ.label: Sequence Number
HO.HOSEQ.description: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

HO.HOGRPID.label: Group ID
HO.HOGRPID.description: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

HO.HOREFID.label: Reference ID
HO.HOREFID.description: Internal or external healthcare encounter identifier.

HO.HOSPID.label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
HO.HOSPID.description: Sponsor-defined identifier. May be preprinted on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: Line number on a Healthcare Encounters CRF page.

HO.HOTERM.label: Healthcare Encounter Term
HO.HOTERM.description: Verbatim or preprinted CRF term for the healthcare encounter.

HO.HODECOD.label: Dictionary-Derived Term
HO.HODECOD.description: Dictionary or sponsor-defined derived text description of HOTERM or the modified topic variable (HOMODIFY).

HO.HOCAT.label: Category for Healthcare Encounter
HO.HOCAT.description: Used to define a category of topic-related values.

HO.HOSCAT.label: Subcategory for Healthcare Encounter
HO.HOSCAT.description: A further categorization of HOCAT values.

HO.HOPRESP.label: Pre-Specified Healthcare Encounter
HO.HOPRESP.description: A value of "Y" indicates that this healthcare encounter event was prespecified on the CRF. Values are null for spontaneously reported events (i.e., those collected as free-text verbatim terms).

HO.HOOCCUR.label: Healthcare Encounter Occurrence
