IS.ISORRESU.description: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for ISORRES. Examples: "Index Value", "gpELISA", "unit/mL".

IS.ISORNRLO.label: Reference Range Lower Limit in Orig Unit
IS.ISORNRLO.description: Lower end of reference range for continuous measurement in original units. Should be populated only for continuous results.

IS.ISORNRHI.label: Reference Range Upper Limit in Orig Unit
IS.ISORNRHI.description: Upper end of reference range for continuous measurement in original units. Should be populated only for continuous results.

IS.ISSTRESC.label: Character Result/Finding in Std Format
IS.ISSTRESC.description: Contains the result value for all findings copied or derived from ISORRES, in a standard format or in standard units. ISSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in ISSTRESN.

IS.ISSTRESN.label: Numeric Results/Findings in Std. Units
IS.ISSTRESN.description: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from ISSTRESC. ISSTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

IS.ISSTRESU.label: Standard Units
IS.ISSTRESU.description: Standardized units used for ISSTRESC and ISSTRESN. Examples: "Index Value", "gpELISA", "unit/mL".

IS.ISSTNRLO.label: Reference Range Lower Limit-Std Units
IS.ISSTNRLO.description: Lower end of reference range for continuous measurements for ISSTRESC/ISSTRESN in standardized units. Should be populated only for continuous results.

IS.ISSTNRHI.label: Reference Range Upper Limit-Std Units
IS.ISSTNRHI.description: Upper end of reference range for continuous measurements in standardized units. Should be populated only for continuous results.

IS.ISSTNRC.label: Reference Range for Char Rslt-Std Units
IS.ISSTNRC.description: For normal range values that are character in ordinal scale or if categorical ranges were supplied. Examples: "-1 to +1", "NEGATIVE TO TRACE".

IS.ISNRIND.label: Reference Range Indicator
IS.ISNRIND.description: Indicates where the value falls with respect to reference range defined by ISORNRLO and ISORNRHI, ISSTNRLO and ISSTNRHI, or by ISSTNRC. Examples: "NORMAL", "ABNORMAL", "HIGH", "LOW". \n Sponsors should specify in the study metadata (Comments column in the Define-XML document) whether ISNRIND refers to the original or standard reference ranges and results. \n Should not be used to indicate clinical significance.

IS.ISSTAT.label: Completion Status
IS.ISSTAT.description: Used to indicate a test was not done. Should be null if a result exists in ISORRES.

IS.ISREASND.label: Reason Not Done
IS.ISREASND.description: Describes why a measurement or test was not performed. Used in conjunction with ISSTAT when value is "NOT DONE".

IS.ISNAM.label: Vendor Name
IS.ISNAM.description: Name or identifier of the laboratory or vendor who provided the test results.

IS.ISSPEC.label: Specimen Type
IS.ISSPEC.description: Defines the types of specimen used for a measurement. Example: "SERUM".

IS.ISSPCCND.label: Specimen Condition
IS.ISSPCCND.description: Free or standardized text describing the condition of the specimen. Examples: "HEMOLYZED", "ICTERIC", "LIPEMIC".

IS.ISSPCUFL.label: Specimen Usability for the Test
IS.ISSPCUFL.description: Describes the usability of the specimen for the test. The value will be "N" if the specimen is not usable, and null if the specimen is usable.

IS.ISMETHOD.label: Method of Test or Examination
IS.ISMETHOD.description: Method of the test or examination. Examples: "ELISA", "ELISPOT".

IS.ISLOBXFL.label: Last Observation Before Exposure Flag
IS.ISLOBXFL.description: Operationally derived indicator used to identify the last non-missing value prior to RFXSTDTC. The value should be "Y" or null.

IS.ISBLFL.label: Baseline Flag
IS.ISBLFL.description: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. Should be "Y" or null. Note that ISBLFL is retained for backward compatibility. The authoritative baseline for statistical analysis is in an ADaM dataset.

IS.ISDRVFL.label: Derived Flag
IS.ISDRVFL.description: Used to indicate a derived record. The value should be "Y" or null. Examples of records that might be derived for the submission datasets include those that represent the average of other records, do not come from the CRF, or are not as originally received or collected. If ISDRVFL="Y", then ISORRES may be null, with ISSTRESC and (if numeric) ISSTRESN having the derived value.

IS.ISLLOQ.label: Lower Limit of Quantitation
IS.ISLLOQ.description: Indicates the lower limit of quantitation for an assay. Units will be those used for ISSTRESU.

IS.VISITNUM.label: Visit Number
IS.VISITNUM.description: Clinical encounter number. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

IS.VISIT.label: Visit Name
IS.VISIT.description: Protocol-defined description of a clinical encounter. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY.

IS.VISITDY.label: Planned Study Day of Visit
IS.VISITDY.description: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

IS.TAETORD.label: Planned Order of Element within Arm
IS.TAETORD.description: Number that gives the planned order of the element within the arm.

IS.EPOCH.label: Epoch
IS.EPOCH.description: Epoch associated with the start date/time of the observation, or the date/time of collection if start date/time is not collected.

IS.ISDTC.label: Date/Time of Collection
IS.ISDTC.description: Collection date and time of an observation.

IS.ISDY.label: Study Day of Visit/Collection/Exam
IS.ISDY.description: Actual study day of visit/collection/exam expressed in integer days relative to sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics.

IS.ISENDY.label: Study Day of End of Specimen Collection
IS.ISENDY.description: Actual study day of end of observation expressed in integer days relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics.

IS.ISTPT.label: Planned Time Point Name
IS.ISTPT.description: Text description of time when specimen should be taken. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point, such as time of last dose. See ISTPTNUM and ISTPTREF. Examples: "Start", "5 min post".

IS.ISTPTNUM.label: Planned Time Point Number
IS.ISTPTNUM.description: Numerical version of ISTPT to aid in sorting.

IS.ISELTM.label: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
IS.ISELTM.description: Planned elapsed time (in ISO 8601) relative to a planned fixed reference (ISTPTREF). This variable is useful where there are repetitive measures. Not a clock time or a date/time variable. Represented as ISO 8601 duration. Examples: "-PT15M" to represent the period of 15 minutes prior to the reference point indicated by ISTPTREF, "PT8H" to represent the period of 8 hours after the reference point indicated by ISTPTREF.

IS.ISTPTREF.label: Time Point Reference
IS.ISTPTREF.description: Name of the fixed reference point referred to by ISELTM, ISTPTNUM, and ISTPT. Examples: "PREVIOUS DOSE", "PREVIOUS MEAL".

IS.ISRFTDTC.label: Date/Time of Reference Time Point
IS.ISRFTDTC.description: Date/time of the reference time point, ISTPTREF.

LB.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
LB.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

LB.LBSEQ.label: Sequence Number
LB.LBSEQ.description: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

LB.LBGRPID.label: Group ID
LB.LBGRPID.description: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

LB.LBREFID.label: Specimen ID
LB.LBREFID.description: Internal or external specimen identifier. Example: specimen ID.

LB.LBSPID.label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
LB.LBSPID.description: Sponsor-defined reference number. May be preprinted on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: Line number on the Lab page.

LB.LBTESTCD.label: Lab Test or Examination Short Name
LB.LBTESTCD.description: Short name of the measurement, test, or examination described in LBTEST. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in LBTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST" is not valid). LBTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: "ALT", "LDH".

LB.LBTEST.label: Lab Test or Examination Name
LB.LBTEST.description: Verbatim name of the test or examination used to obtain the measurement or finding. Note: Any test normally performed by a clinical laboratory is considered a lab test. The value in LBTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: "Alanine Aminotransferase", "Lactate Dehydrogenase".

LB.LBTSTCND.label: Test Condition
LB.LBTSTCND.description: Identifies any planned condition imposed by the assay system on the specimen at the time the test is performed.

LB.LBBDAGNT.label: Binding Agent
LB.LBBDAGNT.description: The textual description of the agent that is binding to the entity in the LBTEST variable. The LBBDAGNT variable is used to indicate that there is a binding relationship between the entities in the LBTEST and LBBDAGNT variables, regardless of direction. \n LBBDAGNT is not a method qualifier. It should only be used when the actual interest of the measurement is the binding interaction between the 2 entities in LBTEST and LBBDAGNT. In other words, the combination of LBTEST and LBBDAGNT should describe the thing, the entity, or the analyte being measured, without the need for additional variables. \n The binding agent may be (but is not limited to) a test article, a portion of the test article, a related compound, or an endogenous molecule.

LB.LBTSTOPO.label: Test Operational Objective
LB.LBTSTOPO.description: Text description of the high-level purpose of the test at the operational level.

LB.LBCAT.label: Category for Lab Test
LB.LBCAT.description: Used to define a category of related records across subjects. Examples: "HEMATOLOGY", "URINALYSIS", "CHEMISTRY".

LB.LBSCAT.label: Subcategory for Lab Test
LB.LBSCAT.description: A further categorization of a test category. Examples: "DIFFERENTIAL", "COAGULATION", "LIVER FUNCTION", "ELECTROLYTES".

LB.LBORRES.label: Result or Finding in Original Units
LB.LBORRES.description: Result of the measurement or finding as originally received or collected.

LB.LBORRESU.label: Original Units
LB.LBORRESU.description: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for LBORRES. Example: "g/L".

LB.LBRESSCL.label: Result Scale
LB.LBRESSCL.description: Classifies the scale of the original result value; for example, whether the result is ordinal, nominal, quantitative, or narrative.

LB.LBRESTYP.label: Result Type
LB.LBRESTYP.description: Classifies the kind of result (i.e., property type) originally reported for the test. Examples include substance concentration, proportion, mass rate, and arbitrary concentration.

LB.LBCOLSRT.label: Collected Summary Result Type
LB.LBCOLSRT.description: Used to indicate the type of collected summary result. This includes source summary results collected on a CRF or provided by an external vendor (e.g., central lab). If the summary result is derived by the sponsor using individual source data records from SDTM, the derived summary result is represented in ADaM. If the summary result is produced and reported by the lab, the collected summary result is represented in SDTM.

LB.LBORNRLO.label: Reference Range Lower Limit in Orig Unit
LB.LBORNRLO.description: Lower end of reference range for continuous measurement in original units. Should be populated only for continuous results.

LB.LBORNRHI.label: Reference Range Upper Limit in Orig Unit
LB.LBORNRHI.description: Upper end of reference range for continuous measurement in original units. Should be populated only for continuous results.

LB.LBLLOD.label: Lower Limit of Detection
LB.LBLLOD.description: The lowest threshold (as originally received or collected) for reliably detecting the presence or absence of substance measured by a specific test. The value for the field will be as described in documentation from the instrument or lab vendor.

LB.LBSTRESC.label: Character Result/Finding in Std Format
LB.LBSTRESC.description: Contains the result value for all findings, copied or derived from LBORRES in a standard format or standard units. LBSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in LBSTRESN. For example, if a test has results "NONE", "NEG", and "NEGATIVE" in LBORRES and these results effectively have the same meaning, they could be represented in standard format in LBSTRESC as "NEGATIVE". For other examples, see Original and Standardized Results.

LB.LBSTRESN.label: Numeric Result/Finding in Standard Units
LB.LBSTRESN.description: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from LBSTRESC. LBSTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

LB.LBSTRESU.label: Standard Units
LB.LBSTRESU.description: Standardized unit used for LBSTRESC or LBSTRESN.

LB.LBSTNRLO.label: Reference Range Lower Limit-Std Units
LB.LBSTNRLO.description: Lower end of reference range for continuous measurements for LBSTRESC/LBSTRESN in standardized units. Should be populated only for continuous results.

LB.LBSTNRHI.label: Reference Range Upper Limit-Std Units
LB.LBSTNRHI.description: Upper end of reference range for continuous measurements in standardized units. Should be populated only for continuous results.

LB.LBSTNRC.label: Reference Range for Char Rslt-Std Units
LB.LBSTNRC.description: For normal range values that are character in ordinal scale or if categorical ranges were supplied. Examples: "-1 to +1", "NEGATIVE TO TRACE".

LB.LBNRIND.label: Reference Range Indicator
LB.LBNRIND.description: Indicates where the value falls with respect to reference range defined by LBORNRLO and LBORNRHI, LBSTNRLO and LBSTNRHI, or by LBSTNRC. Examples: "NORMAL", "ABNORMAL", "HIGH", "LOW". Sponsors should specify in the study metadata (Comments column in the Define-XML document) whether LBNRIND refers to the original or standard reference ranges and results. LBNRIND is not used to indicate clinical significance.

LB.LBSTAT.label: Completion Status
LB.LBSTAT.description: Used to indicate exam not done. Should be null if a result exists in LBORRES.

LB.LBREASND.label: Reason Test Not Done
LB.LBREASND.description: Describes why a measurement or test was not performed. Examples: "BROKEN EQUIPMENT", "SUBJECT REFUSED", or "SPECIMEN LOST". Used in conjunction with LBSTAT when value is "NOT DONE".

LB.LBNAM.label: Vendor Name
LB.LBNAM.description: The name or identifier of the laboratory that performed the test.

LB.LBLOINC.label: LOINC Code
LB.LBLOINC.description: Code for the lab test from the LOINC code system. The sponsor is expected to provide the dictionary name and version used to map the terms utilizing the Define-XML external codelist attributes.

LB.LBSPEC.label: Specimen Type
LB.LBSPEC.description: Defines the type of specimen used for a measurement. Examples: "SERUM", "PLASMA", "URINE".

LB.LBSPCCND.label: Specimen Condition
LB.LBSPCCND.description: The physical state or quality of a sample for an assessment. Examples: "HEMOLYZED", "ICTERIC", "LIPEMIC".

LB.LBSPCUFL.label: Specimen Usability for the Test
LB.LBSPCUFL.description: Describes the usability of the specimen for the test. The value will be "N" if the specimen is not usable, and null if the specimen is usable.

LB.LBMETHOD.label: Method of Test or Examination
LB.LBMETHOD.description: Method of the test or examination. Examples: "EIA" (enzyme immunoassay), "ELECTROPHORESIS", "DIPSTICK".

LB.LBANMETH.label: Analysis Method
LB.LBANMETH.description: Analysis method applied to obtain a summarized result. Analysis method describes the method of secondary processing applied to a complex observation result (e.g., a calculation used to measure eGFR).

LB.LBTMTHSN.label: Test Method Sensitivity
LB.LBTMTHSN.description: The sensitivity of the test methodology with respect to observation, detection, or quantification.

LB.LBLOBXFL.label: Last Observation Before Exposure Flag
LB.LBLOBXFL.description: Operationally derived indicator used to identify the last non-missing value prior to RFXSTDTC. The value should be "Y" or null.

LB.LBBLFL.label: Baseline Flag
LB.LBBLFL.description: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. Should be "Y" or null. Note that LBBLFL is retained for backward compatibility. The authoritative baseline for statistical analysis is in an ADaM dataset.

LB.LBFAST.label: Fasting Status
LB.LBFAST.description: Indicator used to identify fasting status. Examples: "Y", "N".

LB.LBDRVFL.label: Derived Flag
LB.LBDRVFL.description: Used to indicate a derived record. The value should be "Y" or null. Records that represent the average of other records, or do not come from the CRF, or are not as originally received or collected are examples of records that might be derived for the submission datasets. If LBDRVFL="Y", then LBORRES may be null, with LBSTRESC and (if numeric) LBSTRESN having the derived value.

LB.LBTOX.label: Toxicity
LB.LBTOX.description: Description of toxicity quantified by LBTOXGR. The sponsor is expected to provide the name of the scale and version used to map the terms, utilizing the external codelist element in the Define-XML document.

LB.LBTOXGR.label: Standard Toxicity Grade
LB.LBTOXGR.description: Records toxicity grade value using a standard toxicity scale (e.g., the NCI CTCAE). If value is from a numeric scale, represent only the number (e.g., "2" not "Grade 2"). The sponsor is expected to provide the name of the scale and version used to map the terms, utilizing the external codelist element in the Define-XML document.

LB.LBCLSIG.label: Clinically Significant, Collected
LB.LBCLSIG.description: Used to indicate whether a collected observation is clinically significant based on judgment.

LB.VISITNUM.label: Visit Number
LB.VISITNUM.description: Clinical encounter number. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

LB.VISIT.label: Visit Name
LB.VISIT.description: Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY.

LB.VISITDY.label: Planned Study Day of Visit
LB.VISITDY.description: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

LB.TAETORD.label: Planned Order of Element within Arm
LB.TAETORD.description: Number that gives the planned order of the element within the arm.

LB.EPOCH.label: Epoch
LB.EPOCH.description: Epoch associated with the start date/time of the observation, or the date/time of collection if start date/time is not collected.

LB.LBDTC.label: Date/Time of Specimen Collection
LB.LBDTC.description: Date/time of specimen collection represented in ISO 8601 character format.

LB.LBENDTC.label: End Date/Time of Specimen Collection
LB.LBENDTC.description: End date/time of specimen collection represented in ISO 8601 character format.

LB.LBDY.label: Study Day of Specimen Collection
LB.LBDY.description: Study day of specimen collection, measured as integer days. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics. This formula should be consistent across the submission.

LB.LBENDY.label: Study Day of End of Observation
LB.LBENDY.description: Actual study day of end of observation expressed in integer days relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics.

LB.LBTPT.label: Planned Time Point Name
LB.LBTPT.description: Text description of time when specimen should be taken. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point, such as time of last dose. See LBTPTNUM and LBTPTREF. Examples: "Start", "5 min post".

LB.LBTPTNUM.label: Planned Time Point Number
LB.LBTPTNUM.description: Numerical version of LBTPT to aid in sorting.

LB.LBELTM.label: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
LB.LBELTM.description: Planned elapsed time (in ISO 8601) relative to a planned fixed reference (LBTPTREF). This variable is useful where there are repetitive measures. Not a clock time or a date/time variable. Represented as ISO 8601 duration. Examples: "-PT15M" to represent the period of 15 minutes prior to the reference point indicated by LBTPTREF, "PT8H" to represent the period of 8 hours after the reference point indicated by LBTPTREF.

LB.LBTPTREF.label: Time Point Reference
LB.LBTPTREF.description: Name of the fixed reference point referred to by LBELTM, LBTPTNUM, and LBTPT. Examples: "PREVIOUS DOSE", "PREVIOUS MEAL".

LB.LBRFTDTC.label: Date/Time of Reference Time Point
LB.LBRFTDTC.description: Date/time of the reference time point, LBTPTREF.

LB.LBPTFL.label: Point in Time Flag
LB.LBPTFL.description: An indication that the specimen was collected at a single point in time. The value is "Y" or null. The intent of this variable in the LB domain is to aid mapping to LOINC codes in the dataset, when LOINC part "Time Aspect" = "Pt".

LB.LBPDUR.label: Planned Duration
LB.LBPDUR.description: Planned duration of specimen collection. If LBPTFL is "Y" then LBPDUR is null.

MB.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
MB.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

MB.FOCID.label: Focus of Study-Specific Interest
MB.FOCID.description: Identification of a focus of study-specific interest on or within a subject or specimen as called out in the protocol for which a measurement, test, or examination was performed. The value in this variable should have inherent semantic meaning.

MB.MBSEQ.label: Sequence Number
MB.MBSEQ.description: Sequence number to ensure uniqueness of records within a dataset for a subject. May be any valid number.

MB.MBGRPID.label: Group ID
MB.MBGRPID.description: Optional group identifier, used to link together a block of related records within a subject in a domain.

MB.MBREFID.label: Reference ID
MB.MBREFID.description: Internal or external specimen identifier (e.g., sample ID for a subject sample from which a microbial culture was generated).

MB.MBSPID.label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
MB.MBSPID.description: Sponsor-defined reference number. May be preprinted on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database.

MB.MBLNKID.label: Link ID
MB.MBLNKID.description: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This may be a one-to-one or a one-to-many relationship. For example, it may be used to link genetic findings (in the PF domain) about a microbe to the original culture of that microbe (in MB), or to susceptibility records (in MS) if needed.

MB.MBLNKGRP.label: Link Group ID
MB.MBLNKGRP.description: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This will usually be a many-to-one relationship.

MB.MBTESTCD.label: Microbiology Test or Finding Short Name
MB.MBTESTCD.description: Short name of the measurement, test, or finding described in MBTEST. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in MBTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST" is not valid). MBTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: "MCORGIDN" for Microbial Organism Identification "GMNCOC" for Gram Negative Cocci.

MB.MBTEST.label: Microbiology Test or Finding Name
MB.MBTEST.description: Verbatim name of the test or examination used to obtain the measurement or finding. The value in MBTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: "Microbial Organism Identification", "Gram Negative Cocci", "HIV-1 RNA".

MB.MBTSTDTL.label: Measurement, Test or Examination Detail
MB.MBTSTDTL.description: Further description of MBTESTCD and MBTEST. Example: "VIRAL LOAD" when MBTESTCD represents viral genetic material, such as "HCRNA", "QUANTIFICATION" when MBTESTCD represents any organism being quantified.

MB.MBCAT.label: Category
MB.MBCAT.description: Used to define a category of related records.

MB.MBSCAT.label: Subcategory
MB.MBSCAT.description: Used to define a further categorization of MBCAT values.

MB.MBORRES.label: Result or Finding in Original Units
MB.MBORRES.description: Result of the microbiology measurement or finding as originally received or collected. Examples for "GRAM STAIN" findings: "+3 MODERATE", "+2 FEW", "<10". Examples for "CULTURE PLATE" findings: "KLEBSIELLA PNEUMONIAE", "STREPTOCOCCUS PNEUMONIAE".

MB.MBSTRESC.label: Result or Finding in Standard Format
MB.MBSTRESC.description: Contains the result value for all findings copied or derived from MBORRES, in a standard format or standard units. MBSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in MBSTRESN. For example, if a test has results "+3 MODERATE", "MOD", and "MODERATE" in MBORRES and these results effectively have the same meaning, they could be represented in standard format in MBSTRESC as "MODERATE".

MB.MBSTRESN.label: Numeric Result/Finding in Standard Units
MB.MBSTRESN.description: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from MBSTRESC. MBSTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

MB.MBSTRESU.label: Standard Units
MB.MBSTRESU.description: Standardized units used for MBSTRESC and MBSTRESN.

MB.MBRESCAT.label: Result Category
MB.MBRESCAT.description: Used to categorize the result of a finding in a standard format.

MB.MBSTAT.label: Completion Status
MB.MBSTAT.description: Used to indicate that a question was not asked or a test was not done, or that a test was attempted but did not generate a result. Should be null or have a value of "NOT DONE".

MB.MBREASND.label: Reason Not Done
MB.MBREASND.description: Reason not done. Used in conjunction with MBSTAT when value is NOT DONE. Examples: "BROKEN EQUIPMENT", "SUBJECT REFUSED".

MB.MBNAM.label: Laboratory/Vendor Name
MB.MBNAM.description: Name or identifier of the vendor (e.g., laboratory) that provided the test results.

MB.MBLOINC.label: LOINC Code
MB.MBLOINC.description: Logical Observation Identifiers Names and Codes (LOINC) code for the topic variable (e.g., lab test).

MB.MBSPEC.label: Specimen Material Type
MB.MBSPEC.description: Defines the type of specimen used for a measurement. Examples: "SPUTUM", "BLOOD", "PUS".

MB.MBSPCCND.label: Specimen Condition
MB.MBSPCCND.description: Free or standardized text describing the condition of the specimen. Example: "CONTAMINATED".

MB.MBLOC.label: Specimen Collection Location
MB.MBLOC.description: Anatomical location relevant to the collection of the measurement.

MB.MBLAT.label: Laterality
MB.MBLAT.description: Qualifier for specimen collection location further detailing laterality. Examples: "RIGHT", "LEFT", "BILATERAL".

MB.MBDIR.label: Directionality
MB.MBDIR.description: Qualifier for specimen collection location further detailing directionality. Examples: "ANTERIOR", "LOWER", "PROXIMAL".

MB.MBMETHOD.label: Method of Test or Examination
MB.MBMETHOD.description: Method of the test or examination. Examples: "GRAM STAIN", "MICROBIAL CULTURE, LIQUID", "QUANTITATIVE REVERSE TRANSCRIPTASE POLYMERASE CHAIN REACTION".

MB.MBLOBXFL.label: Last Observation Before Exposure Flag
MB.MBLOBXFL.description: Operationally derived indicator used to identify the last non-missing value prior to RFXSTDTC. The value should be "Y" or null.

MB.MBBLFL.label: Baseline Flag
MB.MBBLFL.description: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. Should be "Y" or null. Note that MBBLFL is retained for backward compatibility. The authoritative baseline for statistical analysis is in an ADaM dataset.

MB.MBFAST.label: Fasting Status
MB.MBFAST.description: Indicator used to identify fasting status. Valid values include "Y", "N", "U", or null if not relevant.

MB.MBDRVFL.label: Derived Flag
MB.MBDRVFL.description: Used to indicate a derived record (e.g., a record that represents the average of other records such as a computed baseline). Should be "Y" or null.

MB.VISITNUM.label: Visit Number
MB.VISITNUM.description: Clinical encounter number. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

MB.VISIT.label: Visit Name
MB.VISIT.description: Protocol-defined description of a clinical encounter.

MB.VISITDY.label: Planned Study Day of Visit
MB.VISITDY.description: Planned study day of VISIT. Should be an integer.

MB.TAETORD.label: Planned Order of Element within Arm
MB.TAETORD.description: Number that gives the planned order of the element within the arm for the element which the specimen collection occurred.

MB.EPOCH.label: Epoch
MB.EPOCH.description: Epoch associated with the date/time at which the specimen was collected.

MB.MBDY.label: Study Day of Visit/Collection/Exam
MB.MBDY.description: Study day of the specimen collection, measured as integer days. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics. This formula should be consistent across the submission.

MB.MBTPT.label: Planned Time Point Name
MB.MBTPT.description: Text description of time when specimen should be taken. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point, such as time of last dose. See MBTPTNUM and MBTPTREF. Examples: "Start", "5 min post".

MB.MBTPTNUM.label: Planned Time Point Number
MB.MBTPTNUM.description: Numeric version of MBTPT used in sorting.

MB.MBELTM.label: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
MB.MBELTM.description: Planned elapsed time (in ISO 8601) relative to a planned fixed reference (MBTPTREF). This variable is useful where there are repetitive measures. Not a clock time or a date time variable. Represented as an ISO 8601 duration. Examples: "-PT15M" to represent the period of 15 minutes prior to the reference point indicated by MBTPTREF, or "PT8H" to represent the period of 8 hours after the reference point indicated by MBTPTREF.

MB.MBTPTREF.label: Time Point Reference
MB.MBTPTREF.description: Name of the fixed reference point referred to by MBELTM, MBTPTNUM, and MBTPT. Example: "PREVIOUS DOSE".

MB.MBRFTDTC.label: Date/Time of Reference Time Point
MB.MBRFTDTC.description: Date/time for a fixed reference time point, MBTPTREF.

MI.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
MI.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

MI.MISEQ.label: Sequence Number
MI.MISEQ.description: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

MI.MIGRPID.label: Group ID
MI.MIGRPID.description: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject. This is not the treatment group number.

MI.MIREFID.label: Reference ID
MI.MIREFID.description: Internal or external specimen identifier. Example: specimen barcode number.

MI.MISPID.label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
MI.MISPID.description: Sponsor-defined reference number. May be printed on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: line number from the MI Findings page.

MI.MITESTCD.label: Microscopic Examination Short Name
MI.MITESTCD.description: Short name of the measurement, test, or examination described in MITEST. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in MITESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST" is not valid). MITESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: "HER2", "BRCA1", "TTF1".

MI.MITEST.label: Microscopic Examination Name
MI.MITEST.description: Verbatim name of the test or examination used to obtain the measurement or finding. The value in MITEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: "Human Epidermal Growth Factor Receptor 2", "Breast Cancer Susceptibility Gene 1", "Thyroid Transcription Factor 1".

MI.MITSTDTL.label: Microscopic Examination Detail
MI.MITSTDTL.description: Further description of the test performed in producing the MI result. This would be used to represent specific attributes, such as intensity score or percentage of cells displaying presence of the biomarker or compound.

MI.MICAT.label: Category for Microscopic Finding
MI.MICAT.description: Used to define a category of related records.

MI.MISCAT.label: Subcategory for Microscopic Finding
MI.MISCAT.description: Used to define a further categorization of MICAT.

MI.MIORRES.label: Result or Finding in Original Units
MI.MIORRES.description: Result of the histopathology measurement or finding as originally received or collected.

MI.MISTRESC.label: Character Result/Finding in Std Format
MI.MISTRESC.description: Contains the result value for all findings, copied or derived from MIORRES in a standard format or standard units. MISTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in MISTRESN.

MI.MISTRESN.label: Numeric Result/Finding in Standard Units
MI.MISTRESN.description: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from MISTRESC. MISTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

MI.MISTRESU.label: Standard Units
MI.MISTRESU.description: Standardized unit used for MISTRESC and MISTRESN.

MI.MIRESCAT.label: Result Category
MI.MIRESCAT.description: Used to categorize the result of a finding. Examples: "MALIGNANT" or "BENIGN" for tumor findings.

MI.MISTAT.label: Completion Status
MI.MISTAT.description: Used to indicate examination not done or result is missing. Should be null if a result exists in MIORRES or have a value of "NOT DONE" when MIORRES = "NULL".

MI.MIREASND.label: Reason Not Done
MI.MIREASND.description: Reason not done. Used in conjunction with MISTAT when value is NOT DONE. Examples: "SAMPLE AUTOLYZED", "SPECIMEN LOST".

MI.MINAM.label: Laboratory/Vendor Name
MI.MINAM.description: Name or identifier of the vendor (e.g., laboratory) that provided the test results.

MI.MISPEC.label: Specimen Material Type
MI.MISPEC.description: Subject of the observation. Defines the type of specimen used for a measurement. Examples: "TISSUE", "BLOOD", "BONE MARROW".

MI.MISPCCND.label: Specimen Condition
MI.MISPCCND.description: Free or standardized text describing the condition of the specimen. Example: "AUTOLYZED".

MI.MILOC.label: Specimen Collection Location
MI.MILOC.description: Location relevant to the collection of the specimen. Examples: "LUNG", "KNEE JOINT", "ARM", "THIGH".

MI.MILAT.label: Specimen Laterality within Subject
MI.MILAT.description: Qualifier for laterality of the location of the specimen in MILOC. Examples: "LEFT", "RIGHT", "BILATERAL".

MI.MIDIR.label: Specimen Directionality within Subject
MI.MIDIR.description: Qualifier for directionality of the location of the specimen in MILOC. Examples: "DORSAL", "PROXIMAL".

MI.MIMETHOD.label: Method of Test or Examination
MI.MIMETHOD.description: Method of the test or examination. This could include the technique or type of staining used for the slides. Examples: "IHC", "Crystal violet", "Safranin", "Trypan blue", or "Propidium iodide".

MI.MILOBXFL.label: Last Observation Before Exposure Flag
MI.MILOBXFL.description: Operationally derived indicator used to identify the last non-missing value prior to RFXSTDTC. The value should be "Y" or null.

MI.MIBLFL.label: Baseline Flag
MI.MIBLFL.description: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. The value should be "Y" or null. Note that MIBLFL is retained for backward compatibility. The authoritative baseline flag for statistical analysis is in an ADaM dataset.

MI.MIEVAL.label: Evaluator
MI.MIEVAL.description: Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Example: "PATHOLOGIST", "PEER REVIEW", "SPONSOR PATHOLOGIST".

MI.VISITNUM.label: Visit Number
MI.VISITNUM.description: Clinical encounter number. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

MI.VISIT.label: Visit Name
MI.VISIT.description: Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY.

MI.VISITDY.label: Planned Study Day of Visit
MI.VISITDY.description: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

MI.TAETORD.label: Planned Order of Element within Arm
MI.TAETORD.description: Number that gives the planned order of the element within the arm for the element in which the assessment was made.

MI.EPOCH.label: Epoch
MI.EPOCH.description: Epoch associated with the date/time at which the specimen was collected.

MI.MIDTC.label: Date/Time of Specimen Collection
MI.MIDTC.description: Date/time of specimen collection, in ISO 8601 format.

MI.MIDY.label: Study Day of Specimen Collection
MI.MIDY.description: Study day of specimen collection, in integer days. The algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in the Demographics (DM) domain.

MK.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
MK.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

MK.MKSEQ.label: Sequence Number
MK.MKSEQ.description: Sequence number to ensure uniqueness of records within a dataset for a subject (or within a parameter, in the case of the Trial Summary domain). May be any valid number (including decimals) and does not have to start at 1.

MK.MKGRPID.label: Group ID
MK.MKGRPID.description: Used to link together a block of related records within a subject in a domain.

MK.MKREFID.label: Reference ID
MK.MKREFID.description: Optional internal or external identifier such as lab specimen ID or a medical image.

MK.MKSPID.label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
MK.MKSPID.description: Sponsor-defined identifier. Example: Preprinted line identifier on a Concomitant Medications page.

MK.MKLNKID.label: Link ID
MK.MKLNKID.description: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This may be a one-to-one or a one-to-many relationship.

MK.MKLNKGRP.label: Link Group ID
MK.MKLNKGRP.description: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This will usually be a many-to-one relationship.

MK.MKTESTCD.label: Short Name of Musculoskeletal Test
MK.MKTESTCD.description: Short character value for MKTEST used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical format to a horizontal format. The value in MKTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST" is not valid). MKTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: "TNDRIND", "SWLLIND", "SGJSNSCR".

MK.MKTEST.label: Name of Musculoskeletal Test
MK.MKTEST.description: Long name For MKTESTCD. Examples: "Tenderness Indicator", "Swollen Indicator", "Sharp/Genant JSN Score".

MK.MKCAT.label: Category for Musculoskeletal Test
MK.MKCAT.description: Used to define a category of topic-variable values. Examples: "SWOLLEN/TENDER JOINT ASSESSMENT".

MK.MKSCAT.label: Subcategory for Musculoskeletal Test
MK.MKSCAT.description: Used to define a further categorization of MKCAT values.

MK.MKPOS.label: Position of Subject
MK.MKPOS.description: Position of the subject during a measurement or examination. Examples: "SUPINE", "STANDING", "SITTING".

MK.MKORRES.label: Result or Finding in Original Units
MK.MKORRES.description: Result of the measurement or finding as originally received or collected.

MK.MKSTRESC.label: Character Result/Finding in Std Format
MK.MKSTRESC.description: Contains the result value for all findings, copied or derived from MKORRES in a standard format or in standard units. MKSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in MKSTRESN. For example, if various tests have results "NONE", "NEG", and "NEGATIVE" in MKORRES and these results effectively have the same meaning, they could be represented in standard format in MKSTRESC as "NEGATIVE".

MK.MKSTRESN.label: Numeric Result/Finding in Standard Units
MK.MKSTRESN.description: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from MKSTRESC. MKSTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

MK.MKSTRESU.label: Standard Units
MK.MKSTRESU.description: Standardized units used for MKSTRESC and MKSTRESN.

MK.MKSTAT.label: Completion Status
MK.MKSTAT.description: Used to indicate that a question was not asked or a test was not done, or that a test was attempted but did not generate a result. Should be null if a result exists in MKORRES.

MK.MKREASND.label: Reason Not Done
MK.MKREASND.description: Reason not done. Used in conjunction with MKSTAT when value is "NOT DONE".

MK.MKLOC.label: Location Used for the Measurement
MK.MKLOC.description: Anatomical location of the subject relevant to the collection of the measurement. Examples: "INTERPHALANGEAL JOINT 1", "SHOULDER JOINT".

MK.MKLAT.label: Laterality
MK.MKLAT.description: Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing laterality. Examples: "RIGHT", "LEFT", "BILATERAL".

MK.MKDIR.label: Directionality
MK.MKDIR.description: Qualifier for anatomical location further detailing directionality. Examples: "ANTERIOR", "LOWER", "PROXIMAL".

MK.MKMETHOD.label: Method of Test or Examination
MK.MKMETHOD.description: Method of the test or examination. Examples: "X-RAY", "MRI", "CT SCAN".

MK.MKLOBXFL.label: Last Observation Before Exposure Flag
MK.MKLOBXFL.description: Operationally derived indicator used to identify the last non-missing value prior to RFXSTDTC. The value should be "Y" or null.

MK.MKBLFL.label: Baseline Flag
MK.MKBLFL.description: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. Should be "Y" or null. Note that MKBLFL is retained for backward compatibility. The authoritative baseline for statistical analysis is in an ADaM dataset.

MK.MKDRVFL.label: Derived Flag
MK.MKDRVFL.description: Used to indicate a derived record (e.g., a record that represents the average of other records such as a computed baseline). Should be "Y" or null.

MK.MKEVAL.label: Evaluator
MK.MKEVAL.description: Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Used only for results that are subjective (e.g., assigned by a person or a group). Examples: "ADJUDICATION COMMITTEE", "INDEPENDENT ASSESSOR", "RADIOLOGIST".

MK.MKEVALID.label: Evaluator Identifier
MK.MKEVALID.description: Used to distinguish multiple evaluators with the same role recorded in MKEVAL. Examples: "RADIOLOGIST1" or "RADIOLOGIST2".

MK.VISITNUM.label: Visit Number
MK.VISITNUM.description: Clinical encounter number. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

MK.VISIT.label: Visit Name
MK.VISIT.description: Protocol-defined description of a clinical encounter.

MK.VISITDY.label: Planned Study Day of Visit
MK.VISITDY.description: Planned study day of VISIT. Should be an integer.

MK.TAETORD.label: Planned Order of Element within Arm
MK.TAETORD.description: Number that gives the planned order of the element within the arm for the element in which the assessment was made.

MK.EPOCH.label: Epoch
MK.EPOCH.description: Epoch associated with the date/time at which the assessment was made.

MK.MKDTC.label: Date/Time of Collection
MK.MKDTC.description: Collection date and time of an observation.

MK.MKDY.label: Study Day of Visit/Collection/Exam
MK.MKDY.description: Actual study day of visit/collection/exam expressed in integer days relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics.

MK.MKTPT.label: Planned Time Point Name
MK.MKTPT.description: Text description of time when a measurement or observation should be taken as defined in the protocol. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point, such as time of last dose. See MKTPTNUM and MKTPTREF.

MK.MKTPTNUM.label: Planned Time Point Number
MK.MKTPTNUM.description: Numeric version of planned time point used in sorting.

MK.MKELTM.label: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
MK.MKELTM.description: Planned Elapsed time relative to a planned fixed reference (MKTPTREF; e.g., "PREVIOUS DOSE", "PREVIOUS MEAL"). This variable is useful where there are repetitive measures. Not a clock time or a date/time variable, but an interval, represented as ISO duration.

MK.MKTPTREF.label: Time Point Reference
MK.MKTPTREF.description: Description of the fixed reference point referred to by MKELTM, MKTPTNUM, and MKTPT. Examples: "PREVIOUS DOSE", "PREVIOUS MEAL".

MK.MKRFTDTC.label: Date/Time of Reference Time Point
MK.MKRFTDTC.description: Date/time for a fixed reference time point defined by MKTPTREF.

MS.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
MS.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

MS.NHOID.label: Non-host Organism ID
MS.NHOID.description: Sponsor-defined identifier for a non-host organism which should only be used when the organism is the subject of the TEST. This variable should be populated with an intuitive name based on the identity of the non-host organism as reported by a lab (e.g., "A/California/7/2009 (H1N1)"). It is not to be used as a qualifier of the result in the record on which it appears.

MS.MSSEQ.label: Sequence Number
MS.MSSEQ.description: Sequence number to ensure uniqueness of records within a dataset for a subject (or within a parameter, in the case of the Trial Summary domain). May be any valid number (including decimals) and does not have to start at 1.

MS.MSGRPID.label: Group ID
MS.MSGRPID.description: Optional group identifier, used to link together a block of related records within a subject in a domain. In SDTMIG v3.2 this was an Expected variable. In this version, the core designation has been changed to Permissible.

MS.MSREFID.label: Reference ID
MS.MSREFID.description: Optional internal or external identifier (e.g., an identifier for the culture/isolate being tested for susceptibility).

MS.MSSPID.label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
MS.MSSPID.description: Sponsor-defined reference number. May be preprinted on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database.

MS.MSLNKID.label: Link ID
MS.MSLNKID.description: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This may be a one-to-one or a one-to-many relationship. For example, it may be used to link genetic findings (in the PF domain) about a microbe to the original culture of that microbe (in MB), or to susceptibility records (in MS) if needed.

MS.MSTESTCD.label: Short Name of Assessment
MS.MSTESTCD.description: Short character value for MSTEST used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical format to a horizontal format. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in MSTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST" is not valid). MSTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: "MIC" for Minimum Inhibitory Concentration; "MICROSUS" for Microbial Susceptibility.

MS.MSTEST.label: Name of Assessment
MS.MSTEST.description: Verbatim name of the test or examination used to obtain the measurement or finding. The value in MSTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: "Minimum Inhibitory Concentration", "Microbial Susceptibility".

MS.MSAGENT.label: Agent Name
MS.MSAGENT.description: The name of the agent for which resistance is tested. The agent specified may be based on genetic markers or direct phenotypic drug sensitivity testing. Examples: "Penicillin", name of study drug.

MS.MSCONC.label: Agent Concentration
MS.MSCONC.description: Numeric concentration of agent listed in MSAGENT.

MS.MSCONCU.label: Agent Concentration Units
MS.MSCONCU.description: Units for value of the agent concentration listed in MSCONC. Example: "mg/L".

MS.MSTSTDTL.label: Measurement, Test or Examination Detail
MS.MSTSTDTL.description: Further description of MSTESTCD and MSTEST.

MS.MSCAT.label: Category
MS.MSCAT.description: Used to define a category of MSTEST values.

MS.MSSCAT.label: Subcategory
MS.MSSCAT.description: Used to define a further categorization of MSCAT values.

MS.MSORRES.label: Result or Finding in Original Units
MS.MSORRES.description: Result of the measurement or finding as originally received or collected.

MS.MSSTRESC.label: Result or Finding in Standard Format
MS.MSSTRESC.description: Contains the result value for all findings, copied or derived from MSORRES in a standard format or in standard units. MSSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in MSSTRESN. For example, if various tests have results "NONE", "NEG", and "NEGATIVE" in MSORRES and these results effectively have the same meaning, they could be represented in standard format in MSSTRESC as "NEGATIVE".

MS.MSSTRESN.label: Numeric Result/Finding in Standard Units
MS.MSSTRESN.description: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from MSSTRESC. MSSTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

MS.MSSTRESU.label: Standard Units
MS.MSSTRESU.description: Standardized units used for MSSTRESC and MSSTRESN. Example: "mol/L".

MS.MSNRIND.label: Normal/Reference Range Indicator
MS.MSNRIND.description: Used to indicate the value is outside the normal range or reference range. May be defined by MSORNRLO and MSORNRHI or other objective criteria. Examples: "Y", "N", "HIGH", "LOW", "NORMAL". "ABNORMAL".

MS.MSRESCAT.label: Result Category
MS.MSRESCAT.description: Used to categorize the result of a finding. In SDTMIG v3.2, MSRESCAT was used to categorize a numeric susceptibility result represented in MSORRES as either "SUSCEPTIBLE", "INTERMEDIATE", or "RESISTANT". However, results from some susceptibility tests may report only a categorical result and not a numeric result. Thus, in order for susceptibility results to be represented consistently, MSRESCAT should no longer be used for this purpose. In this version, the core designation has been changed from Expected to Permissible.

MS.MSSTAT.label: Completion Status
MS.MSSTAT.description: Used to indicate that a question was not asked or a test was not done, or a test was attempted but did not generate a result. Should be null or have a value of "NOT DONE".

MS.MSREASND.label: Reason Not Done
MS.MSREASND.description: Reason not done. Used in conjunction with MSSTAT when value is "NOT DONE".

MS.MSNAM.label: Laboratory/Vendor Name
MS.MSNAM.description: Name or identifier of the vendor (e.g., laboratory) that provided the test results.

MS.MSLOINC.label: LOINC Code
MS.MSLOINC.description: Logical Observation Identifiers Names and Codes (LOINC) code for the topic variable such as a lab test.

MS.MSSPEC.label: Specimen Material Type
MS.MSSPEC.description: Defines the type of specimen used for a measurement. Example: "SPUTUM".

MS.MSSPCCND.label: Specimen Condition
MS.MSSPCCND.description: Defines the condition of the specimen. Example: "CLOUDY".

MS.MSLOC.label: Location Used for the Measurement
MS.MSLOC.description: Anatomical location of the subject relevant to the collection of the measurement.

MS.MSLAT.label: Laterality
MS.MSLAT.description: Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing laterality. Examples: "RIGHT", "LEFT", "BILATERAL".

MS.MSDIR.label: Directionality
MS.MSDIR.description: Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing directionality. Examples: "ANTERIOR", "LOWER", "PROXIMAL".

MS.MSMETHOD.label: Method of Test or Examination
MS.MSMETHOD.description: Method of the test or examination. Examples: "EPSILOMETER", "MACRO BROTH DILUTION".

MS.MSANMETH.label: Analysis Method
MS.MSANMETH.description: Analysis method applied to obtain a summarized result. Analysis method describes the method of secondary processing applied to a complex observation result (e.g., an image or a genetic sequence).

MS.MSLOBXFL.label: Last Observation Before Exposure Flag
MS.MSLOBXFL.description: Operationally derived indicator used to identify the last non-missing value prior to RFXSTDTC. The value should be "Y" or null.

MS.MSBLFL.label: Baseline Flag
MS.MSBLFL.description: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. Should be "Y" or null. Note that MSBLFL is retained for backward compatibility. The authoritative baseline for statistical analysis is in an ADaM dataset.

MS.MSFAST.label: Fasting Status
MS.MSFAST.description: Indicator used to identify fasting status. Valid values include "Y", "N", "U", or null if not relevant.

MS.MSDRVFL.label: Derived Flag
MS.MSDRVFL.description: Used to indicate a derived record (e.g., a record that represents the average of other records such as a computed baseline). Should be "Y" or null.

MS.MSEVAL.label: Evaluator
MS.MSEVAL.description: Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Used only for results that are subjective (e.g., assigned by a person or a group). Examples: "ADJUDICATION COMMITTEE", "INDEPENDENT ASSESSOR", "MICROSCOPIST".

MS.MSEVALID.label: Evaluator Identifier
MS.MSEVALID.description: Used to distinguish multiple evaluators with the same role recorded in MSEVAL. Examples: "RADIOLOGIST1" or "RADIOLOGIST2".

MS.MSACPTFL.label: Accepted Record Flag
MS.MSACPTFL.description: In cases where more than 1 assessor provides an evaluation of a result or response, this flag identifies the record that is considered, by an independent assessor, to be the accepted evaluation. Expected to be "Y" or null.

MS.MSLLOQ.label: Lower Limit of Quantitation
MS.MSLLOQ.description: Indicates the lower limit of quantitation for an assay. Units will be those used for MSSTRESU.

MS.MSULOQ.label: Upper Limit of Quantitation
MS.MSULOQ.description: Indicates the upper limit of quantitation for an assay. Units will be those used for MSSTRESU.

MS.MSREPNUM.label: Repetition Number
MS.MSREPNUM.description: The incidence number of a test that is repeated within a given timeframe for the same test. The level of granularity can vary (e.g., within a time point, within a visit). Examples: multiple measurements of blood pressure, multiple analyses of a sample.

MS.VISITNUM.label: Visit Number
MS.VISITNUM.description: Clinical encounter number. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

MS.VISIT.label: Visit Name
MS.VISIT.description: Protocol-defined description of a clinical encounter.

MS.VISITDY.label: Planned Study Day of Visit
MS.VISITDY.description: Planned study day of VISIT. Should be an integer.

MS.TAETORD.label: Planned Order of Element within Arm
MS.TAETORD.description: Number that gives the planned order of the element within the arm for the element in which the specimen was collected.

MS.EPOCH.label: Epoch
MS.EPOCH.description: Epoch associated with the date/time at which the specimen was collected.

MS.MSDTC.label: Date/Time of Collection
MS.MSDTC.description: Collection date and time of an observation.

MS.MSDY.label: Study Day of Visit/Collection/Exam
MS.MSDY.description: Actual study day of visit/collection/exam expressed in integer days relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics.

MS.MSDUR.label: Duration
MS.MSDUR.description: Collected duration of an event, intervention, or finding. Used only if collected on the CRF and not derived.

MS.MSTPT.label: Planned Time Point Name
MS.MSTPT.description: Text description of time when a measurement or observation should be taken as defined in the protocol. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point (e.g., time of last dose). See MSTPTNUM and MSTPTREF.

MS.MSTPTNUM.label: Planned Time Point Number
MS.MSTPTNUM.description: Numeric version of planned time point used in sorting.

MS.MSELTM.label: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
MS.MSELTM.description: Planned elapsed time relative to a planned fixed reference (MSTPTREF; e.g., previous dose, previous meal). This variable is useful where there are repetitive measures. Not a clock time or a date/time variable, but an interval, represented as ISO duration.

MS.MSTPTREF.label: Time Point Reference
MS.MSTPTREF.description: Description of the fixed reference point referred to by MSELTM, MSTPTNUM, and MSTPT. Example: "PREVIOUS DOSE".

MS.MSRFTDTC.label: Date/Time of Reference Time Point
MS.MSRFTDTC.description: Date/time for a fixed reference time point defined by MSTPTREF.

MS.MSEVLINT.label: Evaluation Interval
MS.MSEVLINT.description: Duration of interval associated with an observation such as a finding MSTESTCD. Example: "-P2M" to represent a period of the past 2 months before the assessment.

MS.MSEVINTX.label: Evaluation Interval Text
MS.MSEVINTX.description: Evaluation interval associated with an observation, where the interval is not able to be represented in ISO 8601 format. Examples: "LIFETIME", "LAST NIGHT", "RECENTLY", "OVER THE LAST FEW WEEKS".

NV.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
NV.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

NV.FOCID.label: Focus of Study-Specific Interest
NV.FOCID.description: Identification of a focus of study-specific interest on or within a subject or specimen as called out in the protocol for which a measurement, test, or examination was performed, such as a drug application site (e.g., "Injection site 1", "Biopsy site 1", "Treated site 1") or a more specific focus (e.g., "OD" (right eye), "Upper left quadrant of the back"). The value in this variable should have inherent semantic meaning.

NV.NVSEQ.label: Sequence Number
NV.NVSEQ.description: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

NV.NVGRPID.label: Group ID
NV.NVGRPID.description: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

NV.NVSPID.label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
NV.NVSPID.description: Sponsor-defined reference number. May be preprinted on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: Line number from the Procedure or Test page.

NV.NVLNKID.label: Link ID
NV.NVLNKID.description: Identifier used to link a procedure to the assessment results over the course of the study.

NV.NVLNKGRP.label: Link Group
NV.NVLNKGRP.description: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This will usually be a many-to-one relationship.

NV.NVTESTCD.label: Short Name of Nervous System Test
NV.NVTESTCD.description: Short name of the measurement, test, or examination described in NVTEST. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in NVTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST" is not valid). NVTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: "SUVR", "N75LAT", "P100LAT","N145LAT".

NV.NVTEST.label: Name of Nervous System Test
NV.NVTEST.description: Verbatim name of the test or examination used to obtain the measurement or finding. The value in NVTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: "Standard Uptake Value Ratio", "N75 Latency", "P100 Latency", "N145 Latency".

NV.NVCAT.label: Category for Nervous System Test
NV.NVCAT.description: Used to define a category of topic-variable values. Example: "VISUAL EVOKED POTENTIAL".

NV.NVSCAT.label: Subcategory for Nervous System Test
NV.NVSCAT.description: Used to define a further categorization of NVCAT values.

NV.NVORRES.label: Result or Finding in Original Units
NV.NVORRES.description: Result of the procedure measurement or finding as originally received or collected.

NV.NVORRESU.label: Original Units
NV.NVORRESU.description: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for NVORRES.

NV.NVSTRESC.label: Character Result/Finding in Std Format
NV.NVSTRESC.description: Contains the result value for all findings copied or derived from NVORRES, in a standard format or standard units. NVSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in NVSTRESN.

NV.NVSTRESN.label: Numeric Result/Finding in Standard Units
NV.NVSTRESN.description: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from NVSTRESC. NVSTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

NV.NVSTRESU.label: Standard Units
NV.NVSTRESU.description: Standardized unit used for NVSTRESC or NVSTRESN.

NV.NVSTAT.label: Completion Status
NV.NVSTAT.description: Used to indicate a test was not done, or a measurement was not taken. Should be null if a result exists in NVORRES.

NV.NVREASND.label: Reason Not Done
NV.NVREASND.description: Describes why a measurement or test was not performed. Examples: "BROKEN EQUIPMENT", "SUBJECT REFUSED". Used in conjunction with NVSTAT when value is "NOT DONE".

NV.NVLOC.label: Location Used for the Measurement
NV.NVLOC.description: Anatomical location of the subject relevant to the collection of the measurement. Examples: "BRAIN", "EYE", "PRECUNEUS", "CINGULATE CORTEX".

NV.NVLAT.label: Laterality
NV.NVLAT.description: Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing laterality. Examples: "RIGHT", "LEFT", "BILATERAL".

NV.NVDIR.label: Directionality
NV.NVDIR.description: Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing directionality. Examples: "ANTERIOR", "LOWER", "PROXIMAL".

NV.NVMETHOD.label: Method of Test or Examination
NV.NVMETHOD.description: Method of the test or examination. Examples: "EEG", "PET/CT SCAN ", "FDGPET".

NV.NVLOBXFL.label: Last Observation Before Exposure Flag
NV.NVLOBXFL.description: Operationally derived indicator used to identify the last non-missing value prior to RFXSTDTC. The value should be "Y" or null.

NV.NVBLFL.label: Baseline Flag
NV.NVBLFL.description: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. Should be "Y" or null. Note that NVBLFL is retained for backward compatibility. The authoritative baseline flag for statistical analysis is in an ADaM dataset.

NV.NVDRVFL.label: Derived Flag
NV.NVDRVFL.description: Used to indicate a derived record (e.g., a record that represents the average of other records such as a computed baseline). Should be "Y" or null.

NV.NVEVAL.label: Evaluator
NV.NVEVAL.description: Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Used only for results that are subjective (e.g., assigned by a person or a group). Examples: "ADJUDICATION COMMITTEE", "INDEPENDENT ASSESSOR", "RADIOLOGIST".

NV.NVEVALID.label: Evaluator Identifier
NV.NVEVALID.description: Used to distinguish multiple evaluators with the same role recorded in NVEVAL. Examples: "RADIOLOGIST 1", "RADIOLOGIST 2".

NV.VISITNUM.label: Visit Number
NV.VISITNUM.description: Clinical encounter number. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

NV.VISIT.label: Visit Name
NV.VISIT.description: Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY.

NV.VISITDY.label: Planned Study Day of Visit
NV.VISITDY.description: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

NV.TAETORD.label: Planned Order of Element within Arm
NV.TAETORD.description: Number that gives the planned order of the element within the arm for the element in which the assessment was made.

NV.EPOCH.label: Epoch
NV.EPOCH.description: Epoch associated with the date/time at which the assessment was made.

NV.NVDY.label: Study Day of Visit/Collection/Exam
NV.NVDY.description: Study day of the procedure or test, measured as integer days. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics.

NV.NVTPT.label: Planned Time Point Name
NV.NVTPT.description: Text description of time when measurement should be taken. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point (e.g., "TIME OF LAST DOSE"). See NVTPTNUM and NVTPTREF. Examples: "START", "5 MIN POST".

NV.NVTPTNUM.label: Planned Time Point Number
NV.NVTPTNUM.description: Numerical version of NVTPT to aid in sorting.

NV.NVELTM.label: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
NV.NVELTM.description: Planned elapsed time (in ISO 8601) relative to a fixed time point reference (NVTPTREF). Not a clock time or a date time variable. Represented as an ISO 8601 duration. Examples: "-PT15M" to represent the period of 15 minutes prior to the reference point indicated by NVTPTREF, "PT8H" to represent the period of 8 hours after the reference point indicated by NVTPTREF.

NV.NVTPTREF.label: Time Point Reference
NV.NVTPTREF.description: Name of the fixed reference point referred to by NVELTM, NVTPTNUM, and NVTPT. Examples: "PREVIOUS DOSE", "PREVIOUS MEAL".

NV.NVRFTDTC.label: Date/Time of Reference Time Point
NV.NVRFTDTC.description: Date/time for a fixed reference time point defined by --TPTREF in ISO 8601 character format.

OE.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
OE.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

OE.FOCID.label: Focus of Study-Specific Interest
OE.FOCID.description: Identification of a focus of study-specific interest on or within a subject or specimen as called out in the protocol for which a measurement, test, or examination was performed.

OE.OESEQ.label: Sequence Number
OE.OESEQ.description: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

OE.OEGRPID.label: Group ID
OE.OEGRPID.description: Optional group identifier, used to link together a block of related records within a subject in a domain.

OE.OELNKID.label: Link ID
OE.OELNKID.description: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This may be a one-to-one or a one-to-many relationship.

OE.OELNKGRP.label: Link Group
OE.OELNKGRP.description: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This will usually be a many-to-one relationship.

OE.OETESTCD.label: Short Name of Ophthalmic Test or Exam
OE.OETESTCD.description: Short character value for OETEST used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical format to a horizontal format. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in OETESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST" is not valid). OETESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Example: "NUMLCOR".

OE.OETEST.label: Name of Ophthalmic Test or Exam
OE.OETEST.description: Long name for the test or examination used to obtain the measurement or finding. The value in OETEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Example: "Number of Letters Correct" for OETESTCD = "NUMLCOR".

OE.OETSTDTL.label: Ophthalmic Test or Exam Detail
OE.OETSTDTL.description: Further description of OETESTCD and OETEST.

OE.OECAT.label: Category for Ophthalmic Test or Exam
OE.OECAT.description: Used to define a category of topic-variable values. Examples: "VISUAL ACUITY", "CONTRAST SENSITIVITY", "OCULAR COMFORT".

OE.OESCAT.label: Subcategory for Ophthalmic Test or Exam
OE.OESCAT.description: Used to define a further categorization of OECAT values. Example: "HIGH CONTRAST" or "LOW CONTRAST" when OECAT is "VISUAL ACUITY".

OE.OEORRES.label: Result or Finding in Original Units
OE.OEORRES.description: Result of the measurement or finding as originally received or collected. Examples: "120", "<1, NORMAL", "RED SPOT VISIBLE".

OE.OEORNRLO.label: Normal Range Lower Limit-Original Units
OE.OEORNRLO.description: Lower end of normal range or reference range for results stored in OEORRES.

OE.OEORNRHI.label: Normal Range Upper Limit-Original Units
OE.OEORNRHI.description: Upper end of normal range or reference range for results stored in OEORRES.

OE.OESTRESC.label: Character Result/Finding in Std Format
OE.OESTRESC.description: Contains the result value for all findings copied or derived from OEORRES, in a standard format or in standard units. OESTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in OESTRESN.

OE.OESTRESN.label: Numeric Result/Finding in Standard Units
OE.OESTRESN.description: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from OESTRESC. OESTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

OE.OESTRESU.label: Standard Units
OE.OESTRESU.description: Standardized units used for OESTRESC and OESTRESN. Examples: "mm", "um".

OE.OESTNRLO.label: Normal Range Lower Limit-Standard Units
OE.OESTNRLO.description: Lower end of normal range or reference range for standardized results (e.g., OESTRESC, OESTRESN) represented in standardized units (OESTRESU).

OE.OESTNRHI.label: Normal Range Upper Limit-Standard Units
OE.OESTNRHI.description: Upper end of normal range or reference range for standardized results (e.g., OESTRESC, OESTRESN) represented in standardized units (OESTRESU).

OE.OESTNRC.label: Normal Range for Character Results
OE.OESTNRC.description: Normal range or reference range for results stored in OESTRESC that are character in ordinal or categorical scale. Example: "Negative to Trace".

OE.OENRIND.label: Normal/Reference Range Indicator
OE.OENRIND.description: Used to indicate the value is outside the normal range or reference range. May be defined by OEORNRLO and OEORNRHI or other objective criteria. Examples: "Y", "N"; "HIGH", "LOW"; "NORMAL", "ABNORMAL".

OE.OERESCAT.label: Result Category
OE.OERESCAT.description: Used to categorize the result of a finding or medical status per interpretation of test results. Examples: "POSITIVE", "NEGATIVE". The variable OERESCAT is not meant to replace the use of OENRIND for cases where normal ranges are provided.

OE.OESTAT.label: Completion Status
OE.OESTAT.description: Used to indicate that a question was not asked or a test was not done, or a test was attempted but did not generate a result. Should be null or have a value of "NOT DONE".

OE.OEREASND.label: Reason Not Done
OE.OEREASND.description: Reason not done. Used in conjunction with OESTAT when value is "NOT DONE".

OE.OEXFN.label: External File Path
OE.OEXFN.description: Filename for an external file, such as one for a retinal OCT image.

OE.OELOC.label: Location Used for the Measurement
OE.OELOC.description: Anatomical location of the subject relevant to the collection of the measurement. Examples: "EYE" for a finding record relative to the complete eye, "RETINA" for a measurement or assessment of only the retina.

OE.OELAT.label: Laterality
OE.OELAT.description: Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing laterality. Examples: "RIGHT", "LEFT", "BILATERAL".

OE.OEDIR.label: Directionality
OE.OEDIR.description: Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing directionality. Examples: "ANTERIOR", "LOWER", "PROXIMAL".

OE.OEPORTOT.label: Portion or Totality
OE.OEPORTOT.description: Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing the distribution (i.e., arrangement of, apportioning of). Examples: "ENTIRE", "SINGLE", "SEGMENT", "MANY".

OE.OEMETHOD.label: Method of Test or Examination
OE.OEMETHOD.description: Method of the test or examination. Example: "ETDRS EYE CHART" for OETESTCD = "NUMLCOR". The different methods may offer different functionality or granularity, affecting the set of results and associated meaning.

OE.OELOBXFL.label: Last Observation Before Exposure Flag
OE.OELOBXFL.description: Operationally derived indicator used to identify the last non-missing value prior to RFXSTDTC. The value should be "Y" or null.

OE.OEBLFL.label: Baseline Flag
OE.OEBLFL.description: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. Should be "Y" or null. Note that OEBLFL is retained for backward compatibility. The authoritative baseline for statistical analysis is in an ADaM dataset.

OE.OEDRVFL.label: Derived Flag
OE.OEDRVFL.description: Used to indicate a derived record (e.g., a record that represents the average of other records such as a computed baseline). Should be "Y" or null.

OE.OEEVAL.label: Evaluator
OE.OEEVAL.description: Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Used only for results that are subjective (e.g., assigned by a person or a group). Examples: "INDEPENDENT ASSESSOR", "INVESTIGATOR".

OE.OEEVALID.label: Evaluator Identifier
OE.OEEVALID.description: Used to distinguish multiple evaluators with the same role recorded in OEEVAL. Examples: "RADIOLOGIST1", "RADIOLOGIST2".

OE.OEACPTFL.label: Accepted Record Flag
OE.OEACPTFL.description: In cases where more than one assessor provides an evaluation of a result or response, this flag identifies the record that is considered, by an independent assessor, to be the accepted evaluation. Expected to be "Y" or null.

OE.OEREPNUM.label: Repetition Number
OE.OEREPNUM.description: The incidence number of a test that is repeated within a given timeframe for the same test. The level of granularity can vary (e.g., within a time point, within a visit). Examples: multiple measurements of blood pressure, multiple analyses of a sample.

OE.VISITNUM.label: Visit Number
OE.VISITNUM.description: Clinical encounter number. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

OE.VISIT.label: Visit Name
OE.VISIT.description: Protocol-defined description of a clinical encounter.

OE.VISITDY.label: Planned Study Day of Visit
OE.VISITDY.description: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

OE.TAETORD.label: Planned Order of Element within Arm
OE.TAETORD.description: Number that gives the planned order of the element within the arm for the element in which the assessment was made.

OE.EPOCH.label: Epoch
OE.EPOCH.description: Epoch associated with the date/time at which the assessment was made.

OE.OEDY.label: Study Day of Visit/Collection/Exam
OE.OEDY.description: Actual study day of observation/exam expressed in integer days relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics.

OE.OETPT.label: Planned Time Point Name
OE.OETPT.description: Text description of time when a measurement or observation should be taken as defined in the protocol. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point.

OE.OETPTNUM.label: Planned Time Point Number
OE.OETPTNUM.description: Numeric version of planned time point used in sorting.

OE.OEELTM.label: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
OE.OEELTM.description: Planned elapsed time relative to a planned fixed reference (OETPTREF; e.g., "PREVIOUS DOSE", "PREVIOUS MEAL"). This variable is useful where there are repetitive measures. Not a clock time or a date/time variable, but an interval, represented as ISO duration.

OE.OETPTREF.label: Time Point Reference
OE.OETPTREF.description: Description of the fixed reference point referred to by OETPT, OETPTNUM, and OEELTM.

OE.OERFTDTC.label: Date/Time of Reference Time Point
OE.OERFTDTC.description: Date/time of the reference time point, OETPTREF.

PC.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
PC.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

PC.PCSEQ.label: Sequence Number
PC.PCSEQ.description: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

PC.PCGRPID.label: Group ID
PC.PCGRPID.description: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain to support relationships within the domain and between domains.

PC.PCTESTCD.label: Pharmacokinetic Test Short Name
PC.PCTESTCD.description: Short name of the analyte or specimen characteristic. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in PCTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST" is not valid). PCTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: "ASA", "VOL", "SPG".

PC.PCTEST.label: Pharmacokinetic Test Name
PC.PCTEST.description: Name of the analyte or specimen characteristic. Note any test normally performed by a clinical laboratory is considered a lab test. The value in PCTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: "Acetylsalicylic Acid", "Volume", "Specific Gravity".

PC.PCCAT.label: Test Category
PC.PCCAT.description: Used to define a category of related records. Examples: "ANALYTE", "SPECIMEN PROPERTY".

PC.PCSCAT.label: Test Subcategory
PC.PCSCAT.description: A further categorization of a test category.

PC.PCORRES.label: Result or Finding in Original Units
PC.PCORRES.description: Result of the measurement or finding as originally received or collected.

PC.PCORRESU.label: Original Units
PC.PCORRESU.description: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for PCORRES. Example: "mg/L".

PC.PCSTRESC.label: Character Result/Finding in Std Format
PC.PCSTRESC.description: Contains the result value for all findings, copied or derived from PCORRES in a standard format or standard units. PCSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in PCSTRESN. For example, if a test has results "NONE", "NEG", and "NEGATIVE" in PCORRES, and these results effectively have the same meaning, they could be represented in standard format in PCSTRESC as "NEGATIVE". For other examples, see general assumptions.

PC.PCSTRESN.label: Numeric Result/Finding in Standard Units
PC.PCSTRESN.description: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from PCSTRESC. PCSTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

PC.PCSTRESU.label: Standard Units
PC.PCSTRESU.description: Standardized unit used for PCSTRESC and PCSTRESN.

PC.PCSTAT.label: Completion Status
PC.PCSTAT.description: Used to indicate a result was not obtained. Should be null if a result exists in PCORRES.

PC.PCREASND.label: Reason Test Not Done
PC.PCREASND.description: Describes why a result was not obtained, such as "SPECIMEN LOST". Used in conjunction with PCSTAT when value is "NOT DONE".

PC.PCNAM.label: Vendor Name
PC.PCNAM.description: Name or identifier of the laboratory or vendor who provides the test results.

PC.PCSPEC.label: Specimen Material Type
PC.PCSPEC.description: Defines the type of specimen used for a measurement. Examples: "SERUM", "PLASMA", "URINE".

PC.PCSPCCND.label: Specimen Condition
PC.PCSPCCND.description: Free or standardized text describing the condition of the specimen. Examples: "HEMOLYZED", "ICTERIC", "LIPEMIC".

PC.PCMETHOD.label: Method of Test or Examination
PC.PCMETHOD.description: Method of the test or examination. Examples: "HPLC/MS", "ELISA". This should contain sufficient information and granularity to allow differentiation of various methods that might have been used within a study.

PC.PCFAST.label: Fasting Status
PC.PCFAST.description: Indicator used to identify fasting status.

PC.PCDRVFL.label: Derived Flag
PC.PCDRVFL.description: Used to indicate a derived record. The value should be "Y" or null. Records that represent the average of other records, which do not come from the CRF, are examples of records that would be derived for the submission datasets. If PCDRVFL = "Y", then PCORRES may be null with PCSTRESC, and PCSTRESN (if the result is numeric) having the derived value.

PC.PCLLOQ.label: Lower Limit of Quantitation
