PC.PCLLOQ.description: Indicates the lower limit of quantitation for an assay. Units should be those used in PCSTRESU.

PC.PCULOQ.label: Upper Limit of Quantitation
PC.PCULOQ.description: Indicates the upper limit of quantitation for an assay. Units should be those used in PCSTRESU.

PC.VISITNUM.label: Visit Number
PC.VISITNUM.description: Clinical encounter number. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

PC.VISIT.label: Visit Name
PC.VISIT.description: Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY.

PC.VISITDY.label: Planned Study Day of Visit
PC.VISITDY.description: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

PC.TAETORD.label: Planned Order of Element within Arm
PC.TAETORD.description: Number that gives the planned order of the element within the arm.

PC.EPOCH.label: Epoch
PC.EPOCH.description: Epoch associated with the start date/time of the observation, or the date/time of collection if start date/time is not collected.

PC.PCDTC.label: Date/Time of Specimen Collection
PC.PCDTC.description: Date/time of specimen collection represented in ISO 8601 character format. If there is no end time, then this will be the collection time.

PC.PCENDTC.label: End Date/Time of Specimen Collection
PC.PCENDTC.description: End date/time of specimen collection represented in ISO 8601 character format. If there is no end time, the collection time should be stored in PCDTC, and PCENDTC should be null.

PC.PCDY.label: Actual Study Day of Specimen Collection
PC.PCDY.description: Study day of specimen collection, measured as integer days. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics.

PC.PCENDY.label: Study Day of End of Observation
PC.PCENDY.description: Actual study day of end of observation expressed in integer days relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics.

PC.PCTPT.label: Planned Time Point Name
PC.PCTPT.description: Text description of time when specimen should be taken. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point, such as time of last dose. See PCTPTNUM and PCTPTREF. Examples: "Start", "5 min post".

PC.PCTPTNUM.label: Planned Time Point Number
PC.PCTPTNUM.description: Numerical version of PCTPT to aid in sorting.

PC.PCELTM.label: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
PC.PCELTM.description: Planned elapsed time (in ISO 8601) relative to a planned fixed reference (PCTPTREF; e.g., "PREVIOUS DOSE", "PREVIOUS MEAL"). This variable is useful where there are repetitive measures. Not a clock time or a date time variable.

PC.PCTPTREF.label: Time Point Reference
PC.PCTPTREF.description: Name of the fixed reference point used as a basis for PCTPT, PCTPTNUM, and PCELTM. Example: "MOST RECENT DOSE".

PC.PCRFTDTC.label: Date/Time of Reference Point
PC.PCRFTDTC.description: Date/time of the reference time point described by PCTPTREF.

PC.PCEVLINT.label: Evaluation Interval
PC.PCEVLINT.description: Evaluation Interval associated with a PCTEST record represented in ISO 8601 character format. Example: "-PT2H" to represent an evaluation interval of 2 hours prior to a PCTPT.

PE.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
PE.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

PE.PESEQ.label: Sequence Number
PE.PESEQ.description: Sequence number to ensure uniqueness of records within a dataset for a subject. May be any valid number.

PE.PEGRPID.label: Group ID
PE.PEGRPID.description: Used to link together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

PE.PESPID.label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
PE.PESPID.description: Sponsor-defined reference number. Perhaps preprinted on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: Line number on a CRF.

PE.PETESTCD.label: Body System Examined Short Name
PE.PETESTCD.description: Short name of a part of the body examined in a physical examination. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in PETESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST" is not valid). PETESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: "HEAD", "ENT". If the results of the entire physical examination are represented in one record, value should be "PHYSEXAM".

PE.PETEST.label: Body System Examined
PE.PETEST.description: Long name of a part of the body examined in a physical examination. The value in PETEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: "Head", "Ear/Nose/Throat". If the results of the entire physical examination are represented in one record, value should be "Physical Examination".

PE.PEMODIFY.label: Modified Reported Term
PE.PEMODIFY.description: If the value of PEORRES is modified for coding purposes, then the modified text is placed here.

PE.PECAT.label: Category for Examination
PE.PECAT.description: Used to define a category of topic-variable values. Example: "GENERAL".

PE.PESCAT.label: Subcategory for Examination
PE.PESCAT.description: Used to define a further categorization of --CAT values.

PE.PEBODSYS.label: Body System or Organ Class
PE.PEBODSYS.description: Body system or organ class (e.g., MedDRA SOC) that is involved for a finding from the standard hierarchy for dictionary-coded results.

PE.PEORRES.label: Verbatim Examination Finding
PE.PEORRES.description: Text description of any abnormal findings. If the examination was completed and there were no abnormal findings, the value should be "NORMAL". If the examination was not performed on a particular body system, or at the subject level, then the value should be null, and "NOT DONE" should appear in PESTAT.

PE.PEORRESU.label: Original Units
PE.PEORRESU.description: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for PEORRES.

PE.PESTRESC.label: Character Result/Finding in Std Format
PE.PESTRESC.description: If there are findings for a body system, then either the dictionary preferred term (if findings are coded using a dictionary) or PEORRES (if findings are not encoded) should appear here. If PEORRES is null, PESTRESC must be null.

PE.PESTAT.label: Completion Status
PE.PESTAT.description: Used to indicate exam not done. Must be null if a result exists in PEORRES/PESTRESC.

PE.PEREASND.label: Reason Not Examined
PE.PEREASND.description: Describes why an examination was not performed or why a body system was not examined. Example: "SUBJECT REFUSED". Used in conjunction with PESTAT when value is "NOT DONE".

PE.PELOC.label: Location of Physical Exam Finding
PE.PELOC.description: Anatomical location of the subject relevant to the collection of the measurement. Example: "ARM" for skin rash.

PE.PELAT.label: Laterality
PE.PELAT.description: Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing laterallity. Examples: "RIGHT", "LEFT", "BILATERAL".

PE.PEMETHOD.label: Method of Test or Examination
PE.PEMETHOD.description: Method of the test or examination. Examples: "PALPATION", "PERCUSSION".

PE.PELOBXFL.label: Last Observation Before Exposure Flag
PE.PELOBXFL.description: Operationally derived indicator used to identify the last non-missing value prior to RFXSTDTC. Should be "Y" or null.

PE.PEBLFL.label: Baseline Flag
PE.PEBLFL.description: A baseline defined by the sponsor (could be derived in the same manner as PELOBXFL or ABLFL, but is not required to be). The value should be "Y" or null. Note that PEBLFL is retained for backward compatibility. The authoritative baseline flag for statistical analysis is in an ADaM dataset.

PE.PEEVAL.label: Evaluator
PE.PEEVAL.description: Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Used only for results that are subjective (e.g., assigned by a person or a group). Example: "INVESTIGATOR".

PE.VISITNUM.label: Visit Number
PE.VISITNUM.description: Clinical encounter number. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

PE.VISIT.label: Visit Name
PE.VISIT.description: Protocol-defined description of a clinical encounter. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY.

PE.VISITDY.label: Planned Study Day of Visit
PE.VISITDY.description: Planned study day of VISIT. Should be an integer.

PE.TAETORD.label: Planned Order of Element within Arm
PE.TAETORD.description: Number that gives the planned order of the element within the arm for the element in which the assessment was made.

PE.EPOCH.label: Epoch
PE.EPOCH.description: Epoch associated with the observation date/time of the physical exam finding.

PE.PEDTC.label: Date/Time of Examination
PE.PEDTC.description: Date and time of the physical examination represented in ISO 8601 character format.

PE.PEDY.label: Study Day of Examination
PE.PEDY.description: Study day of physical exam, measured as integer days. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics.

PP.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
PP.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product. \n

PP.PPSEQ.label: Sequence Number
PP.PPSEQ.description: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

PP.PPGRPID.label: Group ID
PP.PPGRPID.description: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain to support relationships within the domain and between domains.

PP.PPTESTCD.label: Parameter Short Name
PP.PPTESTCD.description: Short name of the pharmacokinetic parameter. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in PPTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST" is not valid). PPTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: "AUCALL", "TMAX", "CMAX".

PP.PPTEST.label: Parameter Name
PP.PPTEST.description: Name of the pharmacokinetic parameter. The value in PPTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: "AUC All", "Time of CMAX", "Max Conc".

PP.PPCAT.label: Parameter Category
PP.PPCAT.description: Used to define a category of related records. For PP, this should be the name of the analyte in PCTEST whose profile the parameter is associated with.

PP.PPSCAT.label: Parameter Subcategory
PP.PPSCAT.description: Categorization of the model type used to calculate the PK parameters. Examples: "COMPARTMENTAL", "NON-COMPARTMENTAL".

PP.PPORRES.label: Result or Finding in Original Units
PP.PPORRES.description: Result of the measurement or finding as originally received or collected.

PP.PPORRESU.label: Original Units
PP.PPORRESU.description: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for PPORRES. Example: "ng/L". See PP Assumption 3.

PP.PPSTRESC.label: Character Result/Finding in Std Format
PP.PPSTRESC.description: Contains the result value for all findings, copied or derived from PPORRES in a standard format or standard units. PPSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in PPSTRESN.

PP.PPSTRESN.label: Numeric Result/Finding in Standard Units
PP.PPSTRESN.description: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from PPSTRESC. PPSTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

PP.PPSTRESU.label: Standard Units
PP.PPSTRESU.description: Standardized unit used for PPSTRESC and PPSTRESN. See PP Assumption 3.

PP.PPSTAT.label: Completion Status
PP.PPSTAT.description: Used to indicate that a parameter was not calculated. Should be null if a result exists in PPORRES.

PP.PPREASND.label: Reason Parameter Not Calculated
PP.PPREASND.description: Describes why a parameter was not calculated, such as "INSUFFICIENT DATA". Used in conjunction with PPSTAT when value is "NOT DONE".

PP.PPSPEC.label: Specimen Material Type
PP.PPSPEC.description: Defines the type of specimen used for a measurement. If multiple specimen types are used for a calculation (e.g., serum and urine for renal clearance), then this field should be left blank. Examples: "SERUM", "PLASMA", "URINE".

PP.PPANMETH.label: Analysis Method
PP.PPANMETH.description: Analysis method applied to obtain a summarized result. Analysis method describes the method of secondary processing applied to a complex observation result. Example: A named formula used to calculate AUC, such as "LIN-LOG TRAPEZOIDAL METHOD". \n Sponsor-defined formulas can also be represented by this variable. Example: Calculating ratio AUCs where the PPANMETH may be "DRUG METABOLITE 1 TO DRUG PARENT" or "DRUG METABOLITE 2 TO METABOLITE 1".

PP.TAETORD.label: Planned Order of Element within Arm
PP.TAETORD.description: Number that gives the planned order of the element within the arm.

PP.EPOCH.label: Epoch
PP.EPOCH.description: Epoch associated with the start date/time of the observation, or the date/time of collection if start date/time is not collected.

PP.PPDY.label: Study Day of Parameter Calculations
PP.PPDY.description: Study day of the collection, in integer days. The algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in the Demographics (DM) domain.

PP.PPTPTREF.label: Time Point Reference
PP.PPTPTREF.description: The description of a time point that acts as a fixed reference for a series of planned time points.

PP.PPRFTDTC.label: Date/Time of Reference Point
PP.PPRFTDTC.description: Date/time of the reference time point from the PC records used to calculate a parameter record. The values in PPRFTDTC should be the same as that in PCRFTDTC for related records.

PP.PPSTINT.label: Planned Start of Assessment Interval
PP.PPSTINT.description: The start of a planned evaluation or assessment interval relative to the time point reference.

PP.PPENINT.label: Planned End of Assessment Interval
PP.PPENINT.description: The end of a planned evaluation or assessment interval relative to the time point reference.

QS.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
QS.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

QS.QSSEQ.label: Sequence Number
QS.QSSEQ.description: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

QS.QSGRPID.label: Group ID
QS.QSGRPID.description: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

QS.QSSPID.label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
QS.QSSPID.description: Sponsor-defined reference number. May be preprinted on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: Question number on a questionnaire.

QS.QSTESTCD.label: Question Short Name
QS.QSTESTCD.description: Topic variable for QS. Short name for the value in QSTEST, which can be used as a column name when converting the dataset from a vertical format to a horizontal format. The value in QSTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST" is not valid). QSTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. \n Controlled terminology for QSTESTCD is published in separate codelists for each questionnaire. See https://www.cdisc.org/standards/semantics/terminology for values for QSTESTCD. Examples: "ADCCMD01", "BPR0103".

QS.QSTEST.label: Question Name
QS.QSTEST.description: Verbatim name of the question or group of questions used to obtain the measurement or finding. The value in QSTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. \n Controlled terminology for QSTEST is published in separate codelists for each questionnaire. See https://www.cdisc.org/standards/semantics/terminology for values for QSTEST. Example: "BPR01 - Emotional Withdrawal".

QS.QSCAT.label: Category of Question
QS.QSCAT.description: Used to specify the questionnaire in which the question identified by QSTEST and QSTESTCD was included. Examples: "ADAS-COG", "MDS-UPDRS".

QS.QSSCAT.label: Subcategory for Question
QS.QSSCAT.description: A further categorization of the questions within the category. Examples: "MENTAL HEALTH" , "DEPRESSION", "WORD RECALL".

QS.QSORRES.label: Finding in Original Units
QS.QSORRES.description: Finding as originally received or collected (e.g., "RARELY", "SOMETIMES"). When sponsors apply codelist to indicate that code values are statistically meaningful standardized scores (which are defined by sponsors or by valid methodologies, e.g., SF36 questionnaires), QSORRES will contain the decode format; QSSTRESC and QSSTRESN may contain the standardized code values or scores.

QS.QSORRESU.label: Original Units
QS.QSORRESU.description: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for QSORRES, such as minutes or seconds or the units associated with a visual analog scale.

QS.QSSTRESC.label: Character Result/Finding in Std Format
QS.QSSTRESC.description: Contains the finding for all questions or subscores copied or derived from QSORRES, in a standard format or standard units. QSSTRESC should store all findings in character format; if findings are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in QSSTRESN. If question scores are derived from the original finding, then the standard format is the score. Examples: "0", "1". \n When sponsors apply codelist to indicate the code values are statistically meaningful standardized scores (which are defined by sponsors or by valid methodologies, e.g., SF36 questionnaires), QSORRES will contain the decode format; QSSTRESC and QSSTRESN may contain the standardized code values or scores.

QS.QSSTRESN.label: Numeric Finding in Standard Units
QS.QSSTRESN.description: Used for continuous or numeric findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from QSSTRESC. QSSTRESN should store all numeric results or findings.

QS.QSSTRESU.label: Standard Units
QS.QSSTRESU.description: Standardized unit used for QSSTRESC or QSSTRESN.

QS.QSSTAT.label: Completion Status
QS.QSSTAT.description: Used to indicate that a question was not done or was not answered. Should be null if a result exists in QSORRES.

QS.QSREASND.label: Reason Not Performed
QS.QSREASND.description: Describes why a question was not answered. Used in conjunction with QSSTAT when value is "NOT DONE". Example: "SUBJECT REFUSED".

QS.QSMETHOD.label: Method of Test or Examination
QS.QSMETHOD.description: Method of the test or examination.

QS.QSLOBXFL.label: Last Observation Before Exposure Flag
QS.QSLOBXFL.description: Operationally derived indicator used to identify the last non-missing value prior to RFXSTDTC. Should be "Y" or null.

QS.QSBLFL.label: Baseline Flag
QS.QSBLFL.description: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. Should be "Y" or null. Note that QSBLFL is retained for backward compatibility. The authoritative baseline for statistical analysis is in an ADaM dataset.

QS.QSDRVFL.label: Derived Flag
QS.QSDRVFL.description: Used to indicate a derived record. The value should be "Y" or null. Records that represent the average of other records or questionnaire subscores that do not come from the CRF are examples of records that would be derived for the submission datasets. If QSDRVFL = "Y", then QSORRES may be null with QSSTRESC and (if numeric) QSSTRESN having the derived value.

QS.VISITNUM.label: Visit Number
QS.VISITNUM.description: Clinical encounter number. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

QS.VISIT.label: Visit Name
QS.VISIT.description: Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY.

QS.VISITDY.label: Planned Study Day of Visit
QS.VISITDY.description: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

QS.TAETORD.label: Planned Order of Element within Arm
QS.TAETORD.description: Number that gives the planned order of the element within the arm for the element in which the assessment was made.

QS.EPOCH.label: Epoch
QS.EPOCH.description: Epoch associated with the observation date/time of the physical exam finding.

QS.QSDY.label: Study Day of Finding
QS.QSDY.description: Study day of finding collection, measured as integer days. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics.

QS.QSTPT.label: Planned Time Point Name
QS.QSTPT.description: Text description of time when questionnaire should be administered. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point (e.g., "TIME OF LAST DOSE"). See QSTPTNUM and QSTPTREF.

QS.QSTPTNUM.label: Planned Time Point Number
QS.QSTPTNUM.description: Numerical version of QSTPT to aid in sorting.

QS.QSELTM.label: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
QS.QSELTM.description: Planned elapsed time (in ISO 8601) relative to a planned fixed reference (QSTPTREF). This variable is useful where there are repetitive measures. Not a clock time or a date time variable. Represented as an ISO 8601 duration. Examples: "-PT15M" to represent the period of 15 minutes prior to the reference point indicated by QSTPTREF, "PT8H" to represent the period of 8 hours after the reference point indicated by QSTPTREF.

QS.QSTPTREF.label: Time Point Reference
QS.QSTPTREF.description: Name of the fixed reference point referred to by QSELTM, QSTPTNUM, and QSTPT. Examples: "PREVIOUS DOSE", "PREVIOUS MEAL".

QS.QSRFTDTC.label: Date/Time of Reference Time Point
QS.QSRFTDTC.description: Date/time of the reference time point, QSTPTREF.

QS.QSEVLINT.label: Evaluation Interval
QS.QSEVLINT.description: Evaluation interval associated with a QSTEST question represented in ISO 8601 character format. Example: "-P2Y" to represent an interval of 2 years in the question "Have you experienced any episodes in the past 2 years?".

QS.QSEVINTX.label: Evaluation Interval Text
QS.QSEVINTX.description: Evaluation interval associated with an observation, where the interval is not able to be represented in ISO 8601 format. Examples: "LIFETIME", "LAST NIGHT", "RECENTLY", "OVER THE LAST FEW WEEKS".

RE.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
RE.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

RE.RESEQ.label: Sequence Number
RE.RESEQ.description: Sequence number to ensure uniqueness of records within a dataset for a subject. May be any valid number (including decimals) and does not have to start at 1.

RE.REGRPID.label: Group ID
RE.REGRPID.description: Optional group identifier, used to link together a block of related records within a subject in a domain.

RE.REREFID.label: Reference ID
RE.REREFID.description: Optional internal or external procedure identifier.

RE.RESPID.label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
RE.RESPID.description: Sponsor-defined identifier. May be preprinted on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database.

RE.RELNKID.label: Link ID
RE.RELNKID.description: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This may be a one-to-one or a one-to-many relationship.

RE.RELNKGRP.label: Link Group
RE.RELNKGRP.description: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This will usually be a many-to-one relationship.

RE.RETESTCD.label: Short Name of Respiratory Test
RE.RETESTCD.description: Short name of the measurement, test, or examination. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical format to a horizontal format. The value in RETESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST" is not valid). RETESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: "FEV1", "FVC".

RE.RETEST.label: Name of Respiratory Test
RE.RETEST.description: Verbatim name of the test or examination used to obtain the measurement or finding. The value in RETEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: "Forced Expiratory Volume in 1 Second", "Forced Vital Capacity".

RE.RECAT.label: Category for Respiratory Test
RE.RECAT.description: Used to categorize observations across subjects.

RE.REPOS.label: Position of Subject During Observation
RE.REPOS.description: Position of the subject during a measurement or examination. Examples: "SUPINE", "STANDING", "SITTING".

RE.REORRES.label: Result or Finding in Original Units
RE.REORRES.description: Result of the procedure measurement or finding as originally received or collected.

RE.REORRESU.label: Original Units
RE.REORRESU.description: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for REORRES and REORREF.

RE.REORREF.label: Reference Result in Original Units
RE.REORREF.description: Reference result for continuous measurements in original units. Should be collected only for continuous results.

RE.RESTRESC.label: Character Result/Finding in Std Format
RE.RESTRESC.description: Contains the result value for all findings, copied or derived from REORRES in a standard format or in standard units. RESTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in RESTRESN.

RE.RESTRESN.label: Numeric Result/Finding in Standard Units
RE.RESTRESN.description: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from RESTRESC. RESTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

RE.RESTRESU.label: Standard Units
RE.RESTRESU.description: Standardized unit used for RESTRESC, RESTRESN and RESTREFN.

RE.RESTREFC.label: Character Reference Result
RE.RESTREFC.description: Reference value for the result or finding copied or derived from --ORREF in a standard format.

RE.RESTREFN.label: Numeric Reference Result in Std Units
RE.RESTREFN.description: Reference result for continuous measurements in standard units. Should be populated only for continuous results.

RE.RESTAT.label: Completion Status
RE.RESTAT.description: Used to indicate that a test was not done or a measurement was not taken. Should be null if a result exists in REORRES.

RE.REREASND.label: Reason Not Done
RE.REREASND.description: Describes why a measurement or test was not performed. Examples: "BROKEN EQUIPMENT", "SUBJECT REFUSED". Used in conjunction with RESTAT when value is "NOT DONE".

RE.RELOC.label: Location Used for the Measurement
RE.RELOC.description: Anatomical location of the subject relevant to the collection of the measurement. Examples: "LUNG", "BRONCHUS".

RE.RELAT.label: Laterality
RE.RELAT.description: Side of the body used to collect measurement. Examples: "RIGHT", "LEFT".

RE.REDIR.label: Directionality
RE.REDIR.description: Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing directionality. Examples: "ANTERIOR", "LOWER", "PROXIMAL".

RE.REMETHOD.label: Method of Test or Examination
RE.REMETHOD.description: Method used to create the result.

RE.RELOBXFL.label: Last Observation Before Exposure Flag
RE.RELOBXFL.description: Operationally-derived indicator used to identify the last non-missing value prior to RFXSTDTC. The value should be "Y" or null.

RE.REBLFL.label: Baseline Flag
RE.REBLFL.description: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. Should be Y or null. Note that REBLFL is retained for backward compatibility. The authoritative baseline flag for statistical analysis is in an ADaM dataset.

RE.REDRVFL.label: Derived Flag
RE.REDRVFL.description: Used to indicate a derived record. Should be "Y" or null. Records that represent the average of other records, or that do not come from the CRF, or are not as originally collected or received are examples of records that would be derived for the submission datasets. If REDRVFL = "Y", then REORRES could be null, with RESTRESC and (if numeric) RESTRESN having the derived value.

RE.REEVAL.label: Evaluator
RE.REEVAL.description: Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Used only for results that are subjective (e.g., assigned by a person or a group). Examples: "ADJUDICATION COMMITTEE", "INDEPENDENT ASSESSOR", "RADIOLOGIST".

RE.REEVALID.label: Evaluator Identifier
RE.REEVALID.description: Used to distinguish multiple evaluators with the same role recorded in REEVAL. Examples: "RADIOLOGIST1", "RADIOLOGIST2".

RE.REREPNUM.label: Repetition Number
RE.REREPNUM.description: The instance number of a test that is repeated within a given time frame for the same test. The level of granularity can vary (e.g., within a time point, within a visit). Example: multiple measurements of pulmonary function.

RE.VISITNUM.label: Visit Number
RE.VISITNUM.description: Clinical encounter number. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

RE.VISIT.label: Visit Name
RE.VISIT.description: Protocol-defined description of a clinical encounter. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY.

RE.VISITDY.label: Planned Study Day of Visit
RE.VISITDY.description: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

RE.TAETORD.label: Planned Order of Element within Arm
RE.TAETORD.description: Number that gives the planned order of the element within the arm for the element in which the assessment was made.

RE.EPOCH.label: Epoch
RE.EPOCH.description: Epoch associated with the date/time at which the assessment was made.

RE.REDY.label: Study Day of Visit/Collection/Exam
RE.REDY.description: Actual study day of visit/collection/exam expressed in integer days relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics.

RE.RETPT.label: Planned Time Point Name
RE.RETPT.description: Text description of time when a measurement or observation should be taken as defined in the protocol. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point (e.g., "TIME OF LAST DOSE"). See RETPTNUM and RETPTREF. Examples: "START", "5 MINUTES POST".

RE.RETPTNUM.label: Planned Time Point Number
RE.RETPTNUM.description: Numeric version of RETPT to aid in sorting.

RE.REELTM.label: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
RE.REELTM.description: Planned elapsed time relative to a planned fixed reference (RETPTREF). Not a clock time or a date/time variable, but an interval, represented as ISO duration. Examples: "-PT15M" to represent 15 minutes prior to the reference time point indicated by RETPTREF, "PT8H" to represent 8 hours after the reference time point represented by RETPTREF.

RE.RETPTREF.label: Time Point Reference
RE.RETPTREF.description: Description of the fixed reference point referred to by REELTM, RETPTNUM, and RETPT. Examples: "PREVIOUS DOSE", "PREVIOUS MEAL".

RE.RERFTDTC.label: Date/Time of Reference Time Point
RE.RERFTDTC.description: Date/time for a fixed reference time point defined by RETPTREF.

RP.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
RP.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

RP.RPSEQ.label: Sequence Number
RP.RPSEQ.description: Sequence number to ensure uniqueness of records within a dataset for a subject (or within a parameter, in the case of the Trial Summary domain). May be any valid number (including decimals) and does not have to start at 1.

RP.RPGRPID.label: Group ID
RP.RPGRPID.description: Optional group identifier, used to link together a block of related records within a subject in a domain. Also used to link together a block of related records in the Trial Summary dataset.

RP.RPREFID.label: Reference ID
RP.RPREFID.description: Optional internal or external identifier (e.g., lab specimen ID, UUID for an ECG waveform or a medical image).

RP.RPSPID.label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
RP.RPSPID.description: Sponsor-defined identifier. Example: Preprinted line identifier on a CRF.

RP.RPLNKID.label: Link ID
RP.RPLNKID.description: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This may be a one-to-one or a one-to-many relationship.

RP.RPLNKGRP.label: Link Group ID
RP.RPLNKGRP.description: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This will usually be a many-to-one relationship.

RP.RPTESTCD.label: Short Name of Reproductive Test
RP.RPTESTCD.description: Short character value for RPTEST used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical format to a horizontal format. The short value can be up to 8 characters. Examples: "CHILDPOT", "BCMETHOD", "MENARAGE".

RP.RPTEST.label: Name of Reproductive Test
RP.RPTEST.description: Long name For RPTESTCD. Examples: "Childbearing Potential", "Birth Control Method", "Menarche Age".

RP.RPCAT.label: Category for Reproductive Test
RP.RPCAT.description: Used to define a category of topic-variable values. Example: "No use case to date, but values would be relative to reproduction tests grouping".

RP.RPSCAT.label: Subcategory for Reproductive Test
RP.RPSCAT.description: Used to define a further categorization of RPCAT values. Example: "No use case to date, but values would be relative to reproduction tests grouping".

RP.RPORRES.label: Result or Finding in Original Units
RP.RPORRES.description: Result of the measurement or finding as originally received or collected. Examples: "120", "<1", "POS".

RP.RPSTRESC.label: Character Result/Finding in Std Format
RP.RPSTRESC.description: Contains the result value for all findings copied or derived from RPORRES, in a standard format or in standard units. RPSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in RPSTRESN. For example, if various tests have results "NONE", "NEG", and "NEGATIVE" in RPORRES, and these results effectively have the same meaning, they could be represented in standard format in RPSTRESC as "NEGATIVE".

RP.RPSTRESN.label: Numeric Result/Finding in Standard Units
RP.RPSTRESN.description: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from RPSTRESC. RPSTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

RP.RPSTRESU.label: Standard Units
RP.RPSTRESU.description: Standardized units used for RPSTRESC and RPSTRESN. Example: "mol/L".

RP.RPSTAT.label: Completion Status
RP.RPSTAT.description: Used to indicate that a question was not asked or a test was not done, or a test was attempted but did not generate a result. Should be null or have a value of "NOT DONE".

RP.RPREASND.label: Reason Not Done
RP.RPREASND.description: Reason not done. Used in conjunction with RPSTAT when value is "NOT DONE".

RP.RPLOBXFL.label: Last Observation Before Exposure Flag
RP.RPLOBXFL.description: Operationally derived indicator used to identify the last non-missing value prior to RFXSTDTC. The value should be "Y" or null.

RP.RPBLFL.label: Baseline Flag
RP.RPBLFL.description: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. Should be "Y" or null. Note that RPBLFL is retained for backward compatibility. The authoritative baseline for statistical analysis is in an ADaM dataset.

RP.RPDRVFL.label: Derived Flag
RP.RPDRVFL.description: Used to indicate a derived record. The value should be "Y" or null. Records which represent the average of other records or which do not come from the CRF are examples of records that would be derived for the submission datasets. If RPDRVFL = "Y", then RPORRES may be null, with RPSTRESC and (if numeric) RPSTRESN having the derived value.

RP.VISITNUM.label: Visit Number
RP.VISITNUM.description: Clinical encounter number. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

RP.VISIT.label: Visit Name
RP.VISIT.description: Protocol-defined description of a clinical encounter.

RP.VISITDY.label: Planned Study Day of Visit
RP.VISITDY.description: Planned study day of VISIT. Should be an integer.

RP.TAETORD.label: Planned Order of Element within Arm
RP.TAETORD.description: Number that gives the planned order of the element within the arm for the element in which the assessment was made.

RP.EPOCH.label: Epoch
RP.EPOCH.description: Epoch associated with the date/time at which the assessment was made.

RP.RPDTC.label: Date/Time of Collection
RP.RPDTC.description: Collection date and time of an observation.

RP.RPDY.label: Study Day of Visit/Collection/Exam
RP.RPDY.description: Actual study day of visit/collection/exam expressed in integer days relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics.

RP.RPDUR.label: Duration
RP.RPDUR.description: Collected duration of an event, intervention, or finding represented in ISO 8601 character format. Used only if collected on the CRF and not derived.

RP.RPTPT.label: Planned Time Point Name
RP.RPTPT.description: Text description of time when a measurement or observation should be taken as defined in the protocol. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point, such as time of last dose.

RP.RPTPTNUM.label: Planned Time Point Number
RP.RPTPTNUM.description: Numeric version of planned time point used in sorting.

RP.RPELTM.label: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
RP.RPELTM.description: Planned elapsed time in ISO 8601 character format relative to a planned fixed reference (RPTPTREF; e.g., "PREVIOUS DOSE", "PREVIOUS MEAL"). This variable is useful where there are repetitive measures. Not a clock time or a date/time variable, but an interval, represented as ISO duration.

RP.RPTPTREF.label: Time Point Reference
RP.RPTPTREF.description: Description of the fixed reference point referred to by RPELTM, RPTPTNUM, and RPTPT. Examples: "PREVIOUS DOSE", "PREVIOUS MEAL".

RP.RPRFTDTC.label: Date/Time of Reference Time Point
RP.RPRFTDTC.description: Date/time for a fixed reference time point defined by RPTPTREF in ISO 8601 character format.

RS.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
RS.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

RS.RSSEQ.label: Sequence Number
RS.RSSEQ.description: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness within a dataset for a subject. May be any valid number.

RS.RSGRPID.label: Group ID
RS.RSGRPID.description: Used to link together a block of related records within a subject in a domain.

RS.RSLNKID.label: Link ID
RS.RSLNKID.description: An identifier used to link the response assessment to the related measurement record in another domain which was used to determine the response result. LNKID values group records within USUBJID.

RS.RSLNKGRP.label: Link Group ID
RS.RSLNKGRP.description: A grouping identifier used to link the response assessment to a group of measurement/assessment records which were used in the assessment of the response. LNKGRP values group records within USUBJID.

RS.RSTESTCD.label: Assessment Short Name
RS.RSTESTCD.description: Short name of the TEST in RSTEST. The value in RSTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST" is not valid). RSTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: "TRGRESP", "NTRGRESP", "OVRLRESP", "SYMPTDTR", "CPS0102". \n There are separate codelists used for RSTESTCD where the choice depends on the value of RSCAT. Codelist "ONCRTSCD" is used for oncology response criteria (when RSCAT is a term in codelist "ONCRSCAT"). Examples: TRGRESP, "NTRGRESP, "OVRLRESP". For Clinical Classifications (when RSCAT is a term in codelist "CCCAT"), QRS Naming Rules apply. These instruments have individual dedicated terminology codelists.

RS.RSTEST.label: Assessment Name
RS.RSTEST.description: Verbatim name of the response assessment. The value in RSTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. \n There are separate codelists used for RSTEST where the choice depends on the value of RSCAT. Codelist "ONCRTS" is used for oncology response criteria (when RSCAT is a term in codelist "ONCRSCAT"). Examples: "Target Response", "Non-target Response", "Overall Response", "Symptomatic Deterioration". For Clinical Classifications (when RSCAT is a term in codelist "CCCAT"), QRS Naming Rules apply. These instruments have individual dedicated terminology codelists.

RS.RSCAT.label: Category for Assessment
RS.RSCAT.description: Used to define a category of related records across subjects. Examples: "RECIST 1.1", "CHILD-PUGH CLASSIFICATION". There are separate codelists used for RSCAT where the choice depends on whether the related records are about an oncology response criterion or another clinical classification. \n RSCAT is required for clinical classifications other than oncology response criteria.

RS.RSSCAT.label: Subcategory
RS.RSSCAT.description: Used to define a further categorization of RSCAT values.

RS.RSORRES.label: Result or Finding in Original Units
RS.RSORRES.description: Result of the response assessment as originally received, collected, or calculated.

RS.RSSTRESC.label: Character Result/Finding in Std Format
RS.RSSTRESC.description: Contains the result value for the response assessment, copied, or derived from RSORRES in a standard format or standard units. RSSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format. \n For Clinical Classifications, this may be a score.

RS.RSSTRESN.label: Numeric Result/Finding in Standard Units
RS.RSSTRESN.description: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from --STRESC. --STRESN should store all numeric test results or findings. For Clinical Classifications, this may be a score.

RS.RSSTRESU.label: Standard Units
RS.RSSTRESU.description: Standardized units used for RSSTRESC and RSSTRESN.

RS.RSSTAT.label: Completion Status
RS.RSSTAT.description: Used to indicate the response assessment was not performed. Should be null if a result exists in RSORRES.

RS.RSREASND.label: Reason Not Done
RS.RSREASND.description: Describes why a response assessment was not performed. Examples: "All target tumors not evaluated", "Subject does not have non-target tumors". Used in conjunction with RSSTAT when value is "NOT DONE".

RS.RSNAM.label: Vendor Name
RS.RSNAM.description: The name or identifier of the vendor that performed the response assessment. This column can be left null when the investigator provides the complete set of data in the domain.

RS.RSMETHOD.label: Method of Test or Examination
RS.RSMETHOD.description: Method of the test or examination.

RS.RSLOBXFL.label: Last Observation Before Exposure Flag
RS.RSLOBXFL.description: Operationally derived indicator used to identify the last non-missing value prior to RFXSTDTC. The value should be "Y" or null. \n When a clinical classification is assessed at multiple times, including baseline, RSLOBXFL should be included in the dataset.

RS.RSBLFL.label: Baseline Flag
RS.RSBLFL.description: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. Should be "Y" or null. Note that --BLFL is retained for backward compatibility. The authoritative baseline for statistical analysis is in an ADaM dataset.

RS.RSDRVFL.label: Derived Flag
RS.RSDRVFL.description: Used to indicate a derived record (e.g., a record that represents the average of other records such as a computed baseline). Should be "Y" or null.

RS.RSEVAL.label: Evaluator
RS.RSEVAL.description: Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Used only for results that are subjective (e.g., assigned by a person or a group). Examples: "ADJUDICATION COMMITTEE", "INDEPENDENT ASSESSOR", "RADIOLOGIST". \n RSEVAL is expected for oncology response criteria. It can be left null when the investigator provides the complete set of data in the domain. However, the column should contain no null values when data from one or more independent assessors is included, meaning that the rows attributed to the investigator should contain a value of "INVESTIGATOR".

RS.RSEVALID.label: Evaluator Identifier
RS.RSEVALID.description: Used to distinguish multiple evaluators with the same role recorded in RSEVAL. Examples: "RADIOLOGIST1", "RADIOLOGIST2". See assumptions in Section 6.3.9.3.1, Disease Response Use Case.

RS.RSACPTFL.label: Accepted Record Flag
RS.RSACPTFL.description: In cases where more than 1 independent assessor (e.g., "RADIOLOGIST 1", "RADIOLOGIST 2", "ADJUDICATOR") provides an evaluation of response, this flag identifies the record that is considered to be the accepted evaluation.

RS.VISITNUM.label: Visit Number
RS.VISITNUM.description: Clinical encounter number. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

RS.VISIT.label: Visit Name
RS.VISIT.description: Protocol-defined description of a clinical encounter.

RS.VISITDY.label: Planned Study Day of Visit
RS.VISITDY.description: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

RS.TAETORD.label: Planned Order of Element within Arm
RS.TAETORD.description: Number that gives the planned order of the element within the arm for the element in which the assessment was made.

RS.EPOCH.label: Epoch
RS.EPOCH.description: Epoch associated with the date/time at which the assessment was made.

RS.RSDTC.label: Date/Time of Assessment
RS.RSDTC.description: Collection date and time of the assessment represented in ISO 8601 character format.

RS.RSDY.label: Study Day of Assessment
RS.RSDY.description: Study day of the assessment, measured as integer days. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics.

RS.RSTPT.label: Planned Time Point Name
RS.RSTPT.description: Text description of time when a measurement or observation should be taken as defined in the protocol. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point, such as time of last dose. See RSTPTNUM and RSTPTREF.

RS.RSTPTNUM.label: Planned Time Point Number
RS.RSTPTNUM.description: Numeric version of planned time point used in sorting.

RS.RSELTM.label: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
RS.RSELTM.description: Planned elapsed time in ISO 8601 character format relative to a planned fixed reference (RSTPTREF; e.g., "PREVIOUS DOSE", "PREVIOUS MEAL"). This variable is useful where there are repetitive measures. Not a clock time or a date/time variable, but an interval, represented as ISO duration.

RS.RSTPTREF.label: Time Point Reference
RS.RSTPTREF.description: Description of the fixed reference point referred to by RSELTM, RSTPTNUM, and RSTPT. Examples: "PREVIOUS DOSE", "PREVIOUS MEAL".

RS.RSRFTDTC.label: Date/Time of Reference Time Point
RS.RSRFTDTC.description: Date/time for a fixed reference time point defined by RSTPTREF in ISO 8601 character format.

RS.RSEVLINT.label: Evaluation Interval
RS.RSEVLINT.description: Duration of interval associated with an observation such as a finding RSTESTCD, represented in ISO 8601 character format. Example: "-P2M" to represent a period of the past 2 months as the evaluation interval.

RS.RSEVINTX.label: Evaluation Interval Text
RS.RSEVINTX.description: Evaluation interval associated with an observation, where the interval is not able to be represented in ISO 8601 format. Examples: "LIFETIME", "LAST NIGHT", "RECENTLY", "OVER THE LAST FEW WEEKS".

RS.RSSTRTPT.label: Start Relative to Reference Time Point
RS.RSSTRTPT.description: Identifies the start of the observation as being before or after the sponsor-defined reference time point defined by variable RSSTTPT. \n Not all values of the codelist are allowable for this variable. See Section 4.4.7, Use of Relative Timing Variables.

RS.RSSTTPT.label: Start Reference Time Point
RS.RSSTTPT.description: Description or date/time in ISO 8601 character format of the sponsor-defined reference point referred to by RSSTRTPT. Examples: "2003-12-15", "VISIT 1".

RS.RSENRTPT.label: End Relative to Reference Time Point
RS.RSENRTPT.description: Identifies the end of the observation as being before or after the sponsor-defined reference time point defined by variable RSENTPT. \n Not all values of the codelist are allowable for this variable. See Section 4.4.7, Use of Relative Timing Variables.

RS.RSENTPT.label: End Reference Time Point
RS.RSENTPT.description: Description or date/time in ISO 8601 character format of the sponsor-defined reference point referred to by RSENRTPT. Examples: "2003-12-25", "VISIT 2".

SC.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
SC.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

SC.SCSEQ.label: Sequence Number
SC.SCSEQ.description: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

SC.SCGRPID.label: Group ID
SC.SCGRPID.description: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

SC.SCSPID.label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
SC.SCSPID.description: Sponsor-defined reference number. May be preprinted on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database.

SC.SCTESTCD.label: Subject Characteristic Short Name
SC.SCTESTCD.description: Short name of the measurement, test, or examination described in SCTEST. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in SCTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST" is not valid). SCTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: "MARISTAT", "NATORIG".

SC.SCTEST.label: Subject Characteristic
SC.SCTEST.description: Verbatim name of the test or examination used to obtain the measurement or finding. The value in SCTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: "Marital Status", "National Origin".

SC.SCCAT.label: Category for Subject Characteristic
SC.SCCAT.description: Used to define a category of related records.

SC.SCSCAT.label: Subcategory for Subject Characteristic
SC.SCSCAT.description: A further categorization of the subject characteristic.

SC.SCORRES.label: Result or Finding in Original Units
SC.SCORRES.description: Result of the subject characteristic as originally received or collected.

SC.SCORRESU.label: Original Units
SC.SCORRESU.description: Original unit in which the data were collected. The unit for SCORRES.

SC.SCSTRESC.label: Character Result/Finding in Std Format
SC.SCSTRESC.description: Contains the result value for all findings copied or derived from SCORRES, in a standard format or standard units. SCSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in SCSTRESN. For example, if a test has results "NONE", "NEG", and "NEGATIVE" in SCORRES, and these results effectively have the same meaning, they could be represented in standard format in SCSTRESC as "NEGATIVE".

SC.SCSTRESN.label: Numeric Result/Finding in Standard Units
SC.SCSTRESN.description: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from SCSTRESC. SCSTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

SC.SCSTRESU.label: Standard Units
SC.SCSTRESU.description: Standardized unit used for SCSTRESC or SCSTRESN.

SC.SCSTAT.label: Completion Status
SC.SCSTAT.description: Used to indicate that the measurement was not done. Should be null if a result exists in SCORRES.

SC.SCREASND.label: Reason Not Performed
SC.SCREASND.description: Describes why the observation has no result. Example: "Subject refused". Used in conjunction with SCSTAT when value is "NOT DONE".

SC.VISITNUM.label: Visit Number
SC.VISITNUM.description: Clinical encounter number. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

SC.VISIT.label: Visit Name
SC.VISIT.description: Protocol-defined description of a clinical encounter. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY.

SC.VISITDY.label: Planned Study Day of Visit
SC.VISITDY.description: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

SC.TAETORD.label: Planned Order of Element within Arm
SC.TAETORD.description: Number that gives the planned order of the element within the arm.

SC.EPOCH.label: Epoch
SC.EPOCH.description: Epoch associated with the start date/time at which the assessment was made.

SC.SCDTC.label: Date/Time of Collection
SC.SCDTC.description: Collection date and time of the subject characteristic represented in ISO 8601 character format.

SC.SCDY.label: Study Day of Examination
SC.SCDY.description: Study day of collection, measured as integer days. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics.

SS.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
SS.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

SS.SSSEQ.label: Sequence Number
SS.SSSEQ.description: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

SS.SSGRPID.label: Group ID
SS.SSGRPID.description: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

SS.SSSPID.label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
SS.SSSPID.description: Sponsor-defined reference number. May be preprinted on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database. Example: Line number from the Procedure or Test page.

SS.SSTESTCD.label: Status Short Name
SS.SSTESTCD.description: Short name of the status assessment described in SSTEST. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in SSTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST" is not valid). SSTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Example: "SURVSTAT".

SS.SSTEST.label: Status Name
SS.SSTEST.description: Verbatim name of the status assessment used to obtain the finding. The value in SSTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Example: "Survival Status".

SS.SSCAT.label: Category for Assessment
SS.SSCAT.description: Used to categorize observations across subjects.

SS.SSORRES.label: Result or Finding Original Result
SS.SSORRES.description: Result of the status assessment finding as originally received or collected.

SS.SSSTRESC.label: Character Result/Finding in Std Format
SS.SSSTRESC.description: Contains the result value for all findings copied or derived from SSORRES, in a standard format.

SS.SSSTAT.label: Completion Status
SS.SSSTAT.description: Used to indicate a status assessment was not done. Should be null if a result exists in SSORRES.

SS.SSREASND.label: Reason Assessment Not Performed
SS.SSREASND.description: Describes why an assessment was not performed. Example: "Subject refused". Used in conjunction with SSSTAT when value is "NOT DONE".

SS.SSEVAL.label: Evaluator
SS.SSEVAL.description: Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Used only for results that are subjective (e.g., assigned by a person or a group). Should be null for records that contain collected or derived data. Examples: "CAREGIVER", "ADJUDICATION COMMITTEE", "FRIEND".

SS.VISITNUM.label: Visit Number
SS.VISITNUM.description: Clinical encounter number. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

SS.VISIT.label: Visit Name
SS.VISIT.description: Protocol-defined description of clinical encounter. May be used in addition to VISITNUM and/or VISITDY.

SS.VISITDY.label: Planned Study Day of Visit
SS.VISITDY.description: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

SS.TAETORD.label: Planned Order of Element within Arm
SS.TAETORD.description: Number that gives the planned order of the element within the arm.

SS.EPOCH.label: Epoch
SS.EPOCH.description: Epoch associated with the start date/time of the subject status assessment.

SS.SSDTC.label: Date/Time of Assessment
SS.SSDTC.description: Date and time of the subject status assessment represented in ISO 8601 character format.

SS.SSDY.label: Study Day of Assessment
SS.SSDY.description: Study day of the subject status assessment, measured as integer days. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics.

TR.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
TR.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

TR.TRSEQ.label: Sequence Number
TR.TRSEQ.description: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness within a dataset for a subject. May be any valid number.

TR.TRGRPID.label: Group ID
TR.TRGRPID.description: Used to link together a block of related records within a subject in a domain.

TR.TRLNKID.label: Link ID
TR.TRLNKID.description: Identifier used to link the assessment result records to the individual tumor/lesion identification record in TU domain.

TR.TRLNKGRP.label: Link Group
TR.TRLNKGRP.description: Used to group and link all of the measurement/assessment records used in the assessment of the response record in the RS domain.

TR.TRTESTCD.label: Tumor/Lesion Assessment Short Name
TR.TRTESTCD.description: Short name of the TEST in TRTEST. TRTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: "TUMSTATE", "DIAMETER", "LESSCIND", "LESRVIND". See assumption 3.

TR.TRTEST.label: Tumor/Lesion Assessment Test Name
TR.TRTEST.description: Verbatim name of the test or examination used to obtain the measurement or finding. The value in TRTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: "Tumor State", "Diameter", "Volume", "Lesion Success Indicator", "Lesion Revascularization Indicator". See assumption 3.

TR.TRORRES.label: Result or Finding in Original Units
TR.TRORRES.description: Result of the tumor/lesion measurement/assessment as originally received or collected.

TR.TRORRESU.label: Original Units
TR.TRORRESU.description: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for TRORRES. Example: "mm".

TR.TRSTRESC.label: Character Result/Finding in Std Format
TR.TRSTRESC.description: Contains the result value for all findings copied or derived from TRORRES, in a standard format or standard units. TRSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in TRSTRESN.

TR.TRSTRESN.label: Numeric Result/Finding in Standard Units
TR.TRSTRESN.description: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from TRSTRESC. TRSTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

TR.TRSTAT.label: Completion Status
TR.TRSTAT.description: Used to indicate a scan/image/physical exam was not performed or a tumor/lesion measurement was not taken. Should be null if a result exists in TRORRES.

TR.TRREASND.label: Reason Not Done
TR.TRREASND.description: Describes why a scan/image/physical exam was not performed or a tumor/lesion measurement was not taken. Examples: "SCAN NOT PERFORMED", "NOT ASSESSABLE: IMAGE OBSCURED TUMOR". Used in conjunction with TRSTAT when value is "NOT DONE".

TR.TRNAM.label: Laboratory/Vendor Name
TR.TRNAM.description: The name or identifier of the vendor that performed the tumor/lesion measurement or assessment. This column can be left null when the investigator provides the complete set of data in the domain.

TR.TRMETHOD.label: Method Used to Identify the Tumor/Lesion
TR.TRMETHOD.description: Method used to measure the tumor/lesion/location of interest. Examples: "MRI", "CT SCAN", "PET SCAN", "Coronary angiography".

TR.TRLOBXFL.label: Last Observation Before Exposure Flag
TR.TRLOBXFL.description: Operationally-derived indicator used to identify the last non-missing value prior to RFXSTDTC. Should be "Y" or null.

TR.TRBLFL.label: Baseline Flag
TR.TRBLFL.description: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. Should be "Y" or null. Note that TRBLFL is retained for backward compatibility. The authoritative baseline flag for statistical analysis is in an ADaM dataset.

TR.TREVAL.label: Evaluator
TR.TREVAL.description: Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Used only for results that are subjective (e.g., assigned by a person or a group). Examples: "ADJUDICATION COMMITTEE", "INDEPENDENT ASSESSOR".

TR.TREVALID.label: Evaluator Identifier
TR.TREVALID.description: Used to distinguish multiple evaluators with the same role recorded in TREVAL. Examples: "RADIOLOGIST1", "RADIOLOGIST2". See assumption 6.

TR.TRACPTFL.label: Accepted Record Flag
TR.TRACPTFL.description: In cases where more than 1 independent assessor (e.g., "RADIOLOGIST 1", "RADIOLOGIST 2", "ADJUDICATION COMMITTEE") provide independent assessments at the same time point, this flag identifies the record that is considered to be the accepted assessment.

TR.VISITNUM.label: Visit Number
TR.VISITNUM.description: Clinical encounter number. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

TR.VISIT.label: Visit Name
TR.VISIT.description: Protocol-defined description of a clinical encounter.

TR.VISITDY.label: Planned Study Day of Visit
TR.VISITDY.description: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics.

TR.TAETORD.label: Planned Order of Element within Arm
TR.TAETORD.description: Epoch associated with the date/time at which the assessment was made.

TR.EPOCH.label: Epoch
TR.EPOCH.description: Epoch associated with the element in the planned sequence of elements for the arm to which the subject was assigned.

TR.TRDTC.label: Date/Time of Tumor/Lesion Measurement
TR.TRDTC.description: The date of the scan/image/physical exam. TRDTC does not represent the date that the image was read to identify tumors/lesions. TRDTC also does not represent the VISIT date.

TR.TRDY.label: Study Day of Tumor/Lesion Measurement
TR.TRDY.description: Study day of the scan/image/physical exam, measured as integer days. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics.

TU.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
TU.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

TU.TUSEQ.label: Sequence Number
TU.TUSEQ.description: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness within a dataset for a subject. May be any valid number.

TU.TUGRPID.label: Group ID
TU.TUGRPID.description: Used to link together a block of related records within a subject in a domain. Can be used to group split or merged tumors/lesions which have been identified.

TU.TUREFID.label: Reference ID
TU.TUREFID.description: Internal or external identifier (e.g., medical image ID number).

TU.TULNKID.label: Link ID
TU.TULNKID.description: Identifier used to link identified tumor/lesion/location of interest to the assessment results (in TR domain) over the course of the study.

TU.TULNKGRP.label: Link Group ID
TU.TULNKGRP.description: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This will usually be a many-to-one relationship.

TU.TUTESTCD.label: Tumor/Lesion ID Short Name
TU.TUTESTCD.description: Short name of the TEST in TUTEST. TUTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters nor can start with a number. TUTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Example: "TUMIDENT". See assumption 3.

TU.TUTEST.label: Tumor/Lesion ID Test Name
TU.TUTEST.description: Verbatim name of the test for the tumor/lesion identification. The value in TUTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Example: "Tumor identification". See assumption 3.

TU.TUORRES.label: Tumor/Lesion ID Result
TU.TUORRES.description: Result of the tumor/lesion identification. The result of tumor/lesion identification is a classification of the identified tumor/lesion. Example: When TUTESTCD = "TUMIDENT", values of TUORRES might be "TARGET", "NON-TARGET", "NEW", or "BENIGN ABNORMALITY".

TU.TUSTRESC.label: Tumor/Lesion ID Result Std. Format
TU.TUSTRESC.description: Contains the result value for all findings copied or derived from TUORRES in a standard format.

TU.TUNAM.label: Laboratory/Vendor Name
TU.TUNAM.description: The name or identifier of the vendor that performed the tumor/lesion Identification. This column can be left null when the investigator provides the complete set of data in the domain.

TU.TULOC.label: Location of the Tumor/Lesion
TU.TULOC.description: Used to specify the anatomical location of the identified tumor/lesion (e.g., "LIVER"). \n Note: When anatomical location is broken down and collected as distinct pieces of data that when combined provide the overall location information (e.g., laterality/directionality/distribution), then additional anatomical location qualifiers should be used. See assumption 3.

TU.TULAT.label: Laterality
TU.TULAT.description: Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing laterality (e.g., "LEFT", "RIGHT", "BILATERAL").

TU.TUDIR.label: Directionality
TU.TUDIR.description: Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing directionality (e.g., "UPPER", "INTERIOR").

TU.TUPORTOT.label: Portion or Totality
TU.TUPORTOT.description: Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing the distribution, which means arrangement of, or apportioning of. Examples: "ENTIRE", "SINGLE", "SEGMENT", "MULTIPLE".

TU.TUMETHOD.label: Method of Identification
TU.TUMETHOD.description: Method used to identify the tumor/lesion. Examples: "MRI", "CT SCAN".

TU.TULOBXFL.label: Last Observation Before Exposure Flag
TU.TULOBXFL.description: Operationally derived indicator used to identify the last non-missing value prior to RFXSTDTC. Should be "Y" or null.

TU.TUBLFL.label: Baseline Flag
TU.TUBLFL.description: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. Should be "Y" or null. Note that TUBLFL is retained for backward compatibility. The authoritative baseline flag for statistical analysis is in an ADaM dataset.

TU.TUEVAL.label: Evaluator
TU.TUEVAL.description: Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Examples: "ADJUDICATION COMMITTEE", "INDEPENDENT ASSESSOR". \n This column can be left null when the investigator provides the complete set of data in the domain. However, the column should contain no null values when data from 1 or more independent assessors is included. For example, the rows attributed to the investigator should contain a value of "INVESTIGATOR".

TU.TUEVALID.label: Evaluator Identifier
TU.TUEVALID.description: Used to distinguish multiple evaluators with the same role recorded in --EVAL. Examples: "RADIOLOGIST1", "RADIOLOGIST2". See assumption 9.

TU.TUACPTFL.label: Accepted Record Flag
TU.TUACPTFL.description: In cases where more than 1 independent assessor (e.g., "RADIOLOGIST 1", "RADIOLOGIST 2", "ADJUDICATION COMMITTEE") provide independent assessments at the same time point, this flag identifies the record that is considered to be the accepted assessment.

TU.VISITNUM.label: Visit Number
TU.VISITNUM.description: Clinical encounter number. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

TU.VISIT.label: Visit Name
TU.VISIT.description: Protocol-defined description of a clinical encounter.

TU.VISITDY.label: Planned Study Day of Visit
TU.VISITDY.description: Planned study day of the visit based upon RFSTDTC in Demographics. Should be an integer.

TU.TAETORD.label: Planned Order of Element within Arm
TU.TAETORD.description: Number that gives the planned order of the element within the arm for the element in which the assessment was made.

TU.EPOCH.label: Epoch
TU.EPOCH.description: Epoch associated with the date/time at which the assessment was made.

TU.TUDTC.label: Date/Time of Tumor/Lesion Identification
TU.TUDTC.description: TUDTC variable represents the date of the scan/image/physical exam. TUDTC does not represent the date that the image was read to identify tumors. TUDTC also does not represent the VISIT date.

TU.TUDY.label: Study Day of Tumor/Lesion Identification
TU.TUDY.description: Study day of the scan/image/physical exam, measured as integer days. Algorithm for calculations must be relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC variable in Demographics.

UR.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
UR.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

UR.URSEQ.label: Sequence Number
UR.URSEQ.description: Sequence number to ensure uniqueness of records within a dataset for a subject. May be any valid number (including decimals) and does not have to start at 1.

UR.URGRPID.label: Group ID
UR.URGRPID.description: Optional group identifier, used to link together a block of related records within a subject in a domain.

UR.URREFID.label: Reference ID
UR.URREFID.description: Optional internal or external identifier (e.g., lab specimen ID, universally unique identifier (UUID) for a medical image).

UR.URSPID.label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
UR.URSPID.description: Sponsor-defined identifier. Example: Preprinted line identifier.

UR.URLNKID.label: Link ID
UR.URLNKID.description: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This may be a one-to-one or a one-to-many relationship.

UR.URLNKGRP.label: Link Group ID
UR.URLNKGRP.description: Identifier used to link related records across domains. This will usually be a many-to-one relationship.

UR.URTESTCD.label: Short Name of Urinary Test
UR.URTESTCD.description: Short character value for URTEST used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical format to a horizontal format. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in URTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST" is not valid). URTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: "COUNT", "LENGTH", "RBLDFLW".

UR.URTEST.label: Name of Urinary Test
UR.URTEST.description: Long name For URTESTCD. Examples: "Count", "Length", "Renal Blood Flow".

UR.URTSTDTL.label: Urinary Test Detail
UR.URTSTDTL.description: Further description of URTESTCD and URTEST.

UR.URCAT.label: Category for Urinary Test
UR.URCAT.description: Used to define a category of topic-variable values.

UR.URSCAT.label: Subcategory for Urinary Test
UR.URSCAT.description: Used to define a further categorization of URCAT values.

UR.URORRES.label: Result or Finding in Original Units
UR.URORRES.description: Result of the measurement or finding as originally received or collected.

UR.URSTRESC.label: Character Result/Finding in Std Format
UR.URSTRESC.description: Contains the result value for all findings copied or derived from URORRES, in a standard format or in standard units. URSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in URSTRESN.

UR.URSTRESN.label: Numeric Result/Finding in Standard Units
UR.URSTRESN.description: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from URSTRESC. URSTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

UR.URSTRESU.label: Standard Units
UR.URSTRESU.description: Standardized units used for URSTRESC and URSTRESN.

UR.URRESCAT.label: Result Category
UR.URRESCAT.description: Used to categorize the result of a finding.

UR.URSTAT.label: Completion Status
UR.URSTAT.description: Used to indicate that a question was not asked or a test was not done, or a test was attempted but did not generate a result. Should be null or have a value of "NOT DONE".

UR.URREASND.label: Reason Not Done
UR.URREASND.description: Reason not done. Used in conjunction with URSTAT when value is "NOT DONE".

UR.URLOC.label: Location Used for the Measurement
UR.URLOC.description: Anatomical location of the subject relevant to the collection of the measurement.

UR.URLAT.label: Laterality
UR.URLAT.description: Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing laterality. Examples: "RIGHT", "LEFT", "BILATERAL".

UR.URDIR.label: Directionality
UR.URDIR.description: Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing directionality. Examples: "ANTERIOR", "LOWER", "PROXIMAL".

UR.URMETHOD.label: Method of Test or Examination
UR.URMETHOD.description: Method of the test or examination.

UR.URLOBXFL.label: Last Observation Before Exposure Flag
UR.URLOBXFL.description: Operationally derived indicator used to identify the last non-missing value prior to RFXSTDTC. The value should be "Y" or null.

UR.URBLFL.label: Baseline Flag
UR.URBLFL.description: A baseline defined by the sponsor The value should be "Y" or null. Note that URBLFL is retained for backward compatibility. The authoritative baseline flag for statistical analysis is in an ADaM dataset.

UR.URDRVFL.label: Derived Flag
UR.URDRVFL.description: Used to indicate a derived record (e.g., a record that represents the average of other records such as a computed baseline). Should be "Y" or null.

UR.UREVAL.label: Evaluator
UR.UREVAL.description: Role of the person who provided the evaluation. Used only for results that are subjective (e.g., assigned by a person or a group). Examples: "ADJUDICATION COMMITTEE", "INDEPENDENT ASSESSOR", "RADIOLOGIST".

UR.UREVALID.label: Evaluator Identifier
UR.UREVALID.description: Used to distinguish multiple evaluators with the same role recorded in UREVAL. Examples: "RADIOLOGIST1", "RADIOLOGIST2".

UR.VISITNUM.label: Visit Number
UR.VISITNUM.description: Clinical encounter number. Numeric version of VISIT, used for sorting.

UR.VISIT.label: Visit Name
UR.VISIT.description: Protocol-defined description of a clinical encounter.

UR.VISITDY.label: Planned Study Day of Visit
UR.VISITDY.description: Planned study day of VISIT. Should be an integer.

UR.TAETORD.label: Planned Order of Element within Arm
UR.TAETORD.description: Number that gives the planned order of the element within the arm for the element in which the observation was made.

UR.EPOCH.label: Epoch
UR.EPOCH.description: Epoch associated with the date/time at which the observation was made.

UR.URDTC.label: Date/Time of Collection
UR.URDTC.description: Collection date and time of an observation.

UR.URDY.label: Study Day of Visit/Collection/Exam
UR.URDY.description: Actual study day of visit/collection/exam expressed in integer days relative to the sponsor-defined RFSTDTC in Demographics.

UR.URTPT.label: Planned Time Point Name
UR.URTPT.description: Text description of time when a measurement or observation should be taken as defined in the protocol. This may be represented as an elapsed time relative to a fixed reference point (e.g., time of last dose). See URTPTNUM and URTPTREF.

UR.URTPTNUM.label: Planned Time Point Number
UR.URTPTNUM.description: Numeric version of planned time point used in sorting.

UR.URELTM.label: Planned Elapsed Time from Time Point Ref
UR.URELTM.description: Planned elapsed time relative to a planned fixed reference (URTPTREF; e.g., "PREVIOUS DOSE", "PREVIOUS MEAL"). This variable is useful where there are repetitive measures. Not a clock time or a date/time variable, but an interval, represented as ISO duration.

UR.URTPTREF.label: Time Point Reference
UR.URTPTREF.description: Description of the fixed reference point referred to by URELTM, URTPTNUM, and URTPT. Examples: "PREVIOUS DOSE", "PREVIOUS MEAL".

UR.URRFTDTC.label: Date/Time of Reference Time Point
UR.URRFTDTC.description: Date/time for a fixed reference time point defined by URTPTREF.

VS.USUBJID.label: Unique Subject Identifier
VS.USUBJID.description: Identifier used to uniquely identify a subject across all studies for all applications or submissions involving the product.

VS.VSSEQ.label: Sequence Number
VS.VSSEQ.description: Sequence number given to ensure uniqueness of subject records within a domain. May be any valid number.

VS.VSGRPID.label: Group ID
VS.VSGRPID.description: Used to tie together a block of related records in a single domain for a subject.

VS.VSSPID.label: Sponsor-Defined Identifier
VS.VSSPID.description: Sponsor-defined reference number. May be preprinted on the CRF as an explicit line identifier or defined in the sponsor's operational database.

VS.VSTESTCD.label: Vital Signs Test Short Name
VS.VSTESTCD.description: Short name of the measurement, test, or examination described in VSTEST. It can be used as a column name when converting a dataset from a vertical to a horizontal format. The value in VSTESTCD cannot be longer than 8 characters, nor can it start with a number (e.g., "1TEST" is not valid). VSTESTCD cannot contain characters other than letters, numbers, or underscores. Examples: "SYSBP", "DIABP", "BMI".

VS.VSTEST.label: Vital Signs Test Name
VS.VSTEST.description: Verbatim name of the test or examination used to obtain the measurement or finding. The value in VSTEST cannot be longer than 40 characters. Examples: "Systolic Blood Pressure", "Diastolic Blood Pressure", "Body Mass Index".

VS.VSCAT.label: Category for Vital Signs
VS.VSCAT.description: Used to define a category of related records.

VS.VSSCAT.label: Subcategory for Vital Signs
VS.VSSCAT.description: A further categorization of a measurement or examination.

VS.VSPOS.label: Vital Signs Position of Subject
VS.VSPOS.description: Position of the subject during a measurement or examination. Examples: "SUPINE", "STANDING", "SITTING".

VS.VSORRES.label: Result or Finding in Original Units
VS.VSORRES.description: Result of the vital signs measurement as originally received or collected.

VS.VSORRESU.label: Original Units
VS.VSORRESU.description: Original units in which the data were collected. The unit for VSORRES. Examples: "in", "LB", "beats/min".

VS.VSSTRESC.label: Character Result/Finding in Std Format
VS.VSSTRESC.description: Contains the result value for all findings, copied or derived from VSORRES in a standard format or standard units. VSSTRESC should store all results or findings in character format; if results are numeric, they should also be stored in numeric format in VSSTRESN. For example, if a test has results "NONE", "NEG", and "NEGATIVE" in VSORRES, and these results effectively have the same meaning, they could be represented in standard format in VSSTRESC as "NEGATIVE".

VS.VSSTRESN.label: Numeric Result/Finding in Standard Units
VS.VSSTRESN.description: Used for continuous or numeric results or findings in standard format; copied in numeric format from VSSTRESC. VSSTRESN should store all numeric test results or findings.

VS.VSSTRESU.label: Standard Units
VS.VSSTRESU.description: Standardized unit used for VSSTRESC and VSSTRESN.

VS.VSSTAT.label: Completion Status
VS.VSSTAT.description: Used to indicate that a vital sign measurement was not done. Should be null if a result exists in VSORRES.

VS.VSREASND.label: Reason Not Performed
VS.VSREASND.description: Describes why a measurement or test was not performed. Examples: "BROKEN EQUIPMENT", "SUBJECT REFUSED". Used in conjunction with VSSTAT when value is "NOT DONE".

VS.VSLOC.label: Location of Vital Signs Measurement
VS.VSLOC.description: Location relevant to the collection of vital signs measurement. Example: "ARM" for blood pressure.

VS.VSLAT.label: Laterality
VS.VSLAT.description: Qualifier for anatomical location or specimen further detailing laterality. Examples: "RIGHT", "LEFT", "BILATERAL".

VS.VSLOBXFL.label: Last Observation Before Exposure Flag
VS.VSLOBXFL.description: Operationally derived indicator used to identify the last non-missing value prior to RFXSTDTC. Should be "Y" or null.

VS.VSBLFL.label: Baseline Flag
VS.VSBLFL.description: Indicator used to identify a baseline value. Should be "Y" or null. Note that VSBLFL is retained for backward compatibility. The authoritative baseline for statistical analysis is in an ADaM dataset.

VS.VSDRVFL.label: Derived Flag
VS.VSDRVFL.description: Used to indicate a derived record. The value should be "Y" or null. Records that represent the average of other records or that do not come from the CRF are examples of records that would be derived for the submission datasets.
